 || February 18 || Indianapolis || 78\u201375 || [[Ed Macauley]] (24) || 32\u201323\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"bbffbb\"\n| 56 || February 21 || New York || 87\u201385 (OT) || [[Ed Macauley]] (36) || 33\u201323\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"bbffbb\"\n| 57 || February 22 || vs Baltimore || 72\u201369 || [[Ed Macauley]] (17) || 34\u201323\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"edbebf\"\n| 58 || February 24 || at Baltimore || 75\u201384 || [[Sidney Hertzberg]] (18) || 34\u201324\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"bbffbb\"\n| 59 || February 25 || Philadelphia || 93\u201383 || [[Bob Cousy]] (39) || 35\u201324\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"edbebf\"\n| 60 || March 1 || New York || 78\u201384 || [[Ed Macauley]] (24) || 35\u201325\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"bbffbb\"\n| 61 || March 3 || at Baltimore || 95\u201387 || [[Ed Macauley]] (21) || 36\u201325\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"bbffbb\"\n| 62 || March 4 || Minneapolis || 92\u201386 || [[Bob Cousy]] (19) || 37\u201325\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"edbebf\"\n| 63 || March 6 || at Indianapolis || 73\u201375 || [[Bob Cousy]] (19) || 37\u201326\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"bbffbb\"\n| 64 || March 7 || at Fort Wayne || 99\u201395 || [[Ed Macauley]] (26) || 38\u201326\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"edbebf\"\n| 65 || March 11 || at Minneapolis || 96\u201398 (2OT) || [[Ed Macauley]] (26) || 38\u201327\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"edbebf\"\n| 66 || March 13 || Rochester || 107\u2013111 (2OT) || [[Bob Cousy]] (32) || 38\u201328\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"bbffbb\"\n| 67 || March 16 || Fort Wayne || 90\u201388 || [[Ed Macauley]] (27) || 39\u201328\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"edbebf\"\n| 68 || March 17 || at Rochester || 89\u2013114 || [[Ed Macauley]] (16) || 39\u201329\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"edbebf\"\n| 69 || March 18 || at Syracuse || 89\u201397 || [[Bob Cousy]] (28) || 39\u201330\n|}\n\n==Playoffs==\n\n===East Division Semifinals===\n\n(2) [[Boston Celtics]] vs. (3) '''[[New York Knicks]]''': ''Knicks win series 2\u20130''\n*'''Game 1''' @ Boston: '''New York 83''', Boston 69\n*'''Game 2''' @ New York: '''New York 92''', Boston 78\n\n==Player statistics==\n\n===Season===\n\n===Playoffs===\n\n==Awards and records==\n*[[Ed Macauley]], [[All-NBA First Team]]\n\n==Transactions==\n\n{{Empty section|date=February 2013}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[1950\u201351 NBA season]]\n\n{{1950\u201351 NBA season by team}}\n{{Boston Celtics}}\n{{Boston Celtics seasons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1950-51 Boston Celtics Season}}\n[[Category:Boston Celtics seasons]]\n[[Category:1950\u201351 NBA season by team|Boston Celtics seasons]]\n[[Category:1950 in sports in Massachusetts|Boston]]\n[[Category:1951 in sports in Massachusetts|Boston]]\n", "name_user": "ToddC4176", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRoster", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1950%E2%80%9351_Boston_Celtics_season"}
{"title_page": "May 1915", "text_new": "{{short description|Month of 1915}}\n{{Events by month|1915}}\n{{calendar|year=1915|month=May}}\n[[File:Bundesarchiv DVM 10 Bild-23-61-17, Untergang der \"Lusitania\".jpg|thumb|right|350px|Painting depicting the [[Sinking of the RMS Lusitania|sinking of the RMS ''Lusitania'']] by German U-boat [[SM U-20 (Germany)|SM ''U-20'']].]]\n[[File:Van Defenders.jpg|thumb|350px|right|Armenian civilians holding a defense line against Ottoman forces in the Armenian walled city of [[Defense of Van (1915)|Van]] in May 1915.]]\n\nThe following events occurred in '''May 1915''':\n\n== [[May 1]], 1915 (Saturday) ==\n[[File:01915 Schwere deutsche Morser.jpg|right|300px|thumb|A German artillery piece used for bombardment during the [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] on the [[Eastern Front (World War I)|Eastern Front]].]]\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013 Combined German and Austro-Hungarian forces under command of General [[August von Mackensen]] [[Battle of Dunajetz|bombarded and attacked]] trenches held by the [[3rd Army (Russian Empire)|Russian Third Army]] along the [[Dunajec]] river in [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]] (now [[Poland]]), expending 70,000 shells over four hours before troops assaulted the trenches.<ref>{{cite book| last1=Stone| first1=Norman| title=The Eastern Front 1914\u20131917| url=https://archive.org/details/easternfront191400norm| url-access=registration| date=1998| publisher=Penguin| location=London| origyear=1971<!--|page=[https://archive.org/details/easternfront191400norm/page/104 104]-->| page=135}}</ref><ref>Tucker, Spencer, and Priscilla Roberts, eds. World War I: The Definitive Encyclopedia and Document Collection. Vol. 2. N.p.: ABC-CLIO, 2014. Print. {{ISBN|978-1851099641}}. {{OCLC|864676778}}, p. 512</ref>\n* [[Battle of Hill 60 (Western Front)|Battle of Hill 60]] \u2013 German forces launched a series of gas attacks to retake the [[Hill 60 (Ypres)|strategic hill]] on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] from the British.<ref>{{cite book |series=History of the Great War Based on Official Documents by Direction of the Historical Section of the Committee of Imperial Defence |title=Military Operations France and Belgium, 1915: Winter 1914\u20131915: Battle of Neuve Chapelle: Battles of Ypres |volume=I |last1=Edmonds |first1=J. E. |last2=Wynne |first2=G. C. |authorlink=|year=1995 |orig-year=1927 |publisher=Macmillan |location=London | edition=Imperial War Museum and Battery Press |isbn=0-89839-218-7 |pages=288\u201389}}</ref>\n* [[Eski Hissarlik|Battle of Eski Hissarlik]] \u2013 Ottoman forces counter-attacked during the night in an attempt to push [[Allies of World War I|Allied]] forces off their beachhead at Cape Helles during the [[Gallipoli campaign]]. However, Allied defenses were strong and well-prepared for night attacks and the Ottoman forces were repelled.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Duffy|first1=Michael|title=Battles \u2013 The Turkish Counter-attack at Eski Hissarlik, 1915|url=http://www.firstworldwar.com/battles/eskihissarlik.htm|website=First World War|publisher=Michael Duffy|accessdate=21 January 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Zaian War]] \u2013 French colonial forces crossed the [[Oum Er-Rbia River|Rbia River]] north of [[Khenifra]], [[Morocco]] to cut of food supplies reserved for the rebelling [[Zayanes]]. During the campaign, a French convoy was attacked by 5,000 tribesmen, but were repulsed with 300 killed and 400 wounded over a two-day battle. The battle lead to six months of relative calm in the region.<ref>{{Citation  | last = Hoisington| first = William A| title = Lyautey and the French Conquest of Morocco| place = New York| publisher = Macmillan (St Martin's Press)| year = 1995| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=iBn1PHEGGokC| doi =   | id =   | isbn = 978-0-312-12529-5 | page=82}}</ref>\n* French submarine {{ship|French submarine|Joule||2}} struck a mine and sank in the [[Dardanelles]] with the loss of all 31 of her crew.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naval-history.net/WW1NavyFrench.htm |title=French Navy |publisher=Naval History |accessdate=21 February 2013}}</ref>\n* British [[destroyer]] {{HMS|Recruit|1896|6}} was torpedoed and sunk in the [[North Sea]] by German submarine {{SMU|UB-6||6}} with the loss of 34 of her crew.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/wwi/ships_hit/7266.html |title=Recruit |publisher=Uboat.net |accessdate=28 October 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Royal Navy]] destroyers protecting naval trawlers [[Battle off Noordhinder Bank|fought]] off German torpedo boats at [[Noordhinder Bank]] in south part of the [[North Sea]], resulting in both torpedo boats being sunk with 13 German sailors killed and another 46 captured. Sixteen British sailors were lost in the attack.<ref>{{cite book |last=Karau |first=Mark |authorlink= |title=Wielding the Dagger |publisher=Praeger |year=2003|location=Westport, CT |isbn=0-313-32475-1|pages=48\u201355}}</ref>\n* British ocean liner [[RMS Lusitania|RMS ''Lusitania'']] departed [[Chelsea Piers#Pier 54|Pier 54]] in [[New York City]] on a return voyage back to [[Liverpool]] with 1,959 passengers and crew on board.<ref>Preston, D. (2003) ''Wilful Murder. The Sinking of the Lusitania''. London : Black Swan. {{ISBN|978-0552998864}}. pp. 132-33</ref>\n* The British [[War Office]] issued instructions specifying the aircraft and armament [[Royal Flying Corps]] [[Squadron (aviation)|squadrons]] were to have ready for defense of [[Great Britain]] against German airships, including having aircraft ready for immediate takeoff at all times, with a specific mix of weapons including bombs, grenades, and incendiary darts.<ref>Whitehouse, Arch, ''The Zeppelin Fighters'', New York: Ace Books, 1966, no ISBN, pp. 72-73.</ref>\n* American [[tanker (ship)|tanker]] ''[[Gulflight]]'' was torpedoed and damaged in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] {{convert|20|nmi|km}} west of the [[Isles of Scilly]] by German submarine {{SMU|U-30|Germany|6}} with the loss of three crew, becoming the first American ship to be attacked in [[World War I]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F70C13F83E5D16738DDDAB0994DD405B858DF1D3 |title=Gulflight attack as officially told  |accessdate= 20 Jan 2011 |newspaper=New York Times |date= 15 May 1915 |page=4}}</ref>\n* [[Ambrose Heal]] and others founded the [[Design and Industries Association]] in [[London]].<ref>[http://www.dia.org.uk/page/AboutUs/Nothing_Need_be_Ugly DIA website]</ref>\n* The first part of the [[Mandra\u2013Bhaun Railway]] opened in [[British Raj|British India]] (now [[Pakistan]]), connecting [[Mandra Junction railway station|Mandra]] with [[Bhaun]].<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/BombayBarodaAndCentralIndiaRailwaySystem/Bombay_Baroda_And_Central_India_Railway_System#page/n124/mode/2up  \" Administration Report on the Railways in India \u2013 corrected up to 31st March 1918\"; Superintendent of Government  Printing,  Calcutta;  page 116]; Retrieved 26 Jan 2016</ref>\n* Rail stations [[Bradley and Moxley railway station|Bradley and Moxley]] and [[Milton Road Halt railway station|Milton Road]] were closed as part of wartime measures in [[England]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Butt |first=R.V.J. |title=The Directory of Railway Stations |year=1995 |publisher=Patrick Stephens Ltd |location=Yeovil |isbn=1-85260-508-1 |id=R508 |page=42}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | first = R. W.| last = Kidner| authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 1985| month = | title = Southern Railway Halts. Survey and Gazetteer| chapter = | editor = | others = | edition = | pages = | publisher = The Oakwood Press| location = Headington, Oxford| isbn = 0-85361-321-4| page = 52 }}</ref>\n* The [[Barry Railway Company]] opened a [[Llandow Halt railway station|rail station]] in [[Llandow]], [[Wales]] to serve the [[South Wales]] line. It closed in 1964.<ref>Chapman, Colin (1998) ''The Vale of Glamorgan Railway'' The Oakwood Press, p. 61</ref> \n* Japanese chemical manufacturer [[Denka (company)|Denka]] was established in [[Tokyo]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Corporate Overview |url=https://www.denka.co.jp/eng/corporate/overview/ |website=Denka |accessdate=2 September 2019}}</ref>\n* Candy store chain [[Haigh's Chocolates]] was established when Alfred E. Haigh opened a chocolate store in [[Adelaide]], [[Australia]]. The shop became a chaing starting in the 1950s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.haighschocolates.com.au/about-us/our-history/ |title=Our company history |publisher=Haigh's Chocolates |accessdate=2007-09-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070829084027/http://haighschocolates.com.au/our_company/history.html |archivedate=2007-08-29 }}</ref>\n* The sports club [[SK Strong|Strong]] was established in [[Oslo]] for hockey, and became one of the founding members of [[GET-ligaen]], the premier Norwegian hockey league. It merged with two other clubs in 1952 to become [[Gr\u00fcner IL|Gr\u00fcner]].<ref>[http://www.grunerhockey.no/?page_id=77 Ishockey inntar Gr\u00fcnerl\u00f8kka]</ref>\n* The [[association football]] club [[SC Silvolde|Silvolde]] was established through a merger of two separate clubs in [[Silvolde]], [[Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The club history part 1 | url=https://www.sportclubsilvolde.nl/algemeen/historie?id=84 |website=Sports Club Silvolde |accessdate=2 September 2019 |language=Dutch}}</ref>\n* [[Frances Cornford]]'s ''Spring Morning'', the first modern book illustrated with [[wood engraving]]s by the poet's cousin [[Gwen Raverat]], was published by The [[Poetry Bookshop]] in [[London]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Balston|first=Thomas|title=Wood-engraving in Modern English Books|location=London|publisher=National Book League|year=1949}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Michael Dillon]], British physician, first [[trans man]] to undergo [[phalloplasty]] (d. [[1962]]); [[Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i]], Vietnamese army officer, first [[General Staff of the Vietnam People's Army]], in [[Ti\u1ec1n H\u1ea3i District]], [[Vietnam]] (d. [[1986]]); [[Archie Williams]], American runner, gold medalist at the [[1936 Summer Olympics]], in [[Oakland, California]] (d. [[1993]])\n\n== [[May 2]], 1915 (Sunday) ==\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013 [[Grand Duke Nicholas Nikolaevich of Russia (1856\u20131929)|Grand Duke Nicholas Nicholaevitch]], supreme commander of the Russian Empire's armed forces, ordered fresh divisions to the Russian line as the [[Central Powers]] crossed the [[Wis\u0142oka|Wis\u0142oka River]] using a captured bridge.<ref>Richard L. DiNardo, Breakthrough: The Gorlice-Tarnow Campaign, 1915 (2010), p. 62, 75</ref>\n* The [[New Zealand and Australian Division]] launched an [[Battle for Baby 700|attack]] on a strategic hill in [[Gallipoli]] held by the [[19th Infantry Division (Ottoman Empire)|19th Infantry Division]] of the [[Military of the Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Army]], with support by the [[1st Royal Naval Brigade]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Bean|first=Charles|authorlink=Charles Bean|title=The Story of ANZAC from the Outbreak of War to the End of the First Phase of the Gallipoli Campaign, May 4, 1915 |url=https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/C1416845 |series=Official History of Australia in the War of 1914\u20131918 |volume=Volume I|edition=11th|year=1941a|publisher=Angus & Robertson|location=Sydney|oclc=220878987|pages=587\u2013594}}</ref>\n* Norwegian cargo ship {{SS|America|1914|2}} was sunk in the [[North Sea]] off [[Bergen]], [[Norway]] by German submarine {{SMU|U-41|Germany|6}}. Her 39 crew were rescued by another Norwegian ship.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/wwi/ships_hit/246.html |title=America |publisher=Uboat.net |accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n* The [[1915 Copa del Rey Final|Copa Del Rey Final]] was played in front of 5,000 spectators at [[Estadio de Amute]] in [[Hondarribia]], [[Spain]]. [[Athletic Bilbao]] beat [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]] 5-0 to win their 6th [[Copa del Rey]] (Spanish Cup).<ref>{{cite web|title=Athletic Club \u2013 Honours|url=http://www.athletic-club.eus/en/honours.html|website=Athletic Club|publisher=Athletic Club|accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref>\n* '''Died:''' [[Clara Immerwahr]], German chemist and women's rights activist, first woman to be awarded a doctorate in chemistry, wife to [[Fritz Haber]] (b. [[1870]]); [[David Dalhoff Neal]], American artist, best known for his portraits of historic figures including ''[[Oliver Cromwell]] of Ely Visits Mr. [[John Milton]]'' (b. [[1838]])\n\n== [[May 3]], 1915 (Monday) ==\n[[File:John McCrae in uniform circa 1914.jpg|right|200px|thumb|Canadian army officer [[John McCrae]], author of \"[[In Flanders Fields]]\".]]\n* Italy officially revoked the [[Triple Alliance (1914)|Triple Alliance]]. In the following days, Italian statesman [[Giovanni Giolitti]] led the neutralist majority of the Italian Parliament in opposing a war declaration, while nationalist crowds demonstrated in public areas for entering the war.<ref>Hamilton, Richard F; Herwig, Holger H. Decisions for War, 1914\u20131917. pp. 194-198</ref>\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013 Russian forces retreated from [[Gorlice]] as German and Austro-Hungarian troops crossed the [[Dunajec]] River north of [[Krak\u00f3w]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Austro-German forces drive Russians out of the Carpathians|url=http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/austro-german-forces-drive-russians-out-of-the-carpathians|website=History Channel|publisher=A+E Networks|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref>\n* Combined Australian, New Zealand and British forces did not sufficient reinforcements to [[Battle for Baby 700|hold onto a strategic hill]] in [[Gallipoli]], resulting in their withdraw at a cost of close to 1,000 casualties.<ref>Bean 1941a, p. 597</ref>\n* The [[RAF Northolt]] station began operating in [[South Ruislip]], [[London]], [[England]]. It remains the longest, continuously used air station by the [[Royal Air Force]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bristow|first1=Mark|title=A History of Royal Air Force Northolt|date=2005|publisher=No. 1 AIDU|location=RAF Northolt|pages=13\u201316}}</ref>\n* The first [[Zeppelin P Class]] airship of the [[German Army (German Empire)|Imperial German Army]] - the ''L38'' - took flight for raids on [[England]].<ref>Robinson, Douglas H., ''Giants in the Sky'' Henley-on Thames: Foulis, 1973 {{ISBN|0-85429-145-8}}, p, 103</ref>\n* While on patrol over the [[North Sea]], a German Navy Zeppelin encountered and attacked four British [[submarine]]s on the surface, however, all subs were able to escape by diving.<ref>Whitehouse 1966, pp. 97-98.</ref>\n* The [[101st Infantry Division (German Empire)|101st]] and [[103rd Infantry Division (German Empire)|103rd Infantry Divisions]] of the [[Imperial German Army]] were established.<ref>[http://www.1914-18.info/erster-weltkrieg.php?u=201 101. Infanterie-Division (Chronik 1915/1918)]</ref>\n* Swedish [[coastal defence ship]] [[HSwMS Sverige|''Sverige'']] was launched by [[G\u00f6taverken]] in [[Gothenburg]], [[Sweden]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Warship 1992|editor=Gardiner, Robert|publisher=Naval Institute Press|location=London|year=1992|isbn=0-85177-603-5|chapter=The Svierge Class Coastal Defense Ships|pages=80\u201398|last=Harris|first=Daniel G.}}</ref>\n* Canadian medical soldier [[John McCrae]] wrote the poem \"[[In Flanders Fields]]\", after presiding over the funeral of a friend and fellow soldier who died in the [[Second Battle of Ypres]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Prescott|first1=John F.|title=In Flanders Fields: The Story of John McCrae|date=1985|publisher=Boston Mills Press|location=Erin, Ontario|isbn=0-919783-07-4|page=96}}</ref>\n* Home team [[Bethlehem Steel F.C. (1907\u20131930)|Bethlehem Steel]] beat [[Brooklyn Celtic]] 3-1 at the second annual [[U.S. Open Cup]] at Taylor Field, [[Lehigh University]] in [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]] before a crowd of 7,000 spectators.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Litterer |first1=Dave |last2=Goloboy |first2=Jim |title=Final Details 1914\u20131947 \u2013 USA \u2013 List of US Open Cup Finals |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesu/usacuphist.html#det |website=RSSSF |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |accessdate=30 May 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vDj5rMKE?url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesu/usacuphist.html |archivedate=24 December 2010 }}</ref>\n* The borough [[Bradford Woods, Pennsylvania]] was incorporated.<ref>{{cite web| url =http://www.phmc.state.pa.us/bah/dam/counties/pdfs/Allegheny.pdf | title = Allegheny County \u2013 2nd Class | accessdate = 2007-10-08}}</ref>\n*  U.S. steamer ''Undine'' arrived in [[Lewiston, Idaho]] from [[Portland, Oregon]] as part of the inaugural cruise for the newly built [[Celilo Canal]] that connected two points of the [[Columbia River]]. The canal was in operation until 1957 when [[The Dalles Dam]] was completed.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Dana|first=Marshall N.|title=The Celebration of the Open Columbia|journal=The Quarterly of the Oregon Historical Society|date=1 June 1915|volume=16|url=https://archive.org/stream/jstor-20609994/20609994#page/n2/mode/1up|accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Stu Hart]], Canadian wrestler, founder of [[Stampede Wrestling]], patriarch of the [[Hart wrestling family]], in [[Saskatoon]], [[Saskatchewan]] (d. [[2003]])\n\n== [[May 4]], 1915 (Tuesday) ==\n* [[Los Angeles]] held a [[1915 Los Angeles mayoral election|mayoral election]], with [[Charles E. Sebastian]] elected to become the city's [[Mayor of Los Angeles|30th mayor]]. Sebastian received over 28,000 votes, or 39 per cent of the polls.<ref>{{cite web| title=Los Angeles Mayor \u2013 Primary| url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=568427| publisher=Our Campaigns}}</ref>\n\n== [[May 5]], 1915 (Wednesday) ==\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013 The [[3rd Army (Russian Empire)|Russian Third Army]] began to collapse, allowing German forces to break through and capture 140,000 enemy soldiers and 100 guns.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rickard|first1=J.|title=Battle of Gorlice-Tarnow, 2-10 May 1915|url=http://www.historyofwar.org/articles/battles_gorlice_tarnow.html|website=History of War|date=20 August 2007|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Battle of Hill 60 (Western Front)|Battle of Hill 60]] \u2013 British forces held off German gas attacks for four days but a renewed attack on the fifth day resulted in the gas following the front line as opposed to crossing it, allowing more British troops to be overcome. This allowed German infantry of the 30th Division to advance and capture the front line on the lower slope of the [[Hill 60 (Ypres)|hill]].{{sfn|Edmonds|Wynne|1927|p=305}}\n* German submarine ''[[SM U-20 (Germany)|U-20]]'' sunk a British merchant [[schooner]], the ''Earl of Lathom'', off the southern coast of [[Ireland]] after stopping it and ordering the crew off the ship.<ref>{{cite book|last=Molony|first=Senan|title=Lusitania, an Irish Tragedy|year=2004|publisher=Mercier Press|location=Cork|isbn=978-1-85635-452-3|page=8}}</ref>\n* The [[Royal Navy]] issued an uncoded warning to all British commercial ships that German [[U-boat]]s were seen active of the south coast of [[Ireland]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Room 40: British Naval Intelligence, 1914\u20131918 |last=Beesly |first=Patrick |year=1982 |publisher=Hamish Hamilton Ltd |location=Long Acre, London |isbn=0-241-10864-0|page=103}}</ref>\n* The British 125th brigade of the [[42nd (East Lancashire) Infantry Division|42nd Infantry Division]] arrived at [[Gallipoli]] to reinforce [[ANZAC Cove]], allowing [[Australian and New Zealand Army Corps|ANZAC]] forces to prepare for a second assault on the village of [[Second Battle of Krithia|Krithia]] the following day.<ref>{{cite book |last=Broadbent |first= Harvey |year=2005 |title=Gallipoli: The Fatal Shore |publisher=Viking/Penguin |location= Camberwell, Victoria |isbn= 0-670-04085-1|page=134}}</ref>\n* The [[105th Infantry Division (German Empire)|105th Infantry Division]] of the [[German Army (German Empire)|Imperial German Army]] was established.<ref>[http://www.1914-18.info/erster-weltkrieg.php?u=201 101. Infanterie-Division (Chronik 1915/1918)]</ref>\n* [[St. John's College, Nugegoda|St. John's College]] was established in [[Nugegoda]], [[British Ceylon]] as the first English-language school in the country.<ref>{{cite web| title=About St. John's College| url=http://www.stjohnscollege.lk/about.html| website=St. John's College| publisher=St. John's College| accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref>\n* The all-girls public school [[Samudradevi Balika Vidyalaya]] was established in [[Nugegoda]], [[British Ceylon]].<ref>{{cite news|title=St.John's, Nugegoda celebrates centenary|url=http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=132176|accessdate=21 June 2017| newspaper=[[The Island (Sri Lanka)]]|date=21 September 2015}}</ref>\n* The [[association football]] organization [[Federa\u00e7\u00e3o Mineira de Futebol]] was established to manage football clubs in [[Minas Gerais]], [[Brazil]] and represent the clubs at the [[Brazilian Football Confederation]].\n* '''Born:''' [[Alice Faye]], American singer and actress, best known for the [[Academy Awards|Oscar-winning]] song \"[[You'll Never Know]]\" in the film ''[[Hello, Frisco, Hello]]'', in [[New York City]] (d. [[1998]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Ronald Poulton]], English rugby player, centre for the [[England national rugby union team]] from 1909 to 1914, and [[Oxford University RFC|Oxford University]] from 1908 to 1911 (killed by a sniper near [[Ploegsteert]], [[Belgium]]) (b. [[1889]])\n\n== [[May 6]], 1915 (Thursday) ==\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013 Russian forces abandoned the city of [[Tarn\u00f3w]], [[Poland]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Austro-German forces drive Russians out of the Carpathians|url=http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/austro-german-forces-drive-russians-out-of-the-carpathians|website=History Channel|publisher=A+E Networks|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Krithia]] \u2013 British, Australian and New Zealand forces launched an assault on Ottoman defenses on the Helles battlefield during the [[Gallipoli campaign]] but failed to advance further than 400 yards (370 metres).<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bean|first1=Charles|title=The Story of ANZAC from 4 May 1915, to the Evacuation of the Gallipoli Peninsula|journal=Official History of Australia in the War of 1914\u20131918|date=1941|volume=II|issue=1926|pages=18\u201319|publisher=Australian War Memorial|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory|oclc=220051990}}</ref>\n* The [[Imperial Russian Army]] launched a major offensive on [[Anatolia]] and also threatened [[Van, Turkey]].<ref>{{cite book| first=Edward |last=Erickson |title=[[Ordered to Die: A History of the Ottoman Army in the First World War]] |location=Westport, Connecticut |publisher=Greenwood Publishing |year=2001a |origyear=2000 |isbn=0-313-31516-7 |page=109}}</ref>\n* After receiving messages that a German [[U-boat]] sunk British merchant ship ''Candidate'' and nearly sunk the British ocean liner [[SS Arabic (1902)|''Arabic'']], Captain [[William Thomas Turner]] of the {{RMS|Lusitania}} ordered the crew to make emergency preparations in case the ship was attacked and had to be abandoned, although passengers were not informed.<ref>Preston 2003, p. 197</ref>\n* German submarine ''[[SM U-20 (Germany)|U-20]]'' fired a torpedo at British steamer ''Cayo Romano'' from [[Cuba]], even though it was flying a neutral flag, off the southern coast of [[Ireland]] narrowly missing by a few feet.<ref>Molony 2004, p. 8</ref>\n* [[Ross Sea party]] \u2013 A fierce winter storm unmoored the polar ship ''[[SY Aurora|Aurora]]'' at [[McMurdo Sound]] in the [[Antarctic]], causing her to drift. On board were 18 men including first officer [[Joseph Stenhouse]] while another 10 were marooned onshore; the six members involved in the sledge parties that were setting up supply depots for the main [[Imperial Trans-Antarctic Expedition]], including expedition commander [[Aeneas Mackintosh]], were stranded in [[Hut Point Peninsula|Hut Point]] and four members scientists that were camped at [[Cape Evans]].<ref>{{cite book | authorlink = Kelly Tyler-Lewis | last = Tyler-Lewis | first = Kelly | title = The Lost Men | publisher = Bloomsbury Publications | year = 2007 | location = London | isbn = 978-0-7475-7972-4|page=129}}</ref>\n* Baseball player [[Babe Ruth]] hit his first career home run off pitcher [[Jack Warhop]] for the [[Boston Red Sox]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Creamer|first1=Robert W.|title=Babe: The Legend Comes to Life|date=1974|publisher=Simon & Schuster|location=New York|isbn=0-671-76070-X|page=[https://archive.org/details/babelegendcomest00crea_0/page/106 106]|edition=First Fireside 1992|url=https://archive.org/details/babelegendcomest00crea_0/page/106}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Orson Welles]], American actor and director, directed and produced ''[[Citizen Kane]]'', considered by most film critics as one of the [[list of films considered the best|all-time greatest films]], as well as acclaimed films ''[[The Magnificent Ambersons]]'' and ''[[Touch of Evil]]'', and roles in ''[[The Third Man]]'' and ''[[Catch-22 (film)|Catch-22]]'',  in [[Kenosha, Wisconsin]] (d. [[1985]])\n\n== [[May 7]], 1915 (Friday) ==\n[[File:Track of Lusitania.jpg|thumb|right|450px|Painting by [[William Lionel Wyllie]] depicting casualties and survivors in the water and in lifeboats following the [[Sinking of the RMS Lusitania|sinking of the RMS ''Lusitania'']].]]\n* British [[ocean liner]] [[sinking of the RMS Lusitania|RMS ''Lusitania'']] was sunk by [[Imperial German Navy]] [[U-boat]] ''[[SM U-20 (Germany)|U-20]]'' off the south-west coast of [[Ireland]], killing 1,198 civilians en route from [[New York City]] to [[Liverpool]].<ref>Preston 2003 pp. 216-17</ref> Among the notable passengers who died during the sinking included:\n** [[Thomas O'Brien Butler]], Irish composer (b. [[1861 in Ireland|1861]])\n** [[Marie Depage]], Belgian nurse (b. [[1872 in science|1872]])\n** [[Justus Miles Forman]], American writer (b. [[1875]])\n** [[Charles Frohman]], American theater producer (b. [[1856]])\n** [[Elbert Hubbard]], American writer and philosopher (b. [[1856]])\n** [[Alice Moore Hubbard]], wife of [[Elbert Hubbard]] (b. [[1861]])\n** [[Hugh Lane]], Irish art dealer, collector and benefactor (b. [[1875 in art|1875]])\n** [[Charles Klein]], American playwright (b. [[1867]])\n** [[Basil Maturin]], Irish preacher (b. [[1847]])\n** [[Frederick Stark Pearson]], American engineer (b. [[1861]])\n** [[Alfred Gwynne Vanderbilt]], American sportsman (b. [[1877]])\n** [[Lothrop Withington]], American historian (b. 1856)\n* [[1915 Danish Folketing election|Parliamentary elections]] were held in [[Denmark]] but, because of [[World War I]], no campaigning took place and 104 out of 114 constituencies did not vote. Even so, ruling Danish political party [[Venstre (Denmark)|Venstre]] retained majority of the 114 seats in the [[Folketing|Danish Parliament]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Hatting|first=J\u00f8rgen|editor=Fabricius, K. |editor2=Frisch, H. |editor3=Hjelholt, H. |editor4=Mackeprang, M. |editor5=M\u00f8ller, A. |title=Den Danske Rigsdag 1849\u20131949 bind III \u2013 Rigsdagen og folket|year=1950|publisher=J. H. Schultz Forlag|location=Copenhagen|language=Danish|chapter=Valgdeltagelsen efter 1866|page=119}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Elklit|first=J\u00f8rgen|editor=Elklit, J\u00f8rgen |editor2=Tonsgaard, Ole |title=Valg og v\u00e6lgeradf\u00e6rd \u2013 Studier i dansk politik|chapter=Det klassiske danske partisystem bliver til|year=1984|publisher=Forlaget Politica|location=\u00c5rhus|language=Danish|isbn=87-7335-058-3|page=34}}</ref>\n* [[Battle of Hill 60 (Western Front)|Battle of Hill 60]] \u2013 Two British infantry companies failed to recapture the [[Hill 60 (Ypres)|hill]] from the Germans, officially ending the battle. In all, the British [[5th Infantry Division (United Kingdom)|5th Infantry Division]] assigned to take Hill 60 had 3,100 casualties.{{sfn|Edmonds|Wynne|1927|p=306}}\n* The Sanuki Railway Company extended the Yosan Line in the [[Kagawa Prefecture]], [[Japan]], with station [[Tsushimanomiya Station|Tsushimanomiya]] serving the line.<ref>{{cite book |script-title=ja: \u505c\u8eca\u5834\u5909\u9077\u5927\u8f9e\u5178 \u56fd\u9244\u30fbJR\u7de8|trans-title=Station Transition Directory - JNR/JR| publisher = JTB | editor1-last = Ishino| editor1-first = Tetsu| year = 1998 | location = Japan |language= Japanese | volume = II| page = 633| isbn = 4-533-02980-9}}</ref>\n* '''Died:''' [[Edward Frederick Robert Bage]], Australian explorer, member of the [[Australasian Antarctic Expedition]] in 1911 to 1914, recipient of the [[Polar Medal]], killed during the [[Gallipoli campaign]] (b. [[1888]])\n\n== [[May 8]], 1915 (Saturday) ==\n* Pressured by its inability to mobilize for war, [[China]] accepted a revision of the [[Twenty-One Demands]] made by [[Japan]].<ref>{{cite web| last1=Duffy| first1=Michael| title='21 Demands' Made by Japan to China, 18 January 1915| url=http://www.firstworldwar.com/source/21demands.htm| website=First World War| publisher=Michael Duffy| accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Ypres]] \u2013 German forces bombarded and attacked Canadian forces defending the forward line of the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] at the Frezenberg ridge over five days.{{sfn|Edmonds|Wynne|1927|p=310}}\n* [[Second Battle of Krithia]] \u2013 New Zealand relieved the British forces who barely made it 800 yards (740 metres) towards the Ottoman line. The New Zealand pushed to gain another 400 yards (370 metres) before being pinned down. By evening, they launched a new attack backed by Australian support. They were able to capture a portion of the front trenches on one of the flanks but they were pushed back everywhere else, thus ending the battle.<ref>Bean, 1941, pp. 18-19</ref>\n* [[Bernhard Dernburg]], former secretary for the [[Imperial Colonial Office]] of [[Germany]], stated the [[Sinking of the RMS Lusitania|sinking of the RMS ''Lusitania'']] was justified as the ship \"carried contraband of war\" and \"was classed as an auxiliary cruiser\".<ref>{{Cite news | author-link =  | last2 =  | first2 =  | author2-link =  | title = Sinking Justified, Says Dr. Dernburg; Lusitania a \"War Vessel,\" Known to be Carrying Contraband, Hence Search Was Not Necessary. |work=New York Times | page = 4 | date = 9 May 1915 | url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1915/05/09/301791392.pdf | format=PDF}}</ref>\n* [[Armenian Genocide]] \u2013 Around 220 Armenians intellectuals arrested on April 24 were separated and sent to holding centres in [[\u00c7ank\u0131r\u0131]] and [[Aya\u015f, Ankara|Aya\u015f]], [[Turkey]].<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=Raymond K\u00e9vorkian|first=Raymond|last=K\u00e9vorkian|title=Le G\u00e9nocide des Arm\u00e9niens [The Armenian Genocide]|language=fr|publisher=Odile Jacob|location=Paris|year=2006|isbn=978-2-7381-1830-1|page=318}}</ref>\n* [[Ross Sea party]] \u2013 The polar ship ''[[SY Aurora|Aurora]]'' was adrift in the ice and moving into the [[Ross Sea]] away from the [[Antarctic]] continent.<ref>{{cite book | last = Haddelsey | first = Stephen | title = Ice Captain | publisher = The History Press | location = Stroud, Gloucestershire | year = 2008 | isbn = 0-7509-4348-3|pages=53\u201357}}</ref>\n* Thoroughbred racehorse [[Regret (horse)|Regret]] with jockey [[Joe Notter]] won the [[1915 Kentucky Derby|41st running]] of the [[Kentucky Derby]] with a time of 2:05.40. Regret was the first [[filly]] ever to win the Derby,  causing [[Churchill Downs]] president [[Matt Winn]] to observe that because of Regret's win \"the Derby was thus made an American institution.\"<ref>Bolus, Jim.  ''Kentucky Derby Stories''.  Pelican Publishing Company.  Gretna, LA, 1993, p. 74</ref>\n* The [[Kew tram depot]] in [[Kew, Victoria]], [[Australia]] began operations to serve the [[Melbourne]] area.<ref>{{cite web|title=The early days|url=http://www.yarratrams.com.au/about-us/our-history/tramway-milestones/the-early-days/|work=[[Yarra Trams]]|accessdate=7 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318134537/http://www.yarratrams.com.au/about-us/our-history/tramway-milestones/the-early-days/|archive-date=18 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Kew Tram Depot celebrates 100 years|url=http://www.yarratrams.com.au/media-centre/news/articles/2015/kew-tram-depot-celebrates-100-years/|publisher=Yarra Trams|accessdate=3 May 2015}}</ref>\n* '''Died:''' [[Henry McNeal Turner]], American religious leader, 12th [[Bishop]] for the [[African Methodist Episcopal Church]] (b. [[1834]])\n\n== [[May 9]], 1915 (Sunday) ==\n[[File:Die erbitterten K\u00e4mpfe um Lorettoh\u00f6he (PK Martin Herpich M\u00fcnchen 1915 TPk132).jpg|thumb|350px|French and German soldiers fight at the opening of the [[Second Battle of Artois]].]]\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013  [[Grand Duke Nicholas Nikolaevich of Russia (1856\u20131929)|Grand Duke Nicholas]] permitted a limited withdrawal as Austro-Hungarian Third and Fourth Armies pressed forward in the [[Carpathian Mountains]].<ref>DiNardo, 2010, p. 75.</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 The French Tenth Army launched a major offensive against the Germans in the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] in northeastern [[France]], capturing a few front line trenches and taking 3,000 Germans prisoner along with 10 field guns and 15 machine guns. However, no successes were made capturing any major villages or towns.<ref>{{cite book |title=Early Trench Tactics in the French Army: the Second Battle of Artois, May\u2013June 1915 |last=Krause |first=J. |authorlink= |year=2013 |publisher=Ashgate |location=Farnham |edition=1st |isbn=1-4094-5500-9|pages=69\u201373}}</ref>\n* [[Battle of Aubers Ridge]] \u2013 The [[First Army (United Kingdom)|British First Army]] launched a simultaneous attack on the German line north of the French Tenth Army to widen the enemy's defensive gap but failed to break through.<ref>{{cite book|series=History of the Great War Based on Official Documents By Direction of the Historical Section of the Committee of Imperial Defence |title=Military Operations France and Belgium, 1915: Battles of Aubers Ridge, Festubert, and Loos |volume=II |last=Edmonds |first=J. E. |authorlink=James Edward Edmonds |year=1928 |publisher=Macmillan |location=London |edition=1st |oclc=58962526 |pages=14\u201315}}</ref>\n* The German government released an official statement confirming an [[Imperial German Navy]] [[u-boat]] had [[Sinking of the RMS Lusitania|sunk the RMS ''Lusitania'']] but maintained the ship was armed and was transporting \"war materials\".<ref>{{cite book | last = Halsey  | first = Francis Whiting | title = The Literary Digest History of the World War | url = https://archive.org/details/literarydigesthi00hals  | publisher = Funk & Wagnalls | year = 1919 | page = [https://archive.org/details/literarydigesthi00hals/page/255 255]}}</ref> However, the [[Port of New York and New Jersey|Port of New York]] issued an official denial of Germany's charges, saying the ship had been inspected and had not been outfitted with any guns nor it was carrying any munitions aside from some ammo for small firearms, a common practice among cargo shipping.<ref>{{Cite news | author-link =  | last2 =  | first2 =  | author2-link =  | title = Lusitania was unarmed | newspaper = [[New York Times]] | date = 10 May 1915 | url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1915/05/10/104646600.pdf | format=PDF}}</ref>\n* '''Died:''' [[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]], Luxembourgian cyclist, first foreigner to win the [[Tour de France]] in 1909, killed at the [[Second Battle of Artois]] (b. [[1887]]); [[Anthony Wilding]], New Zealand tennis player, bronze medalist at the [[1912 Summer Olympics]] and triple World Championship winner in 1913, killed at the [[Battle of Aubers Ridge]] (b. [[1883]])\n\n== [[May 10]], 1915 (Monday) ==\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 The French launched a feint attack as a decoy while new cavalry divisions were moved in to assist the Tenth Army. Meanwhile, Germany launched a counter-attacked and recaptured some of their trenches and tunnels between the villages of [[Carency]] and [[Souchez]],{{sfn|The Times|1916|p=219}} and repulsed an attack at [[Neuville-Vitasse]].{{sfn|Krause|2013|pp=74\u201377}}\n* [[Action of 10 May 1915]] \u2013 The Ottoman battleship [[SMS Goeben|''Yavuz Sultan Selim'']], formerly the [[SMS Goeben|SMS ''Goeben'']], tried to intercept Russian naval ships [[Russian battleship Tri Sviatitelia|''Tri Sviatitelia'']] and [[Russian battleship Potemkin|'' Panteleimon'']] sighted earlier by an Ottoman destroyer in the [[Black Sea]]. Instead, it mistakenly ran into a Russian naval squadron that included [[Russian battleship Evstafi|''Evstafi'']], [[Russian battleship Ioann Zlatoust|''Ioann Zlatoust'']], and [[Russian battleship Rostislav|''Rostislav'']]. The ''Yavuz Sultan Selim'' exchanges fire with the squadron for 15 minutes but, outnumbered, it backed off and escaped.<ref>{{cite book| last = Noppen| first = Ryan K.| title = Ottoman Navy Warships 1914\u201318| publisher = Bloomsbury Publishing| date = 20 July 2015| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=G7edCwAAQBAJ&dq=&source=gbs_navlinks_s| isbn = 978-1-4728-0620-8}}</ref>\n* An [[German Army (German Empire)|Imperial German Army]] [[Zeppelin]] attempted to bomb [[Southend-on-Sea]], [[England]] but was driven off by unexpected gunfire. On retreat, airship commander Erich Linnarz allegedly scrawled a threat to return on a calling card from his wallet and dropping it in a weighted canister found on [[Canvey Island]].<ref>Whitehouse 1966, pp. 80-81.</ref>\n* [[William Thomas Turner]], surviving captain of the {{RMS|Lusitania}}, gave initial evidence of the [[Sinking of the RMS Lusitania|sinking]] to authorities, including testimony a German torpedo struck the ship between the third and fourth funnels.<ref>Preston 2003, pp. 330-32</ref>\n* U.S. President [[Woodrow Wilson]] countered public demands for the [[United States]] to declare war on [[Germany]] for the [[sinking of the RMS Lusitania|sinking of the RMS ''Lusitania'']], stating while in [[Philadelphia]], \"There is such a thing as a nation being so right that it does not need to convince others by force that it is right.\"<ref>{{cite book| last = Jones| first = Howard| title = Crucible of Power: A History of U.S. Foreign Relations Since 1897| year = 2001| publisher = Rowman & Littlefield| isbn = 978-0-8420-2918-6| page = [https://archive.org/details/crucibleofpower00jone/page/73 73]| url = https://archive.org/details/crucibleofpower00jone/page/73}}</ref>\n* Lieutenant [[Denys Corbett Wilson]] of the [[Royal Flying Corps]] died after being shot down while flying a [[Morane-Saulnier L|Morane-Saulnier airplane]] on a reconnaissance mission over France.<ref>{{cite news| title= Ireland's Roll of Honour: Losses in Irish Regiments: Officers Killed| newspaper= Irish Times| location= Dublin| date= 29 May 1915| page= 6}}</ref>\n* The [[Escadrille SPA.57]] of the [[French Air Force]] was established near [[Arras]], [[France]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Franks|first1=Norman|last2=Bailey|first2=Frank W.|title=Over the Front: A Complete Record of the Fighter Aces and Units of the United States and French Air Services, 1914\u20131918|date=1992|publisher=Grub Street|isbn=0-948817-54-2|page=94}}</ref>\n* The first edition of the El Salvadoran daily newspaper ''[[La Prensa Gr\u00e1fica]]'' was published.<ref>See [http://www.cis-elsalvador.org/May-June2004.pdf Centro de Intercambio y Solidaridad, Bulletin, May/June 2004.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071025054541/http://www.cis-elsalvador.org/May-June2004.pdf |date=2007-10-25 }}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Denis Thatcher]], British businessman, husband of UK Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]], in [[London]] (d. 2003); [[Beyers Naud\u00e9]], South African theologian and activist, founder of the [[Christian Institute of Southern Africa]], in [[Roodepoort]], [[Transvaal (province)|Transvaal]], [[South Africa]] (d. [[2004]]); [[Anthony Peraino]], American mobster, member of the [[Colombo crime family]] who financed the pornographic hit ''[[Deep Throat (film)|Deep Throat]]'', in [[New York City]] (d. [[1996]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Gaston Cros]], French archaeologist and army officer, commander of French forces during the [[Zaian War]], lead the archeological dig of the ancient city of [[Girsu]] in [[Mesopotamia]] (now [[Iraq]]), recipient of the [[Legion of Honour]], [[Order of the Dragon of Annam]], ''[[Ordre des Palmes acad\u00e9miques]]'', and ''[[Croix de guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)|Croix de guerre]]'' (killed in action during the [[Second Battle of Artois]] (b. 1861)\n\n== [[May 11]], 1915 (Tuesday) ==\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 French forces captured key high ground from the Germans, depriving them of strategic viewing points of the battlefield.{{sfn|The Times|1916|p=219-222}}{{sfn|Krause|2013|pp=77\u201381}}\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013 Russian forces regrouped and gun in at the [[San (river)|San River]] in what is now southeastern [[Poland]] to slow the [[Central Powers]] advance.<ref>Wren, Jack. ''The Great Battles of World War I''. New York: Grosset & Dunlap, 1971. Print. {{OCLC| 2779383}} {{ISBN|9780448020372}}, p. 116</ref> \n* The [[Royal Flying Corps]] established the [[No. 18 Squadron RAF|No. 18 Squadron]] at [[RAF Northolt]] in [[London Borough of Hillingdon]], [[England]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rawlings|first1=J. D. R.|title=History of No. 18 Squadron|journal=Air Pictorial|date=September 1964|volume=26|issue=9|pages=288\u2013290}}</ref>\n* [[Royal Navy]] [[seaplane tender]] {{HMS|Ben-my-Chree}} tried to intercept a German [[airship]] in the [[North Sea]] using a [[Sopwith Aviation Company|Sopwith]] seaplane. However, the launching platform collapsed as the plane tried to take off, leaving the Zeppelin to go on and bomb four surfaced British submarines (without damaging them).<ref>Whitehouse 1966, p. 98</ref>\n* The Egyptian-Armenian daily newspaper ''[[Arev (daily)|Arev]]'' published its first issue.<ref>[http://ramgavar.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=509%3Aenger-eugene-papazian-by-ara-aharonian&catid=56%3Aramgavar-mamoul&Itemid=27&lang=am Ramgavar.org: \u053e\u0576\u0576\u0564\u0565\u0561\u0576 125-\u0561\u0574\u0565\u0561\u056f - \u0538\u0576\u056f\u0565\u0580 \u0537\u0585\u056a\u0567\u0576 \u0532\u0561\u0562\u0561\u0566\u0565\u0561\u0576] (in Armenian)</ref>\n* The [[Boston Opera Company]] declared bankruptcy.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Eaton|first1=Quaintance|title=The Boston Opera Company| date=1965}}</ref>\n\n== [[May 12]], 1915 (Wednesday) ==\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013 General [[August von Mackensen]] was ordered to advance his forces to the [[San (river)|San]] River and take bridgeheads on the east bank.<ref>DiNardo, 2010, p. 99</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 French forces renewed offenses against the German line, capturing 3,000 enemy troops in the process.{{sfn|The Times|1916|p=222}}\n* British battleship {{HMS|Goliath|1898|6}} was torpedoed and sunk by [[Ottoman destroyer Muavenet-i Milliye|Ottoman destroyer ''Mu\u00e2venet-i Mill\u00eeye'']] in the [[Dardanelles]] with the loss of 570 of her 700 crew.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Burt|first1=R. A.|title=British Battleships 1889\u20131904|date=1988|publisher=Naval Institute Press|location=Annapolis, Maryland|isbn=0-87021-061-0|pages=158\u201359}}</ref>\n* [[Defense of Van (1915)|Defense of Van]] \u2013 Ottoman forces failed to slow the Russian advance at the town of Ardjish north of [[Van, Turkey]].<ref>Verzhine Svazlyan, Armenian massacres, 1915\u20131923, p. 43</ref>\n* South African troops occupied [[Windhoek]], the capital of [[German South West Africa]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Tucker|first=Spencer|title=World War I: encyclopedia|year=2005|publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]]|isbn=1-85109-420-2|page=42}}</ref>\n* [[Tobias Norris]] became premier of [[Manitoba]], replacing [[Rodmond Roblin]] who was forced to resign from office after a commission appointed by the [[Lieutenant Governor of Manitoba]] found the government guilty of corruption in the tending of contracts for new legislative buildings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mhs.mb.ca/docs/features/timelinks/reference/db0011.shtml |title=Legislature Scandal |work=TimeLinks |publisher=Manitoba Historical Society |accessdate=2012-11-29}}</ref>\n* [[James Bryce, 1st Viscount Bryce|James Bryce]] of the [[Committee on Alleged German Outrages]] released a report detailing a mix of confirmed and unsubstantiated reports of atrocities allegedly committed by [[Germany]] during the first months of [[World War I]]. The report was widely accepted and translated into 30 languages.<ref>{{Cite journal | last =| first =| author-link =| last2 =| first2 =| author2-link =| title = The Bryce Report on German Atrocities | journal = [[Literary Digest]] | volume = 50 | issue = 22 | pages =  | date = 29 May 1915 | url =  | doi =  | id = | postscript =}}</ref>\n* The [[2nd Air Refueling Squadron|2nd Aero Squadron]] of the [[United States Army]] was formed.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hennessey |first=Juliette |year=1958 |url=http://www.afhra.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-090602-017.pdf |title=The United States Army Air Arm, April 1861 to April 1917 |work=USAF Historical Study No. 98 |publisher=AFHRA (USAF) |pages=151\u2013152 |accessdate=4 Dec 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722182357/http://www.afhra.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-090602-017.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-22 }}</ref>\n* [[Ross Sea party]] \u2013 While continuing to drift northward in the ice, the crew of the polar ship ''[[SY Aurora|Aurora]]'' managed to set up a temporary wireless aerial and communicate to the stranded members on shore at [[Cape Evans]] but communications failed to get through.<ref>Tyler-Lewis 2007, p. 199</ref>\n* The South African media company [[Naspers]] started out as a newspaper and magazine publisher founded by [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]] leader [[J. B. M. Hertzog]] in [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.naspers.com/our-history.html | title=Naspers website: Our history | publisher=Naspers | work=Company history | accessdate=15 March 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320141659/http://www.naspers.com/our-history.html | archive-date=20 March 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://medialternatives.com/2011/11/15/media-inc-the-story-of-naspers-media24-and-channel-life/ | title=Apartheid Inc, the story of Naspers, Media24 and Channel Life | publisher=Media Alternatives | date=15 November 2011 | accessdate=15 March 2015}}</ref>\n* The [[association football]] club [[Nex\u00f8 Boldklub Bornholm|Nex\u00f8]] was established in [[Nex\u00f8]], [[Denmark]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Club Info - History |url=http://live-10017-klubprojekt-18.umbraco-proxy.com/klubben/klubinfo/historie/ |website=Nex\u00f8 Boldklub Bornholm |accessdate=2 September 2019 |language=Danish}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Brother Roger]], Swiss religious leader, founder of the [[Taiz\u00e9 Community]], in [[Provence, Switzerland]] (d. [[2005]])\n* '''Died:''' [[William H. Forwood]], American army medical officer, 19th [[Surgeon General of the United States Army]] (b. 1838)\n\n== [[May 13]], 1915 (Thursday) ==\n* Italian Prime Minister [[Antonio Salandra]] offered his resignation in the face of growing public opposition of entering [[World War I]] in accordance with the [[Treaty of London (1915)|Treaty of London]], but opposition leader [[Giovanni Giolitti]], fearful of nationalist disorder that might break into open rebellion, declined to succeed him.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Clark|first1=Martin|title=Modern Italy: 1871 to the present|date=2008|publisher=Pearson Education|location=Harlow|isbn=1-4058-2352-6|page=217}}</ref>\n* U.S. President [[Woodrow Wilson]] sent [[Germany]] the first of three letters related to the [[Sinking of the RMS Lusitania|sinking of the RMS ''Lusitania'']] calling for [[Germany]] to abandon submarine warfare against commercial vessels.<ref>{{cite book| last = Zieger| first = Robert H.| title = America's Great War| year = 1972| publisher = Rowman & Littlefield| isbn = 978-0-8476-9645-1| pages = 24\u201325 }}</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Ypres]] \u2013 Canadian forces prevented the forward line at Frezenberg ridge from falling into German hands but suffered massive casualties. In particular, the [[Princess Patricia's Canadian Light Infantry]] saw its 700-man force reduced to 150 men when the battle ended. As a result, the unit's unofficial motto \u2013 \"Holding up the whole damn line\" \u2013 is still used today.{{sfn|Edmonds|Wynne|1927|pp=311\u2013326}}\n* British officer Captain [[Julian Grenfell]] was mortally wounded by shrapnel when a shell landed a few yards away from where he was standing while talking to fellow officers of the [[1st The Royal Dragoons]]. He was taken to a hospital in [[Boulogne-sur-Mer|Boulogne]], [[France]] where he died thirteen days later. His poem \"Into Battle\" was published in ''[[The Times]]'' the day after his death.<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=Nicholas Mosley|last=Mosley|first=Nicholas|year=1976|title=Julian Grenfell: His Life and the Times of his Death 1888\u20131915|location=London|publisher=Weidenfeld & Nicolson|isbn=0-297-77093-4}}</ref> His younger brother Gerald William (Billy) Grenfell was killed in action two months later.\n* In the facing of growing [[anti-German sentiment]] in [[Australia]] following the [[sinking of the RMS Lusitania|sinking of the Lusitania]], the [[German Club, Sydney|German Club in Sydney]] notified the [[List of Commissioners of New South Wales Police|Commissioner of New South Wales Police]] that it was the club's intention to voluntarily close given the heightened threat of damage and violence against Australians with German heritage.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article15579146 |title=GERMAN CLUBS. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |location=NSW |date=14 May 1915 |accessdate=16 December 2015 |page=8 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n* The Kyoto Dent\u014d Company extended the [[Katsuyama Eiheiji Line]] in the [[Fukui Prefecture]], [[Japan]], with station [[Oiwakeguchi Station|Oiwakeguchi]] serving the line.<ref>[http://www57.tok2.com/home/tram/echizen.html History of Katsuyama Eiheiji Line]</ref>\n\n== [[May 14]], 1915 (Friday) ==\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 French forces captured the village of [[Carency]] but stopped from advancing on [[Souchez]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Doughty |first=R. A. |title=Pyrrhic Victory: French Strategy and Operations in the Great War |location=Cambridge, MA |publisher=Belknap Press |year=2005 |isbn=0-674-01880-X|page=161}}</ref>\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013 The [[Central Powers]] forces reached the [[San (river)|San River]] in what is now southeastern [[Poland]].<ref>Wren 1971, p. 116</ref>\n* [[May 14 Revolt]] \u2013 A mutinous group of naval marines, army soldiers, and members of the [[National Republican Guard (Portugal)|National Republican Guard of Portugal]] took control of several naval ships in [[Lisbon]] harbor, including the [[Portuguese ironclad Vasco da Gama|battleship ''Vasco da Game'']], in a revolt against the presidency of [[Manuel de Arriaga]]. The resulting insurrection between soldiers, sailors, police and civilians resulted in 200 deaths and over 1,000 injuries.<ref>{{cite book|first=Jo\u00e3o Ant\u00f3nio|last=Correia dos Santos|title=Subs\u00eddios para a Hist\u00f3ria Pol\u00edtica e Militar da Revolu\u00e7\u00e3o de 14 de Maio de 1915|location=Lisbon, Portugal|publisher=Tipografia da Cooperativa Militar|year=1915|trans-title=Papers on a History of the Revolution of 14th May, 1915|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n* The first local of the [[Fraternal Order of Police]] was established in [[Pittsburgh]].<ref>\"[http://www.fop.net/about/history/index.shtml History] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924090042/http://www.fop.net/about/history/index.shtml |date=2008-09-24 }}.\" Fraternal Order of Police.</ref>\n* The [[Mille Lacs National Wildlife Refuge]] was established in central [[Minnesota]] to protecting breeding spaces for various bird species, and is the smallest [[National Wildlife Refuge]] in the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mile Lacs \u2013 About the Refuge| url=http://www.fws.gov/refuge/Mille_Lacs/about.html|website=U.S. Fish and Wildlife|publisher=U.S. Fish and Wildlife Services}}</ref>\n\n== [[May 15]], 1915 (Saturday) ==\n* [[Battle of Festubert]] \u2013 The [[First Army (United Kingdom)|British First Army]] under command of General [[Douglas Haig, 1st Earl Haig|Douglas Haig]] launched a night-time attack on a {{convert|3|mi|km|adj=on}} portion of the German line from [[Neuve-Chapelle]], [[France]] in the north to the village of [[Festubert]] in the south.{{sfn|Edmonds|1928|pp=49\u201352}}\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 The Germans halted any further French advances into their territory.{{sfn|The Times|1916|p=223}}\n* [[1915 Singapore Mutiny|Singapore Mutiny]] \u2013 The court of inquiry into a mutiny among the Indian [[5th Light Infantry]] in [[Singapore]] concluded causes for it were inconclusively established. More than 200 Indian soldiers and officer were tried and 47 were sentenced to execution by firing squad. The remaining 600 Indian soldiers and officers that did not mutiny were ordered to serve with [[Allies of World War I|Allied]] operations in [[Africa]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Sareen | first = T.R. | title = Secret Documents on Singapore Mutiny 1915 | publisher = New Delhi: Mounto Publishing House | year = 1995 | isbn = 81-7451-009-5 | page = Report Section II}}</ref>\n* The [[1915 Far Eastern Championship Games|second]] [[Far Eastern Championship Games]] were held in [[Shanghai]] with [[China]], [[Japan]] and the [[Philippines]] participating.<ref>Bell, Daniel (2003). ''Encyclopedia of International Games''. McFarland and Company, Inc. Publishers, Jefferson, North Carolina. {{ISBN|0-7864-1026-4}}.</ref>\n* The first reference of [[jazz]] in relation to music may have come from [[Tom Brown (trombonist)|Tom Brown]] and his [[New Orleans]] band as they began performing in [[Chicago]] and started advertising themselves as a \"Jass Band\".<ref>[http://www.redhotjazz.com/browns.html Tom Brown's Band from Dixie Land] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303202853/http://www.redhotjazz.com/browns.html |date=2016-03-03 }}. Accessed 17 April 2013.</ref>\n* ''[[The Gourock Times]]'' weekly newspaper began publishing in [[Gourock]], [[Scotland]]. It would fold in 1980.<ref>{{cite book|title=Newspaper Press Directory|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K57oAAAAMAAJ|year=1928|publisher=Benn Brothers}}</ref>\n* The [[association football]] club [[Real Uni\u00f3n]] was established in [[Irun]], [[Spain]].<ref>{{cite web |title=A little history about the club | url=https://www.realunionclub.com/historia |website=Real Uni\u00f3n |accessdate=13 September 2019 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Hilda Bernstein]], British-American writer and activist, author of ''[[The World That Was Ours]]'', in [[London]] (d. [[2006]]); [[Paul Samuelson]], American economist, recipient of the [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences]], author of ''[[Foundations of Economic Analysis]]'', in [[Gary, Indiana]] (d. [[2009]]); [[Shozo Makino (swimmer)|Shozo Makino]], Japanese swimmer, silver medalist at the [[1932 Summer Olympics]] and bronze medalist at the [[1936 Summer Olympics]], in [[Shizuoka Prefecture]], [[Japan]] (d. [[1987]])\n\n== [[May 16]], 1915 (Sunday) ==\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013 The [[Central Powers]] established bridgeheads over the [[San (river)|San]] River and prepared to assault [[Przemy\u015bl]] and the 44 forts that surrounded it.<ref>DiNardo, 2010, p. 99.</ref>\n* [[Defense of Van (1915)|Defense of Van]] \u2013 While evacuating women and children in [[Van, Turkey]] by way of port ships under cover of artillery fire, Ottoman soldiers massacred 6,000 Armenians.<ref>\"6000 Armenians Killed.\" ''New York Times''. London. 17 May 1915, reproduced in: ''The Armenian Genocide.'' Ed. Richard Diran Kloian. 1980. p. 17</ref>\n* [[Battle of Festubert]] \u2013 Renewed attacks on the German line only resulted in heavy losses for the British.{{sfn|Edmonds|1928|pp=59\u201373}}\n* Two [[Royal Naval Air Service]] planes intercepted two [[Imperial German Navy]] [[Zeppelin]]s, badly damaging one using bombs dropped on its envelope from above.<ref>Thetford, Owen, ''British Naval Aircraft Since 1912'', 6th ed., Annapolis, Maryland: Naval Institute Press, 1991, {{ISBN|1-55750-076-2}}, p. 33.</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Percy Charles Pickard]], British air force officer, commander of the [[No. 51 Squadron RAF|No. 51]] and [[No. 161 Squadron RAF|No. 161 Squadron]] during [[World War II]], recipient of the [[Distinguished Service Order]], [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]], and [[Czechoslovak War Cross 1939\u20131945|Czechoslovak War Cross]], in [[Handsworth, South Yorkshire]], [[England]] (d. [[1944]], killed in action)\n\n== [[May 17]], 1915 (Monday) ==\n[[File:RussianTroops Van1915.jpg|thumb|250px|Russian and Armenian relief forces arrive in [[Defense of Van (1915)|Van]].]]\n* The last purely [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] government in [[Great Britain]] ended when the prime minister [[H. H. Asquith]] formed an all-party [[coalition government]], in response to a cabinet split caused by fallout from the [[Shell Crisis of 1915|Shell Crisis]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Fraser|first1=Peter|title=The British 'Shells Scandal' of 1915|journal=Canadian Journal of History|date=1983|volume=1|issue=18|pages=77\u201394}}</ref>\n* [[Defense of Van (1915)|Defense of Van]] \u2013 Governor [[Djevdet Bey]] of the [[Van Province]] abandoned [[Van, Turkey]] and joined the [[1st Expeditionary Force (Ottoman Empire)|1st Expeditionary Force]] under the command of [[lieutenant colonel|Lieutenant Colonel]] [[Halil Kut]], leaving the city in temporary control of the Armenian militia.<ref>[[Ali \u0130hsan S\u00e2bis]], ''Birinci D\u00fcnya Harbi'', 2. cilt, Nehir Yay\u0131nlar\u0131, {{ISBN|975-551-067-2}}, p. 437. {{in lang|tr}}</ref>\n* [[Germany]] released a [[The German White Book|White Book]] that refuted the claims of German war-time atrocities made in a report by the [[Committee on Alleged German Outrages]] five days earlier while outline their reasons to going to war against the [[Triple Entente]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/pathways/firstworldwar/document_packs/p_whitebook.htm| title=German White Book|publisher=The National Archives| location=United Kingdom| accessdate=23 January 2017}}</ref>\n* Italian-American mob boss [[Giosue Gallucci]], head of one of the [[Camorra in New York City|Camorra gangs]] in [[New York City]], was shot along with his son Lucas in a coffee shop in [[East Harlem]]. His son died the next day and Gallucci died from his wounds fours days later. His murder created a power vacuum among the crime families, resulting in the [[Mafia\u2013Camorra War]] the following year.<ref>{{cite book| last1=Downey|first1=Patrick|title=Gangster City: The History of the New York Underworld, 1900\u20131935|date=2004|publisher=Barricade Books| location=Fort Lee, NJ|isbn=978-1-56980-361-5|pages=85\u201386}}</ref>\n\n== [[May 18]], 1915 (Tuesday) ==\n* [[Battle of Festubert]] \u2013 The [[1st Canadian Division]] was mobilized to attack the German line with support from a British division but failed to progress against enemy artillery.{{sfn|Edmonds|1928|pp=73\u201377}}\n* British submarine [[HMS E11|HMS ''E11'']] infiltrated Turkish waters past the [[Dardanelles]].<ref>{{cite book |last=O'Connell |first=John |title=Submarine Operational Effectiveness in the 20th Century: Part One (1900\u20131939) |year=2010 |location=New York |publisher=Universe |isbn=1-4502-3689-8|page=74}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Pitt |first1=Barrie |last2=Young|first2=Peter |title=History of the First World War|volume=3|year=1970 |location=London |publisher=B.P.C. Publishing |oclc=669723700|page=918}}</ref>\n* The [[4th Guards Infantry Division (German Empire)|4th Guards Infantry Division]] of the [[Imperial German Army]] was established.<ref>[http://www.1914-18.info/erster-weltkrieg.php?u=126 4. Garde-Infanterie-Division (Chronik 1915/1918)]</ref>\n* The [[Belgium]] monarchy created a civilian variant of the [[Civic Decoration]] medal for Belgian civilians and non-combatants that served with distinction during [[World War I]].<ref>{{cite web  | authorlink = Belgian government | title = Royal Decree of 18 May 1915 creating the Civic Decoration 1914\u20131915 | publisher = Belgian Government | date = 1915-05-18  }}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Neil W. Chamberlain]], American economist, known for his concepts on [[bargaining power]], in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]] (d. [[2006]])\n* '''Died:''' [[William Bridges (general)|William Bridges]], Australian army officer, commander of the [[1st Division (Australia)|1st Australian Division]] during the [[Gallipoli campaign]], succumbed to injuries sustained from sniper fire (b. [[1861]]); [[Amos W. Barber]], American politician, second [[List of governors of Wyoming|Governor of Wyoming]] (b. [[1861]])\n\n== [[May 19]], 1915 (Wednesday) ==\n[[File:Assault of Ottoman soldiers.jpg|thumb|250px|Turkish troops attacking during the [[Gallipoli campaign]].]]\n* [[Gallipoli campaign]] \u2013 The Ottoman army launched a [[third attack on Anzac Cove]] with 42,000 soldiers but were repelled by the 17,000 [[Australian and New Zealand Army Corps|ANZAC]] troops. Ottoman forces sustained 13,000 casualties including 3,000 killed, while [[Australian and New Zealand Army Corps|ANZAC]] forces had 468 wounded and 160 killed.<ref>Erickson 2001a, p. 87</ref> Among the noted casualties was Australian army medic [[John Simpson Kirkpatrick]], who innovated the use of mules as stretchers for transporting wounded across the rugged terrain.<ref>[http://www.anzacs.net/Simpson.htm ANZACS.net: Simpson \u2013 Australia's favourite hero] (''c.'' 2010). Retrieved on 19 June 2010.</ref><ref>[http://www.awm.gov.au/exhibitions/dawn/boat/simpson.asp Australian War Memorial: Simpson and his donkey] (2010). Retrieved on 18 June 2010.</ref><ref>[http://www.awm.gov.au/research/people/roll_of_honour/person.asp?p=484810 Australian War Memorial: Roll of Honour \u2013 John Simpson Kirkpatrick] (2010). Retrieved on 18 June 2010.</ref>\n* [[May 14 Revolt]] \u2013 After the revolt among the Portuguese military had been quelled, [[Manuel de Arriaga]] announced his decision to resign as [[President of Portugal]].<ref>*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PkH9wfKMqHwC&pg=PR11&dq=portugal+first+republic&hl=en&ei=5PU8TOWfHpCG4gaHjaj0CQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCwQ6AEwAA#v=snippet&q=pimenta%20de%20castro&f=false|first=Douglas L.|last=Wheeler|title=Republican Portugal: A Political History 1910\u20131926| publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|location=Madison, Wisconsin|isbn=0-299-07450-1|page=124}}</ref>\n* The [[Grosvenor Picture Palace]] opened in [[Manchester]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://manchesterhistory.net/manchester/tours/tour8/area8Apage23.html | title=The Grosvenor Picture Palace | accessdate=29 March 2015}}</ref>\n* The [[Shire of Mundubbera]] was established in [[Queensland]], [[Australia]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article20032100 |title=LOCAL GOVERNMENT. |newspaper=[[The Brisbane Courier]] |date=21 May 1915 |accessdate=23 September 2013 |page=9 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Ren\u00e9e Asherson]], British actress, known for Shakespearean stage performances with [[The Old Vic]], [[Liverpool Playhouse]], [[Westminster Theatre]], and films roles such as ''[[The Way Forward]]'', in [[London]] (d. [[2014]])\n\n== [[May 20]], 1915 (Thursday) ==\n* [[Battle of Festubert]] \u2013 A renewed British offensive started to yield success against the Germans, but it would take five more days of fighting before the French village of Festubert was captured.{{sfn|Edmonds|1928|p=76}}\n* [[Defense of Van (1915)|Defense of Van]] \u2013 Russian forces entered [[Van, Turkey]], providing needed relief for Armenians resisting the onslaught of Ottoman troops.<ref>{{Cite book | editor1-last = Reynolds | editor1-first = Joseph Francis | editor2-first = Allen Leon | editor2-last = Churchill | editor3-first = Francis Trevelyan | editor3-last = Miller | year = 1916 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=410PAAAAYAAJ | title = The Story of the Great War: History of the European War from Official Sources; Complete Historical Records of Events to Date | volume = 3 | publisher = P.F. Collier & Son| page=478}}</ref>\n* [[Cleveland Railway (Ohio)|Cleveland Railway]] opened the [[Courtland station|Courtyard]] and [[Eaton station|Eaton]] stations to serve the Shaker Boulevard rail line in [[Cleveland]].<ref>{{cite book  | last = Toman  | first = James  | authorlink =  | coauthors =  | title = The Shaker Heights Rapid Transit  | publisher = Interurban Press  | date = 1990  | location = Glendale, Calif.  | pages = 17\u201318 | url =  | doi =  | isbn = 0-916374-95-5 }}</ref>\n* The [[Tucum\u00e1n Lawn Tennis Club]] was formed in [[San Miguel de Tucum\u00e1n]], [[Argentina]]. Initially offering tennis and cricket, it was since expanded into a multi-sports club with its [[rugby union]] Tucum\u00e1n LT being its flagship team.<ref>{{cite web|title=Historia \u2013 Institucional|url=http://www.tucumanlawntennis.org.ar/historia/institucional|website=Tucum\u00e1n Lawn Tennis Club|publisher=Tucum\u00e1n Lawn Tennis Club|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n* The sports club [[APGS Amsterdam|Amsterdam]] was formed in [[Amsterdam]] which included rugby, badminton, and even basketball.<ref>[http://apgs-amsterdam.nl/vereniging/organisatie/ APGS organisation]</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Moshe Dayan]], Israeli military leader and politician, commander during the [[1948 Arab\u2013Israeli War]], [[Chief of the General Staff (Israel)|chief of staff]] of the [[Israel Defense Forces]] during the [[Suez Crisis]], and Defense Minister during the [[Six-Day War]] in 1967, in [[Kibbutz]], [[Ottoman Syria]] (d. [[1981]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Charles Francis Adams Jr.]], American rail executive, president of the [[Union Pacific Railroad]] from 1884 to 1890 (b. [[1835]])\n\n== [[May 21]], 1915 (Friday) ==\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 [[France]] consolidated their forces while under heavy German fire but lost key positions.<ref>Doughty 2005, p. 162.</ref>\n* Armenian leader [[Krikor Zohrab]] and another fellow deputy with the Ottoman Parliament were arrested and ordered to [[Aleppo]] to be held while awaiting court-martial, follow the leader's public protests of atrocities committed against Armenians from April 24. He would be murdered in July during the height of the [[Armenian Genocide]].<ref>\u00dcng\u00f6r, U\u011fur, ''The Making of Modern Turkey: Nation and State in Eastern Anatolia, 1913\u20131950''. Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2011, p. 84.</ref>\n* The [[SPAD S.A]] aircraft was first flown in [[France]], but its design proved challenging for most pilots and was replaced soon after.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bruce|first=J.M.|title=SPAD S.A-2/S.A-4|series=Windsock Mini Datafile 4|publisher=Albatros Publications|location=Hertfordshire, UK|year=1996|isbn=978-0948414824|pages=3\u20135}}</ref>\n\n== [[May 22]], 1915 (Saturday) ==\n[[File:QuintinshillILN1.jpg|thumb|250px|A burning carriage in the aftermath of a [[Quintinshill rail disaster|train collision at Quintinshill]], [[Scotland]].]]\n* A [[Quintinshill rail disaster|rail collision and fire in Quintinshill]], [[Scotland]] killed 226 people, most of them troops, in what was the largest number of fatalities in a [[List of rail accidents in the United Kingdom|rail accident in Great Britain]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rolt|first1=L. T. C.|last2=Kichenside|first2=G. M.|title=Red for Danger: A history of railway accidents and railway safety|date=1982|publisher=David & Charles|location=Newton Abbot, Devon|isbn=0-7153-8362-0|pages=207\u2013213|edition=4th}}</ref>\n* [[Lassen Peak]], one of the [[Cascade Volcanoes]] in [[California]], erupted sending an ash plume 30,000 feet in the air and devastating the nearby area with mudslides and hot gas clouds mixed with debris. It is the last volcano to erupt in the contiguous United States until the [[1980 eruption of Mount St. Helens]].<ref name=\"Eruptions of Lassen Peak\">{{cite web | url = http://pubs.usgs.gov/fs/1998/fs173-98/ | title = Eruptions of Lassen Peak, California, 1914 to 1917 | work = U.S. Geological Survey Fact Sheet 173-98 | publisher = [[United States Geological Survey|USGS]] | accessdate = August 23, 2012 }}</ref>\n* [[T. J. Ryan]] was [[1915 Queensland state election|elected]] [[Premier of Queensland]] in [[Australia]], defeating incumbent [[Digby Denham]] with 52% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.uwa.edu.au/elecdetail.lasso?keyvalue=776|title=Parliament of Queensland, Assembly election, 22 May 1915|author=Australian Government and Politics Database|accessdate=14 January 2009}}</ref>\n* Thoroughbred racehorse Tartarean ridden by jockey [[Harry Watts (jockey)|Harry Watts]] won the 56th running of [[Canada]]'s [[Queen's Plate|King's Plate]] race with time of 2:09.20.<ref>{{cite book|title=Morning Telegraph's Racing Chart Book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ciEPAAAAYAAJ|volume=34|year=1915|page=46|oclc=669176445}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title=Chester Krum Good Thing in the Chase| url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=22&dat=19150526&id=eR8BAAAAIBAJ&sjid=bCgDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3204,1144756| newspaper=The Toronto World| date=May 26, 1915| accessdate=November 26, 2013}}</ref>\n* The Italian [[Futurist]] magazine ''[[Lacerba]]'' published its last issue after a brief two-year run in [[Florence]].<ref>{{cite book| author=Alan Bartram| title=Futurist Typography and the Liberated Text|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jRC5KvV7EgEC&pg=PA117| accessdate=18 June 2015| year=2005| publisher=Yale University Press| isbn=0-300-11432-X|page=117}}</ref>\n\n== [[May 23]], 1915 (Sunday) ==\n[[File:Vonmuecke.JPG|right|150px|thumb|German naval officer [[Hellmuth von M\u00fccke]], first officer of the [[SMS Emden|SMS ''Emden'']].]]\n[[Image:Otto Parschau's A-16-15 Eindecker.jpg|thumb|right|150px|The model of the first Fokker Eindecker fighter plane flew by [[Otto Parschau]].]]\n* [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]] joined the [[Allies of World War I|Allies]] after they declared war on [[Austria-Hungary]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Duffy|first1=Michael|title=Who Declared War and When|url=http://www.firstworldwar.com/features/declarationsofwar.htm|website=First World War|accessdate=21 January 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Faisal I of Iraq|Faisal bin Hussein]] received the [[Damascus Protocol]] document while visiting the city during a diplomatic mission to [[Constantinople]]. Authored by Arab secret societies, the document outlined an Arab revolt against the [[Ottoman Empire]] with support of the British, resulting in an independent Arab nation state.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Herzog|first1=Jacob David|title=A People That Dwells Alone: Speeches and Writings of Yaacov Herzog|date=1975|publisher=Weidenfeld and Nicolson|page=213}}</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 French forces began to take ground from the Germans as they advanced of [[Souchez]].<ref>Krause 2013, pp. 106\u2013109</ref>\n* German submarine {{SMU|UB-3||6}} was lost in the [[Gulf of \u0130zmir]] {{convert|80|nmi|km}} off [[\u0130zmir]] with the loss of all fourteen crew.<ref>{{cite book | last = Messimer | first = Dwight R. | title = Verschollen: World War I U-boat losses | location = Annapolis, Maryland | publisher = Naval Institute Press | year = 2002 | pages=126\u201327 | isbn = 978-1-55750-475-3 | oclc = 231973419}}</ref>\n* The [[Austro-Hungarian Navy]] began [[Bombardment of Ancona|bombarding]] the port of [[Ancona]], [[Italy]] soon after the country declared war on the [[Central Powers]].<ref>{{cite book  |last1=Sondhaus  |first1=Lawrence  |title=The Naval Policy of Austria-Hungary, 1867-1918: Navalism, Industrial Development, and the Politics of Dualism  |date=1994  |publisher=Purdue University Press  |location=West Lafayette, IN  |isbn=1-55753-034-3| pages=266\u2013270}}</ref>\n* [[Hellmuth von M\u00fccke]], first officer of the [[SMS Emden|SMS ''Emden'']], safely led 48 members of his surviving landing party to [[Constantinople]] where he reported to the German admiral stationed there. From the time they were stranded on the [[Cocos (Keeling) Islands|Cocos Islands]] in the [[Indian Ocean]] to their arrival in the Ottoman capital, von M\u00fccke had successfully led his men 11,000&nbsp;km over sea and land, losing only four on the way. He and his men arrived in [[Germany]] later that summer as heroes.<ref>{{cite book| last1=Carlton| first1=Mike| title=First Victory: 1914| date=2013| publisher=William Heinemann| location=Australia| isbn=1-74275-763-4| pages=333\u201334}}</ref>\n* German pilot [[Otto Parschau]] flew the first of the [[Fokker Eindecker fighters]], designed by [[Anthony Fokker]], in [[Douai]], [[France]]. The aircraft's high maneuverability, combined with [[synchronization gear]] that allowed fighter pilots to fire mounted machine gun bullets between the plane's propellers, gave German air superiority over the [[Allies of World War I|Allies]] for most of 1915 and 1916, to the point the fighters were referred to as [[Fokker Scourge]].<ref>Dierikx, Marc. ''Fokker: A Transatlantic Biography''. Washington, DC: Smithsonian Institution Press, 1997. {{ISBN|1-56098-735-9}}, p. 31</ref>\n* The sports club [[\u00c4lvsj\u00f6 AIK|\u00c4lvsj\u00f6]] was established in [[Stockholm]]. Initially the club included [[association football]], [[bandy]], [[hockey]] and [[floorball]]. In 1993, [[association football]] separated and became its own club.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.sportnik.com/group/2882/page/histria |title= \u00c4lvsj\u00f6 AIK FF \u2013 Historia |format= |work= |accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref>\n* German noble [[Heinrich XXVII, Prince Reuss Younger Line|Prince Heinrich]] established the [[War Merit Cross (Reuss)|War Merit Cross]] to be awarded to all ranks for exemplary conduct in combat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ehrenzeichen-orden.de/deutsche-staaten/kriegsverdienstkreuz-1915-steckkreuz.html |title=Kriegsverdienstkreuz 1915 (Steckkreuz) |publisher=Ehrenzeichen-orden.de |date= |accessdate=2013-07-30}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[S. Donald Stookey]], American inventor, patented 60 inventions related to ceramics or glass, including FotoForm which is used by [[CorningWare]], in [[Hay Springs, Nebraska]] (d. 2014); [[Jim Chamberlin]], Canadian aerodynamic engineer, member of the design team of the [[Avro Canada CF-105 Arrow|Avro Arrow]] and later for the [[Apollo program]], in [[Kamloops]], [[British Columbia]] (d. 1981)\n\n== [[May 24]], 1915 (Monday) ==\n* The term \"crime against humanity\" is used for the first time by governments in joint public statement issued by the [[Allies of World War I|Allied]] governments to Ottoman government accusing them of [[Armenian Genocide|committing genocide on ethnic Armenians]] within the [[Ottoman Empire]].<ref>1915 declaration\n* [http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/cpquery/T?&report=hr933&dbname=106& Affirmation of the United States Record on the Armenian Genocide Resolution] 106th Congress,2nd Session, House of Representatives\n* [http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c109:H.RES.316: Affirmation of the United States Record on the Armenian Genocide Resolution (Introduced in House of Representatives)] 109th Congress, 1st Session, [http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d109:HE00316: H.RES.316], June 14, 2005. 15 September 2005 House Committee/Subcommittee:International Relations actions. Status: Ordered to be Reported by the Yeas and Nays: 40\u20137.\n* \"Crimes Against Humanity\", 23 British Yearbook of International Law (1946) p. 181\n* Schabas [[#References|References]] pp. 16-17\n* [http://www.armenian-genocide.org/Affirmation.160/current_category.7/affirmation_detail.html  Original source of the telegram sent by the Department of State, Washington containing the French, British and Russian joint declaration]</ref>\n* British military diplomat [[Aubrey Herbert]] and Ottoman senior army officer [[Mustafa Kemal Atat\u00fcrk]] agreed to call an eight-hour truce at [[Gallipoli campaign|Gallipoli]] so both sides could recover and bury the dead.<ref>Broadbent 2005, p. 156</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Ypres]] \u2013 Germans released a gas attack on British forces defending a {{convert|7|km|mi|adj=on}} front near [[Hooge, Ypres|Hooge]], [[Belgium]], forcing them to retreat.{{sfn|Edmonds|Wynne|1927|p=340}}\n* The [[Bombardment of Ancona|bombardment]] on [[Ancona]], [[Italy]] ended with 63 killed and at least one Italian destroyer damaged.<ref>Sondhaus 1994, pp. 266=270</ref>\n* Irish soldier [[John Condon (British Army soldier)|John Condon]] for the [[British Army]] was killed in action, becoming the youngest British soldier to die in [[World War I]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Reading Room Manchester |url=http://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/491331 |title=Commonwealth War Graves Commission database record for John Condon |publisher=Cwgc.org |date=1915-05-24 |accessdate=2014-04-12}}</ref>\n* The prototype for the [[Siemens-Schuckert R.I]] airplane was first flown in [[Berlin]] and delivered for military service the following month.<ref>{{cite book| last=Haddow |first=G.W. |author2=Peter M. Grosz  |title=The German Giants: The Story of the R-planes 1914\u20131919 |publisher=Putnam |location=London |year=1962|page=175}}</ref>\n* Stage actress [[Alice Brady]] made her first credited film debut in ''[[The Boss (1915 film)|The Boss]]'', produced by her father  [[William A. Brady]].<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/B/Boss1915.html ''The Boss'' at silentera.com]</ref><ref>[http://ibdb.com/production.php?id=6997 ''The Boss'' as produced on Broadway at the Astor Theatre, January 30, 1911 to April 1911, 88 performances; IBDb.com]</ref>\n\n== [[May 25]], 1915 (Tuesday) ==\n[[File:E11 in action.jpg|thumb|right|400px|[[Royal Navy]] submarine [[HMS E11|HMS ''E11'']] torpedoes the \"Stamboul\" off [[Constantinople]].]]\n* [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|China]] agreed to the [[Twenty-One Demands]] made by [[Japan]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gowen|first1=Robert Joseph|title=Great Britain and the Twenty-One Demands of 1915: Cooperation versus Effacement|journal=Journal of Modern History|date=1971|volume=1|issue=43|pages=76\u2013106|bibcode= }}</ref>\n* [[Russia]], [[China]] and [[Mongolia]] signed the [[Treaty of Kyakhta (1915)|Treaty of Kyakhta]] which recognized the autonomy of [[Outer Mongolia]]. However, most Mongolians opposed the treaty because it did not recognize an independent, [[Pan-Mongolism|all-Mongolian]] state. The treaty became moot following the 1917 [[October Revolution]] in [[Russia]].<ref>Batsaikhan, O. The Last King of Mongolia, Bogdo Jebtsundamba Khutuktu. Ulaanbaatar: Admon, 2008, p.290-293 - {{ISBN|978-99929-0-464-0}}</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 French forces launched assaults to take [[Andres, Pas-de-Calais]], [[France]] from the Germans.<ref>The Times 1916, p. 226</ref>\n* [[Battle of Festubert]] \u2013 The British captured the French village of [[Festubert]] from the Germans. After 10 days of fighting, British forces had only advanced three kilometres (1.9 miles) while losing over 16,000 casualties, while German defenses only sustained 5,000.{{sfn|Edmonds|1928|p=76}}\n* [[Second Battle of Ypres]] \u2013 The British failed in retaking trenches lost to the German gas attack the day before, forcing them to retreat {{convert|1|km|mi}} northwards. The battle ended with the Germans compressing the Ypres salient by {{convert|5|km|mi}}.{{sfn|Edmonds|Wynne|1927|pp=353\u2013359}} Casualties on both sides were massive, with the Germans suffering close to 35,000 while the British were worse at just over 59,000. French forces sustained close to 22,000 casualties while the Canadian forces had close to 6,000. The city of [[Ypres]] itself was completely demolished by artillery fire.{{sfn|Edmonds|Wynne|1927|pp=359, 284}}\n* British battleship {{HMS|Triumph|1903|6}} was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Dardanelles]] by {{SMU|U-21|Germany|6}} with the loss of 78 of her 803 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{HMS|Chelmer|1904|6}}.<ref>Burt 1988, p. 276</ref>\n* Dutch ocean liner {{USS|Rijndam|ID-2505|2}} collided with Norwegian ocean liner SS ''Joseph J. Cuneo'' in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] {{convert|10|nmi|km}} south of the [[Nantucket Shoals]] of the [[United States]]. Two hundred and thirty passengers were rescued by [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] ships {{USS|Louisiana|BB-19|6}}, {{USS|Michigan|BB-27|6}}, {{USS|South Carolina|BB-26|6}} and {{USS|Texas|BB-35|6}}. ''Rijndam'' was subsequently repaired and returned to service.\n* The [[Asquith coalition ministry]], a national wartime [[coalition government]] to lead [[Great Britain]], went into effect. However, Irish leader [[John Redmond]] chose not to join and garnered support from [[Irish Parliamentary Party]].<ref>{{cite journal| last1=Butler| first1=David| last2=Butler| first2=Gareth| title=Twentieth Century British Political Facts, 1900\u20132000| date=2000| publisher=St. Martin's}}</ref>\n* British submarine [[HMS E11|HMS ''E11'']] slipped in [[Constantinople]] harbor in a search for the German warships {{SMS|Goeben}} and {{SMS|Breslau}}, but instead torpedoed Turkish transport ship ''Stambou'' before escaping. The attack caused a panic in the city and forced the {{SMS|Breslau}} to relocate.<ref>O'Connell 2010, p. 74</ref><ref>Pitt & Young 1970, p. 918</ref>\n* [[Ross Sea party]] \u2013 The polar ship ''[[SY Aurora|Aurora]]'' drifted toward the [[Victoria Land]] coastline on the western side of the [[Ross Ice Shelf]] in the [[Antarctic]].<ref>{{cite book | authorlink = Ernest Shackleton | last = Shackleton | first = Ernest | title = South | publisher = Century Publishing | location = London | year = 1983 | isbn = 0-7126-0111-2| page=312}}</ref>\n* The [[French Army]] established the [[102nd Fortress Division (France)|102nd Fortress Division]] for the [[6th Army (France)|6th Army]].<ref>{{cite web| title=102e Division d' Infanterie Territoriale |url=http://sacarcheo.nuxit.net/regiment/102eDIT.PDF |accessdate=28 August 2009 | archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5jWCYsQRS?url=http://sacarcheo.nuxit.net/regiment/102eDIT.PDF |archivedate=3 September 2009 |url-status=live | df=dmy }}</ref>\n* An [[Kochrab Ashram|ashram]] for [[Mahatma Gandhi]] was prepared by Jivanlal Desai, barrister and friend to Gandhi, just outside the city of [[Ahmedabad]], [[India]]. However, Gandhi wanted to practice farming and other pursuits and would need more usable land, so the [[Sabarmati Ashram|ashram]] was relocated two years later to a suburb in [[Ahmedabad]] on the banks of the [[Sabarmati River]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Gandhi|first=Mohandas|title=Gandhi Ashram Official Website|url=http://www.gandhiashramsabarmati.org}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Robin Day (designer)|Robin Day]], British furniture designer, designed the [[polypropylene stacking chair]], in [[High Wycombe]], [[England]] (d. [[2010]])\n\n== [[May 26]], 1915 (Wednesday) ==\n* The German [[Army of the Niemen]] was formed under the command of General [[Otto von Below]], who had previously commanded a reserve corps unit under the [[8th Army (German Empire)|8th Army]]. The army was meant to create diversionary action against the Russian armies to distract them from [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] planned to break through the [[Eastern Front (World War I)|Eastern Front]]. The original 8th Army was dissolved in September, only to be renewed using the diversionary army under von Below.<ref>{{cite book | last = Cron | first = Hermann | year = 2002 | title = Imperial German Army 1914\u201318: Organisation, Structure, Orders-of-Battle [first published: 1937] | publisher = Helion & Co. | pages=82\u201383 | isbn = 1-874622-70-1}}</ref>\n* The [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Arauca]] was established in [[Arauca, Arauca|Arauca]], [[Colombia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Diocese of Arauca|url=http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/arau0.htm|website=GCatholic.org|publisher=GCatholic.org|accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Tommy Walker (footballer, born 1915)|Tommy Walker]], Scottish [[association football]] player, [[inside forward]] for [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Midlothian]] and the [[Scotland national football team]] from 1933 to 1948, in [[Livingston, West Lothian]], [[Scotland]] (d. 1993)\n* '''Died:''' [[Julian Grenfell]], English poet and army officer, author of the poem \"Into Battle\" (b. 1888)\n\n== [[May 27]], 1915 (Thursday) ==\n* The [[General Assembly of the Ottoman Empire]] passed the [[Tehcir Law]] which authorized the deportation of the entire [[Armenians in the Ottoman Empire|Armenian]] populations in the Empire.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fakulteler.atauni.edu.tr/ermenia/mndty.php?al=3 |title=''Sevk ve \u0130sk\u00e2n Kanunu'' |publisher=Research Centre for Turkish\u2013Armenian Relations, [[Ataturk University]] |accessdate=April 25, 2010 |language=Turkish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090426035934/http://fakulteler.atauni.edu.tr/ermenia/mndty.php?al=3 |archivedate=April 26, 2009 }}</ref>\n* [[Urfa Resistance|Armenian resistance]] against the [[Ottoman Empire]] began to be organized in [[Urfa]], [[Turkey]].<ref>[[Guenter Lewy|Lewy, Guenter]]. ''[[The Armenian Massacres in Ottoman Turkey: A Disputed Genocide]]'', p. 201. Salt Lake City: [[Utah University Press]], 2005. {{ISBN|0-87480-849-9}}.</ref>\n* British minelayer {{HMS|Princess Irene}} exploded and sank while loading mines off [[Sheerness]] with the loss of 352 lives.<ref>{{cite book|first=Roy |last=Ingleton |title=Kent Disasters |year=2010 |publisher=Pen & Sword |location= Barnsley |page=50|ISBN=978-1-84563-116-1}}</ref>\n* British battleship {{HMS|Majestic|1895|6}} was torpedoed and sunk by German submarine {{SMU|U-21|Germany|6}} in the [[Dardanelles]] and sank with the loss of 49 of her 672 crew.<ref>Burt 1988, p. 131</ref>\n* British [[sloop]] [[HMS Veronica (1915)|HMS ''Veronica'']] was launched at [[Dunlop Bremner & Company]] in [[Port Glasgow]], [[Scotland]] and would serve with the [[New Zealand Division of the Royal Navy]]. The ship notably rescued hundred of survivors following the [[1931 Hawke's Bay earthquake]] in [[New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=McDougall|first1=R. J.|title=New Zealand Naval Vessels|date=1989|publisher=Government Printing Office|location=Wellington|isbn=978-0-477-01399-4|pages=18\u201319}}</ref>\n* The ''[[Alpenkorps (German Empire)|Alpenkorps]]'' were established in the [[German Army (German Empire)|Imperial German Army]] as an elite mountain fighting unit.<ref>''Histories of Two Hundred and Fifty-One Divisions of the German Army which Participated in the War (1914\u20131918), compiled from records of Intelligence section of the General Staff, American Expeditionary Forces, at General Headquarters, Chaumont, France 1919,'' (1920)</ref>\n* A resistance group formed in [[Urfa Resistance|Urfa]], [[Turkey]] (now \u015eanl\u0131urfa) in response to the deportation of Armenians.<ref>{{cite book | last = Kurdoghlian | first = Mihran | title = Badmoutioun Hayots, Volume III | publisher = Hradaragoutioun Azkayin Oussoumnagan Khorhourti |year= 1996 | location = Athens, Greece | pages = 93\u201395|language=hy}}</ref>\n* The first edition of ''Pioneer-News'' was published with the headline \"Status of the New Townsite\" referring to what was to become [[Anchorage, Alaska]]. The paper eventually became the ''[[Anchorage Times]]''.<ref>{{cite book  | last = Atwood  | first = Evangeline  | title = Anchorage: Star of the North  | publisher = Continental Heritage Press | date = 1982  | isbn = 0-932986-25-0  | page = 37 }}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Herman Wouk]], American writer, author of ''[[The Caine Mutiny]]'', ''[[The Winds of War]]'' and ''[[War and Remembrance]]'', in [[New York City]] (d. 2019)\n\n== [[May 28]], 1915 (Friday) ==\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 The French failed to capture [[Andres, Pas-de-Calais]], [[France]] from the Germans.<ref>The Times 1916, p. 226.</ref>\n* [[Battle for No.3 Post]] \u2013 Soldiers with [[New Zealand Mounted Rifles Brigade]] fought members of the [[19th Infantry Division (Ottoman Empire)|Ottoman 19th Infantry Division]] to capture a strategic defense post on the ridge overlooking [[ANZAC Cove]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Wilkie|first=A. H.|title=Official War History of the Wellington Mounted Rifles Regiment, 1914\u20131919|publisher=Whitcombe and Tombs|year=1924|location=Auckland|isbn=978-1-84342-796-4|page=27}}</ref>\n* [[1915 Sinhalese-Muslim riots|Riots]] began to break out between the ethnic [[Sinhalese people|Sinhalese]] and [[Sri Lankan Moors|Muslims]] in [[Kandy]], [[British Ceylon]] before spreading to [[Colombo]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Perera |first1=Edward Walter |title=Memorandum upon recent disturbances in Ceylon |url=https://archive.org/details/memorandumuponre00pererich |website=Archive.org |accessdate=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n* The [[Royal Flying Corps]] opened a [[RAF Narborough|military aerodrome]] at [[Norfolk]], [[England]].<ref>{{cite book |last= Jefford |first= C.G. |title= RAF Squadrons |year=1988 |publisher= Airlife Publishing Ltd |isbn= 1-85310-053-6|page=158}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Morton Smith]], American academic, most known for the discovery of the [[Mar Saba letter]] which allegedly contained references to the ''[[Secret Gospel of Mark]]'', in [[Philadelphia]] (d. [[1991]]); [[Joseph Greenberg]], American linguist, leading expert in African languages, in [[New York City]] (d. [[2001]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Yenovk Shahen]], Armenian stage actor celebrated in the [[Ottoman Empire]] for his performances in [[Victor Hugo]]'s ''[[Le roi s'amuse]]'', ''[[Othello]]'', and ''[[The Merchant of Venice]]'', murdered during the [[Armenian Genocide]] (b. [[1881]])\n\n== [[May 29]], 1915 (Saturday) ==\n* [[Manuel de Arriaga]] officially resigned as president of [[First Portuguese Republic|Portugal]], allowing Prime Minister [[Te\u00f3filo Braga]] to take over as the second president of the country.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Luz|first1=Jos\u00e9 Lu\u00eds Brand\u00e3o da|title=Te\u00f3filo Braga e o Liceu de Ponta Delgada: A Prop\u00f3sito de uma Carta aos seus Estudantes|journal=Insulana|date=2002|issue=58|pages=29\u201334|publisher=\u00d3rg\u00e3o do Instituto Cultural de Ponta Delgada|location=Ponta Delgada|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n* Ottoman troops attacked the [[15th Battalion (Australia)|15th Australian Battalion]] but were driven back, the last major offensive Ottoman forces would attempt during the [[Gallipoli campaign]].{{sfn|Broadbent|2005|pp=169\u2013170}}\n* [[Battle for No.3 Post]] \u2013 [[New Zealand]] forces successfully captured a key defense post overlooking [[ANZAC Cove]] and prepared to defend it from counterattacks by the Ottomans.<ref>Wilkie 1924, p. 27</ref>\n* British ocean liner {{SS|Merion||2}} was torpedoed and damaged in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] by German submarine [[SM UB-8|''UB-8'']] and sank two days later.<ref>{{cite web | last = Helgason | first = Gu\u00f0mundur | title = Ships hit during WWI: Merion | url = http://uboat.net/wwi/ships_hit/4093.html | work = U-Boat War in World War I | publisher = Uboat.net | date =  | accessdate = 3 March 2009 }}</ref>\n* British cruiser [[HMS Champion (1915)|HMS ''Champion'']] was launched by [[Hawthorn Leslie and Company]] in [[Tyneside]], [[England]]. It would participate in the [[Battle of Jutland]] the following year.<ref>Gardiner, Robert, ed., ''Conway's All the World's Fighting Ships, 1906\u20131921'', Annapolis, Maryland: Naval Institute Press, 1985, {{ISBN|0-87021-907-3}}, {{OCLC|423834653}}, {{LCCN|84042782 }}, p. 57, ([https://books.google.com/books?id=V2r_TBjR2TYC&pg=PA57 preview of 2006 reprint])</ref>\n* [[Goodall Park]] was opened for professional baseball in [[Sanford, Maine]] and is the current home for the ball team [[Sanford Mainers]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sullivan|first1=Shawn P.|title=Goodall Park at 100|url=http://www.fosters.com/article/20150603/NEWS/150609742|accessdate=26 February 2016|work=Sanford News|date=June 3, 2015}}</ref>\n* The city of [[Lake Alfred, Florida]] was established.<ref>{{cite web |title=Beginnings |url=http://mylakealfred.com/lake-alfred-profile/beginnings/ |website=My Lake Alfred |publisher=City of Lake Alfred |accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n* '''Died:''' [[John G. McCullough]], American politician, 49th [[Governor of Vermont]] (d. 1835)\n\n== [[May 30]], 1915 (Sunday) ==\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013 Eleventh German Army's artillery began to bombard forts around [[Przemy\u015bl]].<ref>DiNardo, 2010, p. 99.</ref>\n* [[Battle for No.3 Post]] \u2013 Ottoman forces successfully recaptured a key defense post from [[New Zealand]] forces, ending the battle with 200 casualties for the Ottomans and 104 wounded and 42 dead among the [[New Zealand Mounted Rifles Brigade]].<ref>Wilkie 1924, p. 33</ref>\n* U.S. President [[Woodrow Wilson]] dedicated the [[USS Maine Mast Memorial|memorial site]] honoring those who died during the sinking of the [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] cruiser [[USS Maine (ACR-1)|USS ''Maine'']] in 1898 in the [[Arlington National Cemetery]], [[Virginia]].<ref>\"Honors For Hero Dead.\" ''Washington Post.'' May 16, 1915</ref>\n* Shinano Railway extended the [[\u014cito Line]] in the [[Nagano Prefecture]], [[Japan]], with station [[Nakagaya Station|Nakagaya]] serving the line.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Shinano Mainichi Shimbun |title=Nagano Prefecture All Railway Stations, revised edition (\u9577\u91ce\u770c\u9244\u9053\u5168\u99c5 \u5897\u88dc\u6539\u8a02\u7248) |date=2011 |publisher=Shinano Mainichi Shinbun Publishing |isbn=9784784071647 |page=97|language=ja}}</ref>\n* A [[Helensburgh railway station|rail station]] was opened in [[Helensburgh, New South Wales]] to serve the [[South Coast railway line, New South Wales|South Coast line]] in [[Australia]].<ref>{{cite NSW SHR|5012054|Helensburgh Railway Station group|hr=01168|accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Pearl City (Boca Raton)|Pearl City]] was established near [[Boca Raton, Florida]] as a segregated neighborhood for African-American workers.<ref>Evans and Lee, (1990).  Pearl City, Florida: A Black Community Remembers.  Boca Raton: Florida Atlantic UP/UP of Florida.</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Henry Aaron Hill]], American chemist, first African American president of the [[American Chemical Society]], in [[St. Joseph, Missouri]] (d. [[1979 in science|1979]]); [[Jerome Wiesner]], American academic and engineer, chair of the [[President's Science Advisory Committee]] during the [[John F. Kennedy]] administration, president of [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] from 1971 to 1980, in [[Detroit]] (d. [[1994]])\n* '''Born:''' [[Ray Crowe]], American basketball coach, head of the [[Crispus Attucks High School]] basketball team from 1950 and 1957, [[Indiana High School Boys Basketball Tournament]] champion in 1955, the first time an all-black high school team won the [[Indiana]] state championship, in [[Franklin, Indiana]] (d. 2003); [[Martin Manulis]], American television producer, best known for the 1950s [[CBS|CBS Television]] specials ''[[Playhouse 90]]'' and ''[[Studio One (American TV series)|Studio One]]'', in [[New York City]] (d. [[2007]]); [[Exterminator (horse)|Exterminator]], American racehorse, winner of the [[1918 Kentucky Derby]], in [[Lexington, Kentucky]] (d. [[1945]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Marcelo Azc\u00e1rraga Palmero]], Spanish state leader, 13th [[Prime Minister of Spain]] (b. [[1832]])\n\n== [[May 31]], 1915 (Monday) ==\n* [[Defense of Van (1915)|Defense of Van]] \u2013 Russian general [[Nikolai Yudenich]] arrived in [[Van, Turkey]] and arranged for Armenian resistance leader [[Aram Manukian]] to become governor of the [[Occupation of Western Armenia|Armenian provisional government]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Hinterhoff | first = Eugene | title = Illustrated Encyclopedia of World War I | volume = iv. Persia: The Stepping Stone To India | publisher = Marshall Cavendish | year = 1984 | location = New York | isbn = 0-86307-181-3 |pages=1153\u201357}}</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 The Germans repulsed the French advance on [[Souchez]], [[France]] after six days of fighting.<ref>The Times 1916, pp. 225-226.</ref>\n* [[Battle of Amara]] \u2013 British Indian and Ottoman troops clashed in the marshes of the [[Tigris]] between the towns of [[Amarah|Amara]] and [[Al-Qurnah|Qurna]], [[Mesopotamia]] (now [[Iraq]]).<ref>Keogh, E.G. (1955) ''The River in the Desert'' p. 52-67. Melbourne, Wilke & Co. {{OCLC|12058974}}</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Garua]] \u2013 British and French colonial troops laid siege to German forts around [[Garoua|Garua]], [[German Cameroon]] (now [[Cameroon]]).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hilditch|first1=A. N.|title=Battle Sketches, 1914\u20131915|date=1915|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=39}}</ref>\n* The [[German Army (German Empire)|Imperial German Army]] carried out its first airship raid on [[London]] using the ''L38'' Zeppelin. It dropped {{convert|3000|lb|kg|disp=flip}} of bombs on the eastern suburb of the city, killing seven people and injuring 14.<ref>Robinson 1973, p. 103</ref><ref>{{cite book| last=Palmer| first=Alan| author2=Veronica| year=1992| title=The Chronology of British History| publisher=Century Ltd| location=London| pages=351\u2013352| isbn=0-7126-5616-2}}</ref>\n* The [[11th Indian Division]] was disbanded following the [[Raid on the Suez Canal]] and became primarily a defense force for the canal.<ref>{{cite book  | ref = harv  | last = Perry | first = F.W.  | year = 1993  | title = Order of Battle of Divisions Part 5B. Indian Army Divisions  | publisher = Ray Westlake Military Books  | location = Newport  | isbn = 1-871167-23-X|page=121}}</ref>\n* Italian race driver [[Ralph DePalma]] won the [[1915 Indianapolis 500|5th running]] of the [[Indianapolis 500]] at the [[Indianapolis Motor Speedway]] in a [[Mercedes (marque)|Mercedes 18/100]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Indianapolis 500 Historical Stats \u2013 1911\u20132015|url=https://www.indianapolismotorspeedway.com/events/indy500/history/historical-stats/race-stats/race-results/1915|website=Indianapolis Motor Speedway|publisher=IMS LLC|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Judith Wright]], Australian poet, known for her poetry collections such as ''Birds'', in [[Armidale, New South Wales]], [[Australia]] (d. [[2000 in poetry|2000]]); [[Jack Real]], American aerospace engineer, designer of many [[Lockheed Corporation|Lockheed]] aircraft, confidant to [[Howard Hughes]] from 1957 to the billionaire's death in 1976, in [[Calumet, Michigan]] (d. 2005); [[Carmen Herrera]], Cuban-American artist, member of the [[abstract expressionism]] in [[New York City]], in [[Havana]]\n* '''Died:''' [[Victor Child Villiers, 7th Earl of Jersey|Victor Child Villiers]], Australian statesman, 18th [[Governor of New South Wales]] (b. [[1845]])\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Events by month links}}\n\n[[Category:May|1915]]\n[[Category:1915|*1915-05]]\n[[Category:Months in the 1910s|*1915-05]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Month of 1915}}\n{{Events by month|1915}}\n{{calendar|year=1915|month=May}}\n[[File:Bundesarchiv DVM 10 Bild-23-61-17, Untergang der \"Lusitania\".jpg|thumb|right|350px|Painting depicting the [[Sinking of the RMS Lusitania|sinking of the RMS ''Lusitania'']] by German U-boat [[SM U-20 (Germany)|SM ''U-20'']].]]\n[[File:Van Defenders.jpg|thumb|350px|right|Armenian civilians holding a defense line against Ottoman forces in the Armenian walled city of [[Defense of Van (1915)|Van]] in May 1915.]]\n\nThe following events occurred in '''May 1915''':\n\n== [[May 1]], 1915 (Saturday) ==\n[[File:01915 Schwere deutsche Morser.jpg|right|300px|thumb|A German artillery piece used for bombardment during the [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] on the [[Eastern Front (World War I)|Eastern Front]].]]\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013 Combined German and Austro-Hungarian forces under command of General [[August von Mackensen]] [[Battle of Dunajetz|bombarded and attacked]] trenches held by the [[3rd Army (Russian Empire)|Russian Third Army]] along the [[Dunajec]] river in [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]] (now [[Poland]]), expending 70,000 shells over four hours before troops assaulted the trenches.<ref>{{cite book| last1=Stone| first1=Norman| title=The Eastern Front 1914\u20131917| url=https://archive.org/details/easternfront191400norm| url-access=registration| date=1998| publisher=Penguin| location=London| origyear=1971<!--|page=[https://archive.org/details/easternfront191400norm/page/104 104]-->| page=135}}</ref><ref>Tucker, Spencer, and Priscilla Roberts, eds. World War I: The Definitive Encyclopedia and Document Collection. Vol. 2. N.p.: ABC-CLIO, 2014. Print. {{ISBN|978-1851099641}}. {{OCLC|864676778}}, p. 512</ref>\n* [[Battle of Hill 60 (Western Front)|Battle of Hill 60]] \u2013 German forces launched a series of gas attacks to retake the [[Hill 60 (Ypres)|strategic hill]] on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] from the British.<ref>{{cite book |series=History of the Great War Based on Official Documents by Direction of the Historical Section of the Committee of Imperial Defence |title=Military Operations France and Belgium, 1915: Winter 1914\u20131915: Battle of Neuve Chapelle: Battles of Ypres |volume=I |last1=Edmonds |first1=J. E. |last2=Wynne |first2=G. C. |authorlink=|year=1995 |orig-year=1927 |publisher=Macmillan |location=London | edition=Imperial War Museum and Battery Press |isbn=0-89839-218-7 |pages=288\u201389}}</ref>\n* [[Eski Hissarlik|Battle of Eski Hissarlik]] \u2013 Ottoman forces counter-attacked during the night in an attempt to push [[Allies of World War I|Allied]] forces off their beachhead at Cape Helles during the [[Gallipoli campaign]]. However, Allied defenses were strong and well-prepared for night attacks and the Ottoman forces were repelled.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Duffy|first1=Michael|title=Battles \u2013 The Turkish Counter-attack at Eski Hissarlik, 1915|url=http://www.firstworldwar.com/battles/eskihissarlik.htm|website=First World War|publisher=Michael Duffy|accessdate=21 January 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Zaian War]] \u2013 French colonial forces crossed the [[Oum Er-Rbia River|Rbia River]] north of [[Khenifra]], [[Morocco]] to cut of food supplies reserved for the rebelling [[Zayanes]]. During the campaign, a French convoy was attacked by 5,000 tribesmen, but were repulsed with 300 killed and 400 wounded over a two-day battle. The battle lead to six months of relative calm in the region.<ref>{{Citation  | last = Hoisington| first = William A| title = Lyautey and the French Conquest of Morocco| place = New York| publisher = Macmillan (St Martin's Press)| year = 1995| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=iBn1PHEGGokC| doi =   | id =   | isbn = 978-0-312-12529-5 | page=82}}</ref>\n* French submarine {{ship|French submarine|Joule||2}} struck a mine and sank in the [[Dardanelles]] with the loss of all 31 of her crew.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naval-history.net/WW1NavyFrench.htm |title=French Navy |publisher=Naval History |accessdate=21 February 2013}}</ref>\n* British [[destroyer]] {{HMS|Recruit|1896|6}} was torpedoed and sunk in the [[North Sea]] by German submarine {{SMU|UB-6||6}} with the loss of 34 of her crew.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/wwi/ships_hit/7266.html |title=Recruit |publisher=Uboat.net |accessdate=28 October 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Royal Navy]] destroyers protecting naval trawlers [[Battle off Noordhinder Bank|fought]] off German torpedo boats at [[Noordhinder Bank]] in south part of the [[North Sea]], resulting in both torpedo boats being sunk with 13 German sailors killed and another 46 captured. Sixteen British sailors were lost in the attack.<ref>{{cite book |last=Karau |first=Mark |authorlink= |title=Wielding the Dagger |publisher=Praeger |year=2003|location=Westport, CT |isbn=0-313-32475-1|pages=48\u201355}}</ref>\n* British ocean liner [[RMS Lusitania|RMS ''Lusitania'']] departed [[Chelsea Piers#Pier 54|Pier 54]] in [[New York City]] on a return voyage back to [[Liverpool]] with 1,959 passengers and crew on board.<ref>Preston, D. (2003) ''Wilful Murder. The Sinking of the Lusitania''. London : Black Swan. {{ISBN|978-0552998864}}. pp. 132-33</ref>\n* The British [[War Office]] issued instructions specifying the aircraft and armament [[Royal Flying Corps]] [[Squadron (aviation)|squadrons]] were to have ready for defense of [[Great Britain]] against German airships, including having aircraft ready for immediate takeoff at all times, with a specific mix of weapons including bombs, grenades, and incendiary darts.<ref>Whitehouse, Arch, ''The Zeppelin Fighters'', New York: Ace Books, 1966, no ISBN, pp. 72-73.</ref>\n* American [[tanker (ship)|tanker]] ''[[Gulflight]]'' was torpedoed and damaged in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] {{convert|20|nmi|km}} west of the [[Isles of Scilly]] by German submarine {{SMU|U-30|Germany|6}} with the loss of three crew, becoming the first American ship to be attacked in [[World War I]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F70C13F83E5D16738DDDAB0994DD405B858DF1D3 |title=Gulflight attack as officially told  |accessdate= 20 Jan 2011 |newspaper=New York Times |date= 15 May 1915 |page=4}}</ref>\n* [[Ambrose Heal]] and others founded the [[Design and Industries Association]] in [[London]].<ref>[http://www.dia.org.uk/page/AboutUs/Nothing_Need_be_Ugly DIA website]</ref>\n* The first part of the [[Mandra\u2013Bhaun Railway]] opened in [[British Raj|British India]] (now [[Pakistan]]), connecting [[Mandra Junction railway station|Mandra]] with [[Bhaun]].<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/BombayBarodaAndCentralIndiaRailwaySystem/Bombay_Baroda_And_Central_India_Railway_System#page/n124/mode/2up  \" Administration Report on the Railways in India \u2013 corrected up to 31st March 1918\"; Superintendent of Government  Printing,  Calcutta;  page 116]; Retrieved 26 Jan 2016</ref>\n* Rail stations [[Bradley and Moxley railway station|Bradley and Moxley]] and [[Milton Road Halt railway station|Milton Road]] were closed as part of wartime measures in [[England]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Butt |first=R.V.J. |title=The Directory of Railway Stations |year=1995 |publisher=Patrick Stephens Ltd |location=Yeovil |isbn=1-85260-508-1 |id=R508 |page=42}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | first = R. W.| last = Kidner| authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 1985| month = | title = Southern Railway Halts. Survey and Gazetteer| chapter = | editor = | others = | edition = | pages = | publisher = The Oakwood Press| location = Headington, Oxford| isbn = 0-85361-321-4| page = 52 }}</ref>\n* The [[Barry Railway Company]] opened a [[Llandow Halt railway station|rail station]] in [[Llandow]], [[Wales]] to serve the [[South Wales]] line. It closed in 1964.<ref>Chapman, Colin (1998) ''The Vale of Glamorgan Railway'' The Oakwood Press, p. 61</ref> \n* Japanese chemical manufacturer [[Denka (company)|Denka]] was established in [[Tokyo]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Corporate Overview |url=https://www.denka.co.jp/eng/corporate/overview/ |website=Denka |accessdate=2 September 2019}}</ref>\n* Candy store chain [[Haigh's Chocolates]] was established when Alfred E. Haigh opened a chocolate store in [[Adelaide]], [[Australia]]. The shop became a chaing starting in the 1950s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.haighschocolates.com.au/about-us/our-history/ |title=Our company history |publisher=Haigh's Chocolates |accessdate=2007-09-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070829084027/http://haighschocolates.com.au/our_company/history.html |archivedate=2007-08-29 }}</ref>\n* The sports club [[SK Strong|Strong]] was established in [[Oslo]] for hockey, and became one of the founding members of [[GET-ligaen]], the premier Norwegian hockey league. It merged with two other clubs in 1952 to become [[Gr\u00fcner IL|Gr\u00fcner]].<ref>[http://www.grunerhockey.no/?page_id=77 Ishockey inntar Gr\u00fcnerl\u00f8kka]</ref>\n* The [[association football]] club [[SC Silvolde|Silvolde]] was established through a merger of two separate clubs in [[Silvolde]], [[Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The club history part 1 | url=https://www.sportclubsilvolde.nl/algemeen/historie?id=84 |website=Sports Club Silvolde |accessdate=2 September 2019 |language=Dutch}}</ref>\n* [[Frances Cornford]]'s ''Spring Morning'', the first modern book illustrated with [[wood engraving]]s by the poet's cousin [[Gwen Raverat]], was published by The [[Poetry Bookshop]] in [[London]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Balston|first=Thomas|title=Wood-engraving in Modern English Books|location=London|publisher=National Book League|year=1949}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Michael Dillon]], British physician, first [[trans man]] to undergo [[phalloplasty]] (d. [[1962]]); [[Ho\u00e0ng V\u0103n Th\u00e1i]], Vietnamese army officer, first [[General Staff of the Vietnam People's Army]], in [[Ti\u1ec1n H\u1ea3i District]], [[Vietnam]] (d. [[1986]]); [[Archie Williams]], American runner, gold medalist at the [[1936 Summer Olympics]], in [[Oakland, California]] (d. [[1993]])\n\n== [[May 2]], 1915 (Sunday) ==\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013 [[Grand Duke Nicholas Nikolaevich of Russia (1856\u20131929)|Grand Duke Nicholas Nicholaevitch]], supreme commander of the Russian Empire's armed forces, ordered fresh divisions to the Russian line as the [[Central Powers]] crossed the [[Wis\u0142oka|Wis\u0142oka River]] using a captured bridge.<ref>Richard L. DiNardo, Breakthrough: The Gorlice-Tarnow Campaign, 1915 (2010), p. 62, 75</ref>\n* The [[New Zealand and Australian Division]] launched an [[Battle for Baby 700|attack]] on a strategic hill in [[Gallipoli]] held by the [[19th Infantry Division (Ottoman Empire)|19th Infantry Division]] of the [[Military of the Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Army]], with support by the [[1st Royal Naval Brigade]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Bean|first=Charles|authorlink=Charles Bean|title=The Story of ANZAC from the Outbreak of War to the End of the First Phase of the Gallipoli Campaign, May 4, 1915 |url=https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/C1416845 |series=Official History of Australia in the War of 1914\u20131918 |volume=Volume I|edition=11th|year=1941a|publisher=Angus & Robertson|location=Sydney|oclc=220878987|pages=587\u2013594}}</ref>\n* Norwegian cargo ship {{SS|America|1914|2}} was sunk in the [[North Sea]] off [[Bergen]], [[Norway]] by German submarine {{SMU|U-41|Germany|6}}. Her 39 crew were rescued by another Norwegian ship.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/wwi/ships_hit/246.html |title=America |publisher=Uboat.net |accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n* The [[1915 Copa del Rey Final|Copa Del Rey Final]] was played in front of 5,000 spectators at [[Estadio de Amute]] in [[Hondarribia]], [[Spain]]. [[Athletic Bilbao]] beat [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]] 5-0 to win their 6th [[Copa del Rey]] (Spanish Cup).<ref>{{cite web|title=Athletic Club \u2013 Honours|url=http://www.athletic-club.eus/en/honours.html|website=Athletic Club|publisher=Athletic Club|accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref>\n* '''Died:''' [[Clara Immerwahr]], German chemist and women's rights activist, first woman to be awarded a doctorate in chemistry, wife to [[Fritz Haber]] (b. [[1870]]); [[David Dalhoff Neal]], American artist, best known for his portraits of historic figures including ''[[Oliver Cromwell]] of Ely Visits Mr. [[John Milton]]'' (b. [[1838]])\n\n== [[May 3]], 1915 (Monday) ==\n[[File:John McCrae in uniform circa 1914.jpg|right|200px|thumb|Canadian army officer [[John McCrae]], author of \"[[In Flanders Fields]]\".]]\n* Italy officially revoked the [[Triple Alliance (1914)|Triple Alliance]]. In the following days, Italian statesman [[Giovanni Giolitti]] led the neutralist majority of the Italian Parliament in opposing a war declaration, while nationalist crowds demonstrated in public areas for entering the war.<ref>Hamilton, Richard F; Herwig, Holger H. Decisions for War, 1914\u20131917. pp. 194-198</ref>\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013 Russian forces retreated from [[Gorlice]] as German and Austro-Hungarian troops crossed the [[Dunajec]] River north of [[Krak\u00f3w]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Austro-German forces drive Russians out of the Carpathians|url=http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/austro-german-forces-drive-russians-out-of-the-carpathians|website=History Channel|publisher=A+E Networks|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref>\n* Combined Australian, New Zealand and British forces did not sufficient reinforcements to [[Battle for Baby 700|hold onto a strategic hill]] in [[Gallipoli]], resulting in their withdraw at a cost of close to 1,000 casualties.<ref>Bean 1941a, p. 597</ref>\n* The [[RAF Northolt]] station began operating in [[South Ruislip]], [[London]], [[England]]. It remains the longest, continuously used air station by the [[Royal Air Force]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bristow|first1=Mark|title=A History of Royal Air Force Northolt|date=2005|publisher=No. 1 AIDU|location=RAF Northolt|pages=13\u201316}}</ref>\n* The first [[Zeppelin P Class]] airship of the [[German Army (German Empire)|Imperial German Army]] - the ''L38'' - took flight for raids on [[England]].<ref>Robinson, Douglas H., ''Giants in the Sky'' Henley-on Thames: Foulis, 1973 {{ISBN|0-85429-145-8}}, p, 103</ref>\n* While on patrol over the [[North Sea]], a German Navy Zeppelin encountered and attacked four British [[submarine]]s on the surface, however, all subs were able to escape by diving.<ref>Whitehouse 1966, pp. 97-98.</ref>\n* The [[101st Infantry Division (German Empire)|101st]] and [[103rd Infantry Division (German Empire)|103rd Infantry Divisions]] of the [[Imperial German Army]] were established.<ref>[http://www.1914-18.info/erster-weltkrieg.php?u=201 101. Infanterie-Division (Chronik 1915/1918)]</ref>\n* Swedish [[coastal defence ship]] [[HSwMS Sverige|''Sverige'']] was launched by [[G\u00f6taverken]] in [[Gothenburg]], [[Sweden]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Warship 1992|editor=Gardiner, Robert|publisher=Naval Institute Press|location=London|year=1992|isbn=0-85177-603-5|chapter=The Svierge Class Coastal Defense Ships|pages=80\u201398|last=Harris|first=Daniel G.}}</ref>\n* Canadian medical soldier [[John McCrae]] wrote the poem \"[[In Flanders Fields]]\", after presiding over the funeral of a friend and fellow soldier who died in the [[Second Battle of Ypres]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Prescott|first1=John F.|title=In Flanders Fields: The Story of John McCrae|date=1985|publisher=Boston Mills Press|location=Erin, Ontario|isbn=0-919783-07-4|page=96}}</ref>\n* Home team [[Bethlehem Steel F.C. (1907\u20131930)|Bethlehem Steel]] beat [[Brooklyn Celtic]] 3-1 at the second annual [[U.S. Open Cup]] at Taylor Field, [[Lehigh University]] in [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]] before a crowd of 7,000 spectators.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Litterer |first1=Dave |last2=Goloboy |first2=Jim |title=Final Details 1914\u20131947 \u2013 USA \u2013 List of US Open Cup Finals |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesu/usacuphist.html#det |website=RSSSF |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |accessdate=30 May 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vDj5rMKE?url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesu/usacuphist.html |archivedate=24 December 2010 }}</ref>\n* The borough [[Bradford Woods, Pennsylvania]] was incorporated.<ref>{{cite web| url =http://www.phmc.state.pa.us/bah/dam/counties/pdfs/Allegheny.pdf | title = Allegheny County \u2013 2nd Class | accessdate = 2007-10-08}}</ref>\n*  U.S. steamer ''Undine'' arrived in [[Lewiston, Idaho]] from [[Portland, Oregon]] as part of the inaugural cruise for the newly built [[Celilo Canal]] that connected two points of the [[Columbia River]]. The canal was in operation until 1957 when [[The Dalles Dam]] was completed.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Dana|first=Marshall N.|title=The Celebration of the Open Columbia|journal=The Quarterly of the Oregon Historical Society|date=1 June 1915|volume=16|url=https://archive.org/stream/jstor-20609994/20609994#page/n2/mode/1up|accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Stu Hart]], Canadian wrestler, founder of [[Stampede Wrestling]], patriarch of the [[Hart wrestling family]], in [[Saskatoon]], [[Saskatchewan]] (d. [[2003]])\n\n== [[May 4]], 1915 (Tuesday) ==\n* [[Los Angeles]] held a [[1915 Los Angeles mayoral election|mayoral election]], with [[Charles E. Sebastian]] elected to become the city's [[Mayor of Los Angeles|30th mayor]]. Sebastian received over 28,000 votes, or 39 per cent of the polls.<ref>{{cite web| title=Los Angeles Mayor \u2013 Primary| url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=568427| publisher=Our Campaigns}}</ref>\n\n== [[May 5]], 1915 (Wednesday) ==\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013 The [[3rd Army (Russian Empire)|Russian Third Army]] began to collapse, allowing German forces to break through and capture 140,000 enemy soldiers and 100 guns.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rickard|first1=J.|title=Battle of Gorlice-Tarnow, 2-10 May 1915|url=http://www.historyofwar.org/articles/battles_gorlice_tarnow.html|website=History of War|date=20 August 2007|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Battle of Hill 60 (Western Front)|Battle of Hill 60]] \u2013 British forces held off German gas attacks for four days but a renewed attack on the fifth day resulted in the gas following the front line as opposed to crossing it, allowing more British troops to be overcome. This allowed German infantry of the 30th Division to advance and capture the front line on the lower slope of the [[Hill 60 (Ypres)|hill]].{{sfn|Edmonds|Wynne|1927|p=305}}\n* German submarine ''[[SM U-20 (Germany)|U-20]]'' sunk a British merchant [[schooner]], the ''Earl of Lathom'', off the southern coast of [[Ireland]] after stopping it and ordering the crew off the ship.<ref>{{cite book|last=Molony|first=Senan|title=Lusitania, an Irish Tragedy|year=2004|publisher=Mercier Press|location=Cork|isbn=978-1-85635-452-3|page=8}}</ref>\n* The [[Royal Navy]] issued an uncoded warning to all British commercial ships that German [[U-boat]]s were seen active of the south coast of [[Ireland]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Room 40: British Naval Intelligence, 1914\u20131918 |last=Beesly |first=Patrick |year=1982 |publisher=Hamish Hamilton Ltd |location=Long Acre, London |isbn=0-241-10864-0|page=103}}</ref>\n* The British 125th brigade of the [[42nd (East Lancashire) Infantry Division|42nd Infantry Division]] arrived at [[Gallipoli]] to reinforce [[ANZAC Cove]], allowing [[Australian and New Zealand Army Corps|ANZAC]] forces to prepare for a second assault on the village of [[Second Battle of Krithia|Krithia]] the following day.<ref>{{cite book |last=Broadbent |first= Harvey |year=2005 |title=Gallipoli: The Fatal Shore |publisher=Viking/Penguin |location= Camberwell, Victoria |isbn= 0-670-04085-1|page=134}}</ref>\n* The [[105th Infantry Division (German Empire)|105th Infantry Division]] of the [[German Army (German Empire)|Imperial German Army]] was established.<ref>[http://www.1914-18.info/erster-weltkrieg.php?u=201 101. Infanterie-Division (Chronik 1915/1918)]</ref>\n* [[St. John's College, Nugegoda|St. John's College]] was established in [[Nugegoda]], [[British Ceylon]] as the first English-language school in the country.<ref>{{cite web| title=About St. John's College| url=http://www.stjohnscollege.lk/about.html| website=St. John's College| publisher=St. John's College| accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref>\n* The all-girls public school [[Samudradevi Balika Vidyalaya]] was established in [[Nugegoda]], [[British Ceylon]].<ref>{{cite news|title=St.John's, Nugegoda celebrates centenary|url=http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=132176|accessdate=21 June 2017| newspaper=[[The Island (Sri Lanka)]]|date=21 September 2015}}</ref>\n* The [[association football]] organization [[Federa\u00e7\u00e3o Mineira de Futebol]] was established to manage football clubs in [[Minas Gerais]], [[Brazil]] and represent the clubs at the [[Brazilian Football Confederation]].\n* '''Born:''' [[Alice Faye]], American singer and actress, best known for the [[Academy Awards|Oscar-winning]] song \"[[You'll Never Know]]\" in the film ''[[Hello, Frisco, Hello]]'', in [[New York City]] (d. [[1998]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Ronald Poulton]], English rugby player, centre for the [[England national rugby union team]] from 1909 to 1914, and [[Oxford University RFC|Oxford University]] from 1908 to 1911 (killed by a sniper near [[Ploegsteert]], [[Belgium]]) (b. [[1889]])\n\n== [[May 6]], 1915 (Thursday) ==\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013 Russian forces abandoned the city of [[Tarn\u00f3w]], [[Poland]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Austro-German forces drive Russians out of the Carpathians|url=http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/austro-german-forces-drive-russians-out-of-the-carpathians|website=History Channel|publisher=A+E Networks|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Krithia]] \u2013 British, Australian and New Zealand forces launched an assault on Ottoman defenses on the Helles battlefield during the [[Gallipoli campaign]] but failed to advance further than 400 yards (370 metres).<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bean|first1=Charles|title=The Story of ANZAC from 4 May 1915, to the Evacuation of the Gallipoli Peninsula|journal=Official History of Australia in the War of 1914\u20131918|date=1941|volume=II|issue=1926|pages=18\u201319|publisher=Australian War Memorial|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory|oclc=220051990}}</ref>\n* The [[Imperial Russian Army]] launched a major offensive on [[Anatolia]] and also threatened [[Van, Turkey]].<ref>{{cite book| first=Edward |last=Erickson |title=[[Ordered to Die: A History of the Ottoman Army in the First World War]] |location=Westport, Connecticut |publisher=Greenwood Publishing |year=2001a |origyear=2000 |isbn=0-313-31516-7 |page=109}}</ref>\n* After receiving messages that a German [[U-boat]] sunk British merchant ship ''Candidate'' and nearly sunk the British ocean liner [[SS Arabic (1902)|''Arabic'']], Captain [[William Thomas Turner]] of the {{RMS|Lusitania}} ordered the crew to make emergency preparations in case the ship was attacked and had to be abandoned, although passengers were not informed.<ref>Preston 2003, p. 197</ref>\n* German submarine ''[[SM U-20 (Germany)|U-20]]'' fired a torpedo at British steamer ''Cayo Romano'' from [[Cuba]], even though it was flying a neutral flag, off the southern coast of [[Ireland]] narrowly missing by a few feet.<ref>Molony 2004, p. 8</ref>\n* [[Ross Sea party]] \u2013 A fierce winter storm unmoored the polar ship ''[[SY Aurora|Aurora]]'' at [[McMurdo Sound]] in the [[Antarctic]], causing her to drift. On board were 18 men including first officer [[Joseph Stenhouse]] while another 10 were marooned onshore; the six members involved in the sledge parties that were setting up supply depots for the main [[Imperial Trans-Antarctic Expedition]], including expedition commander [[Aeneas Mackintosh]], were stranded in [[Hut Point Peninsula|Hut Point]] and four members scientists that were camped at [[Cape Evans]].<ref>{{cite book | authorlink = Kelly Tyler-Lewis | last = Tyler-Lewis | first = Kelly | title = The Lost Men | publisher = Bloomsbury Publications | year = 2007 | location = London | isbn = 978-0-7475-7972-4|page=129}}</ref>\n* Baseball player [[Babe Ruth]] hit his first career home run off pitcher [[Jack Warhop]] for the [[Boston Red Sox]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Creamer|first1=Robert W.|title=Babe: The Legend Comes to Life|date=1974|publisher=Simon & Schuster|location=New York|isbn=0-671-76070-X|page=[https://archive.org/details/babelegendcomest00crea_0/page/106 106]|edition=First Fireside 1992|url=https://archive.org/details/babelegendcomest00crea_0/page/106}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Orson Welles]], American actor and director, directed and produced ''[[Citizen Kane]]'', considered by most film critics as one of the [[list of films considered the best|all-time greatest films]], as well as acclaimed films ''[[The Magnificent Ambersons]]'' and ''[[Touch of Evil]]'', and roles in ''[[The Third Man]]'' and ''[[Catch-22 (film)|Catch-22]]'',  in [[Kenosha, Wisconsin]] (d. [[1985]])\n\n== [[May 7]], 1915 (Friday) ==\n[[File:Track of Lusitania.jpg|thumb|right|450px|Painting by [[William Lionel Wyllie]] depicting casualties and survivors in the water and in lifeboats following the [[Sinking of the RMS Lusitania|sinking of the RMS ''Lusitania'']].]]\n* British [[ocean liner]] [[sinking of the RMS Lusitania|RMS ''Lusitania'']] was sunk by [[Imperial German Navy]] [[U-boat]] ''[[SM U-20 (Germany)|U-20]]'' off the south-west coast of [[Ireland]], killing 1,198 civilians en route from [[New York City]] to [[Liverpool]].<ref>Preston 2003 pp. 216-17</ref> Among the notable passengers who died during the sinking included:\n** [[Thomas O'Brien Butler]], Irish composer (b. [[1861 in Ireland|1861]])\n** [[Marie Depage]], Belgian nurse (b. [[1872 in science|1872]])\n** [[Justus Miles Forman]], American writer (b. [[1875]])\n** [[Charles Frohman]], American theater producer (b. [[1856]])\n** [[Elbert Hubbard]], American writer and philosopher (b. [[1856]])\n** [[Alice Moore Hubbard]], wife of [[Elbert Hubbard]] (b. [[1861]])\n** [[Hugh Lane]], Irish art dealer, collector and benefactor (b. [[1875 in art|1875]])\n** [[Charles Klein]], American playwright (b. [[1867]])\n** [[Basil Maturin]], Irish preacher (b. [[1847]])\n** [[Frederick Stark Pearson]], American engineer (b. [[1861]])\n** [[Alfred Gwynne Vanderbilt]], American sportsman (b. [[1877]])\n** [[Lothrop Withington]], American historian (b. 1856)\n* [[1915 Danish Folketing election|Parliamentary elections]] were held in [[Denmark]] but, because of [[World War I]], no campaigning took place and 104 out of 114 constituencies did not vote. Even so, ruling Danish political party [[Venstre (Denmark)|Venstre]] retained majority of the 114 seats in the [[Folketing|Danish Parliament]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Hatting|first=J\u00f8rgen|editor=Fabricius, K. |editor2=Frisch, H. |editor3=Hjelholt, H. |editor4=Mackeprang, M. |editor5=M\u00f8ller, A. |title=Den Danske Rigsdag 1849\u20131949 bind III \u2013 Rigsdagen og folket|year=1950|publisher=J. H. Schultz Forlag|location=Copenhagen|language=Danish|chapter=Valgdeltagelsen efter 1866|page=119}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Elklit|first=J\u00f8rgen|editor=Elklit, J\u00f8rgen |editor2=Tonsgaard, Ole |title=Valg og v\u00e6lgeradf\u00e6rd \u2013 Studier i dansk politik|chapter=Det klassiske danske partisystem bliver til|year=1984|publisher=Forlaget Politica|location=\u00c5rhus|language=Danish|isbn=87-7335-058-3|page=34}}</ref>\n* [[Battle of Hill 60 (Western Front)|Battle of Hill 60]] \u2013 Two British infantry companies failed to recapture the [[Hill 60 (Ypres)|hill]] from the Germans, officially ending the battle. In all, the British [[5th Infantry Division (United Kingdom)|5th Infantry Division]] assigned to take Hill 60 had 3,100 casualties.{{sfn|Edmonds|Wynne|1927|p=306}}\n* The Sanuki Railway Company extended the Yosan Line in the [[Kagawa Prefecture]], [[Japan]], with station [[Tsushimanomiya Station|Tsushimanomiya]] serving the line.<ref>{{cite book |script-title=ja: \u505c\u8eca\u5834\u5909\u9077\u5927\u8f9e\u5178 \u56fd\u9244\u30fbJR\u7de8|trans-title=Station Transition Directory - JNR/JR| publisher = JTB | editor1-last = Ishino| editor1-first = Tetsu| year = 1998 | location = Japan |language= Japanese | volume = II| page = 633| isbn = 4-533-02980-9}}</ref>\n* '''Died:''' [[Edward Frederick Robert Bage]], Australian explorer, member of the [[Australasian Antarctic Expedition]] in 1911 to 1914, recipient of the [[Polar Medal]], killed during the [[Gallipoli campaign]] (b. [[1888]])\n\n== [[May 8]], 1915 (Saturday) ==\n* Pressured by its inability to mobilize for war, [[China]] accepted a revision of the [[Twenty-One Demands]] made by [[Japan]].<ref>{{cite web| last1=Duffy| first1=Michael| title='21 Demands' Made by Japan to China, 18 January 1915| url=http://www.firstworldwar.com/source/21demands.htm| website=First World War| publisher=Michael Duffy| accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Ypres]] \u2013 German forces bombarded and attacked Canadian forces defending the forward line of the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] at the Frezenberg ridge over five days.{{sfn|Edmonds|Wynne|1927|p=310}}\n* [[Second Battle of Krithia]] \u2013 New Zealand relieved the British forces who barely made it 800 yards (740 metres) towards the Ottoman line. The New Zealand pushed to gain another 400 yards (370 metres) before being pinned down. By evening, they launched a new attack backed by Australian support. They were able to capture a portion of the front trenches on one of the flanks but they were pushed back everywhere else, thus ending the battle.<ref>Bean, 1941, pp. 18-19</ref>\n* [[Bernhard Dernburg]], former secretary for the [[Imperial Colonial Office]] of [[Germany]], stated the [[Sinking of the RMS Lusitania|sinking of the RMS ''Lusitania'']] was justified as the ship \"carried contraband of war\" and \"was classed as an auxiliary cruiser\".<ref>{{Cite news | author-link =  | last2 =  | first2 =  | author2-link =  | title = Sinking Justified, Says Dr. Dernburg; Lusitania a \"War Vessel,\" Known to be Carrying Contraband, Hence Search Was Not Necessary. |work=New York Times | page = 4 | date = 9 May 1915 | url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1915/05/09/301791392.pdf | format=PDF}}</ref>\n* [[Armenian Genocide]] \u2013 Around 220 Armenians intellectuals arrested on April 24 were separated and sent to holding centres in [[\u00c7ank\u0131r\u0131]] and [[Aya\u015f, Ankara|Aya\u015f]], [[Turkey]].<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=Raymond K\u00e9vorkian|first=Raymond|last=K\u00e9vorkian|title=Le G\u00e9nocide des Arm\u00e9niens [The Armenian Genocide]|language=fr|publisher=Odile Jacob|location=Paris|year=2006|isbn=978-2-7381-1830-1|page=318}}</ref>\n* [[Ross Sea party]] \u2013 The polar ship ''[[SY Aurora|Aurora]]'' was adrift in the ice and moving into the [[Ross Sea]] away from the [[Antarctic]] continent.<ref>{{cite book | last = Haddelsey | first = Stephen | title = Ice Captain | publisher = The History Press | location = Stroud, Gloucestershire | year = 2008 | isbn = 0-7509-4348-3|pages=53\u201357}}</ref>\n* Thoroughbred racehorse [[Regret (horse)|Regret]] with jockey [[Joe Notter]] won the [[1915 Kentucky Derby|41st running]] of the [[Kentucky Derby]] with a time of 2:05.40. Regret was the first [[filly]] ever to win the Derby,  causing [[Churchill Downs]] president [[Matt Winn]] to observe that because of Regret's win \"the Derby was thus made an American institution.\"<ref>Bolus, Jim.  ''Kentucky Derby Stories''.  Pelican Publishing Company.  Gretna, LA, 1993, p. 74</ref>\n* The [[Kew tram depot]] in [[Kew, Victoria]], [[Australia]] began operations to serve the [[Melbourne]] area.<ref>{{cite web|title=The early days|url=http://www.yarratrams.com.au/about-us/our-history/tramway-milestones/the-early-days/|work=[[Yarra Trams]]|accessdate=7 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318134537/http://www.yarratrams.com.au/about-us/our-history/tramway-milestones/the-early-days/|archive-date=18 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Kew Tram Depot celebrates 100 years|url=http://www.yarratrams.com.au/media-centre/news/articles/2015/kew-tram-depot-celebrates-100-years/|publisher=Yarra Trams|accessdate=3 May 2015}}</ref>\n* '''Died:''' [[Henry McNeal Turner]], American religious leader, 12th [[Bishop]] for the [[African Methodist Episcopal Church]] (b. [[1834]])\n\n== [[May 9]], 1915 (Sunday) ==\n[[File:Die erbitterten K\u00e4mpfe um Lorettoh\u00f6he (PK Martin Herpich M\u00fcnchen 1915 TPk132).jpg|thumb|350px|French and German soldiers fight at the opening of the [[Second Battle of Artois]].]]\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013  [[Grand Duke Nicholas Nikolaevich of Russia (1856\u20131929)|Grand Duke Nicholas]] permitted a limited withdrawal as Austro-Hungarian Third and Fourth Armies pressed forward in the [[Carpathian Mountains]].<ref>DiNardo, 2010, p. 75.</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 The French Tenth Army launched a major offensive against the Germans in the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] in northeastern [[France]], capturing a few front line trenches and taking 3,000 Germans prisoner along with 10 field guns and 15 machine guns. However, no successes were made capturing any major villages or towns.<ref>{{cite book |title=Early Trench Tactics in the French Army: the Second Battle of Artois, May\u2013June 1915 |last=Krause |first=J. |authorlink= |year=2013 |publisher=Ashgate |location=Farnham |edition=1st |isbn=1-4094-5500-9|pages=69\u201373}}</ref>\n* [[Battle of Aubers Ridge]] \u2013 The [[First Army (United Kingdom)|British First Army]] launched a simultaneous attack on the German line north of the French Tenth Army to widen the enemy's defensive gap but failed to break through.<ref>{{cite book|series=History of the Great War Based on Official Documents By Direction of the Historical Section of the Committee of Imperial Defence |title=Military Operations France and Belgium, 1915: Battles of Aubers Ridge, Festubert, and Loos |volume=II |last=Edmonds |first=J. E. |authorlink=James Edward Edmonds |year=1928 |publisher=Macmillan |location=London |edition=1st |oclc=58962526 |pages=14\u201315}}</ref>\n* The German government released an official statement confirming an [[Imperial German Navy]] [[u-boat]] had [[Sinking of the RMS Lusitania|sunk the RMS ''Lusitania'']] but maintained the ship was armed and was transporting \"war materials\".<ref>{{cite book | last = Halsey  | first = Francis Whiting | title = The Literary Digest History of the World War | url = https://archive.org/details/literarydigesthi00hals  | publisher = Funk & Wagnalls | year = 1919 | page = [https://archive.org/details/literarydigesthi00hals/page/255 255]}}</ref> However, the [[Port of New York and New Jersey|Port of New York]] issued an official denial of Germany's charges, saying the ship had been inspected and had not been outfitted with any guns nor it was carrying any munitions aside from some ammo for small firearms, a common practice among cargo shipping.<ref>{{Cite news | author-link =  | last2 =  | first2 =  | author2-link =  | title = Lusitania was unarmed | newspaper = [[New York Times]] | date = 10 May 1915 | url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1915/05/10/104646600.pdf | format=PDF}}</ref>\n* '''Died:''' [[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]], Luxembourgian cyclist, first foreigner to win the [[Tour de France]] in 1909, killed at the [[Second Battle of Artois]] (b. [[1887]]); [[Anthony Wilding]], New Zealand tennis player, bronze medalist at the [[1912 Summer Olympics]] and triple World Championship winner in 1913, killed at the [[Battle of Aubers Ridge]] (b. [[1883]])\n\n== [[May 10]], 1915 (Monday) ==\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 The French launched a feint attack as a decoy while new cavalry divisions were moved in to assist the Tenth Army. Meanwhile, Germany launched a counter-attacked and recaptured some of their trenches and tunnels between the villages of [[Carency]] and [[Souchez]],{{sfn|The Times|1916|p=219}} and repulsed an attack at [[Neuville-Vitasse]].{{sfn|Krause|2013|pp=74\u201377}}\n* [[Action of 10 May 1915]] \u2013 The Ottoman battleship [[SMS Goeben|''Yavuz Sultan Selim'']], formerly the [[SMS Goeben|SMS ''Goeben'']], tried to intercept Russian naval ships [[Russian battleship Tri Sviatitelia|''Tri Sviatitelia'']] and [[Russian battleship Potemkin|'' Panteleimon'']] sighted earlier by an Ottoman destroyer in the [[Black Sea]]. Instead, it mistakenly ran into a Russian naval squadron that included [[Russian battleship Evstafi|''Evstafi'']], [[Russian battleship Ioann Zlatoust|''Ioann Zlatoust'']], and [[Russian battleship Rostislav|''Rostislav'']]. The ''Yavuz Sultan Selim'' exchanges fire with the squadron for 15 minutes but, outnumbered, it backed off and escaped.<ref>{{cite book| last = Noppen| first = Ryan K.| title = Ottoman Navy Warships 1914\u201318| publisher = Bloomsbury Publishing| date = 20 July 2015| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=G7edCwAAQBAJ&dq=&source=gbs_navlinks_s| isbn = 978-1-4728-0620-8}}</ref>\n* An [[German Army (German Empire)|Imperial German Army]] [[Zeppelin]] attempted to bomb [[Southend-on-Sea]], [[England]] but was driven off by unexpected gunfire. On retreat, airship commander Erich Linnarz allegedly scrawled a threat to return on a calling card from his wallet and dropping it in a weighted canister found on [[Canvey Island]].<ref>Whitehouse 1966, pp. 80-81.</ref>\n* [[William Thomas Turner]], surviving captain of the {{RMS|Lusitania}}, gave initial evidence of the [[Sinking of the RMS Lusitania|sinking]] to authorities, including testimony a German torpedo struck the ship between the third and fourth funnels.<ref>Preston 2003, pp. 330-32</ref>\n* U.S. President [[Woodrow Wilson]] countered public demands for the [[United States]] to declare war on [[Germany]] for the [[sinking of the RMS Lusitania|sinking of the RMS ''Lusitania'']], stating while in [[Philadelphia]], \"There is such a thing as a nation being so right that it does not need to convince others by force that it is right.\"<ref>{{cite book| last = Jones| first = Howard| title = Crucible of Power: A History of U.S. Foreign Relations Since 1897| year = 2001| publisher = Rowman & Littlefield| isbn = 978-0-8420-2918-6| page = [https://archive.org/details/crucibleofpower00jone/page/73 73]| url = https://archive.org/details/crucibleofpower00jone/page/73}}</ref>\n* Lieutenant [[Denys Corbett Wilson]] of the [[Royal Flying Corps]] died after being shot down while flying a [[Morane-Saulnier L|Morane-Saulnier airplane]] on a reconnaissance mission over France.<ref>{{cite news| title= Ireland's Roll of Honour: Losses in Irish Regiments: Officers Killed| newspaper= Irish Times| location= Dublin| date= 29 May 1915| page= 6}}</ref>\n* The [[Escadrille SPA.57]] of the [[French Air Force]] was established near [[Arras]], [[France]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Franks|first1=Norman|last2=Bailey|first2=Frank W.|title=Over the Front: A Complete Record of the Fighter Aces and Units of the United States and French Air Services, 1914\u20131918|date=1992|publisher=Grub Street|isbn=0-948817-54-2|page=94}}</ref>\n* The first edition of the El Salvadoran daily newspaper ''[[La Prensa Gr\u00e1fica]]'' was published.<ref>See [http://www.cis-elsalvador.org/May-June2004.pdf Centro de Intercambio y Solidaridad, Bulletin, May/June 2004.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071025054541/http://www.cis-elsalvador.org/May-June2004.pdf |date=2007-10-25 }}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Denis Thatcher]], British businessman, husband of UK Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]], in [[London]] (d. 2003); [[Beyers Naud\u00e9]], South African theologian and activist, founder of the [[Christian Institute of Southern Africa]], in [[Roodepoort]], [[Transvaal (province)|Transvaal]], [[South Africa]] (d. [[2004]]); [[Anthony Peraino]], American mobster, member of the [[Colombo crime family]] who financed the pornographic hit ''[[Deep Throat (film)|Deep Throat]]'', in [[New York City]] (d. [[1996]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Gaston Cros]], French archaeologist and army officer, commander of French forces during the [[Zaian War]], lead the archeological dig of the ancient city of [[Girsu]] in [[Mesopotamia]] (now [[Iraq]]), recipient of the [[Legion of Honour]], [[Order of the Dragon of Annam]], ''[[Ordre des Palmes acad\u00e9miques]]'', and ''[[Croix de guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)|Croix de guerre]]'' (killed in action during the [[Second Battle of Artois]] (b. 1861)\n\n== [[May 11]], 1915 (Tuesday) ==\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 French forces captured key high ground from the Germans, depriving them of strategic viewing points of the battlefield.{{sfn|The Times|1916|p=219-222}}{{sfn|Krause|2013|pp=77\u201381}}\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013 Russian forces regrouped and gun in at the [[San (river)|San River]] in what is now southeastern [[Poland]] to slow the [[Central Powers]] advance.<ref>Wren, Jack. ''The Great Battles of World War I''. New York: Grosset & Dunlap, 1971. Print. {{OCLC| 2779383}} {{ISBN|9780448020372}}, p. 116</ref> \n* The [[Royal Flying Corps]] established the [[No. 18 Squadron RAF|No. 18 Squadron]] at [[RAF Northolt]] in [[London Borough of Hillingdon]], [[England]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rawlings|first1=J. D. R.|title=History of No. 18 Squadron|journal=Air Pictorial|date=September 1964|volume=26|issue=9|pages=288\u2013290}}</ref>\n* [[Royal Navy]] [[seaplane tender]] {{HMS|Ben-my-Chree}} tried to intercept a German [[airship]] in the [[North Sea]] using a [[Sopwith Aviation Company|Sopwith]] seaplane. However, the launching platform collapsed as the plane tried to take off, leaving the Zeppelin to go on and bomb four surfaced British submarines (without damaging them).<ref>Whitehouse 1966, p. 98</ref>\n* The Egyptian-Armenian daily newspaper ''[[Arev (daily)|Arev]]'' published its first issue.<ref>[http://ramgavar.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=509%3Aenger-eugene-papazian-by-ara-aharonian&catid=56%3Aramgavar-mamoul&Itemid=27&lang=am Ramgavar.org: \u053e\u0576\u0576\u0564\u0565\u0561\u0576 125-\u0561\u0574\u0565\u0561\u056f - \u0538\u0576\u056f\u0565\u0580 \u0537\u0585\u056a\u0567\u0576 \u0532\u0561\u0562\u0561\u0566\u0565\u0561\u0576] (in Armenian)</ref>\n* The [[Boston Opera Company]] declared bankruptcy.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Eaton|first1=Quaintance|title=The Boston Opera Company| date=1965}}</ref>\n\n== [[May 12]], 1915 (Wednesday) ==\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013 General [[August von Mackensen]] was ordered to advance his forces to the [[San (river)|San]] River and take bridgeheads on the east bank.<ref>DiNardo, 2010, p. 99</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 French forces renewed offenses against the German line, capturing 3,000 enemy troops in the process.{{sfn|The Times|1916|p=222}}\n* British battleship {{HMS|Goliath|1898|6}} was torpedoed and sunk by [[Ottoman destroyer Muavenet-i Milliye|Ottoman destroyer ''Mu\u00e2venet-i Mill\u00eeye'']] in the [[Dardanelles]] with the loss of 570 of her 700 crew.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Burt|first1=R. A.|title=British Battleships 1889\u20131904|date=1988|publisher=Naval Institute Press|location=Annapolis, Maryland|isbn=0-87021-061-0|pages=158\u201359}}</ref>\n* [[Defense of Van (1915)|Defense of Van]] \u2013 Ottoman forces failed to slow the Russian advance at the town of Ardjish north of [[Van, Turkey]].<ref>Verzhine Svazlyan, Armenian massacres, 1915\u20131923, p. 43</ref>\n* South African troops occupied [[Windhoek]], the capital of [[German South West Africa]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Tucker|first=Spencer|title=World War I: encyclopedia|year=2005|publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]]|isbn=1-85109-420-2|page=42}}</ref>\n* [[Tobias Norris]] became premier of [[Manitoba]], replacing [[Rodmond Roblin]] who was forced to resign from office after a commission appointed by the [[Lieutenant Governor of Manitoba]] found the government guilty of corruption in the tending of contracts for new legislative buildings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mhs.mb.ca/docs/features/timelinks/reference/db0011.shtml |title=Legislature Scandal |work=TimeLinks |publisher=Manitoba Historical Society |accessdate=2012-11-29}}</ref>\n* [[James Bryce, 1st Viscount Bryce|James Bryce]] of the [[Committee on Alleged German Outrages]] released a report detailing a mix of confirmed and unsubstantiated reports of atrocities allegedly committed by [[Germany]] during the first months of [[World War I]]. The report was widely accepted and translated into 30 languages.<ref>{{Cite journal | last =| first =| author-link =| last2 =| first2 =| author2-link =| title = The Bryce Report on German Atrocities | journal = [[Literary Digest]] | volume = 50 | issue = 22 | pages =  | date = 29 May 1915 | url =  | doi =  | id = | postscript =}}</ref>\n* The [[2nd Air Refueling Squadron|2nd Aero Squadron]] of the [[United States Army]] was formed.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hennessey |first=Juliette |year=1958 |url=http://www.afhra.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-090602-017.pdf |title=The United States Army Air Arm, April 1861 to April 1917 |work=USAF Historical Study No. 98 |publisher=AFHRA (USAF) |pages=151\u2013152 |accessdate=4 Dec 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722182357/http://www.afhra.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-090602-017.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-22 }}</ref>\n* [[Ross Sea party]] \u2013 While continuing to drift northward in the ice, the crew of the polar ship ''[[SY Aurora|Aurora]]'' managed to set up a temporary wireless aerial and communicate to the stranded members on shore at [[Cape Evans]] but communications failed to get through.<ref>Tyler-Lewis 2007, p. 199</ref>\n* The South African media company [[Naspers]] started out as a newspaper and magazine publisher founded by [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]] leader [[J. B. M. Hertzog]] in [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.naspers.com/our-history.html | title=Naspers website: Our history | publisher=Naspers | work=Company history | accessdate=15 March 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320141659/http://www.naspers.com/our-history.html | archive-date=20 March 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://medialternatives.com/2011/11/15/media-inc-the-story-of-naspers-media24-and-channel-life/ | title=Apartheid Inc, the story of Naspers, Media24 and Channel Life | publisher=Media Alternatives | date=15 November 2011 | accessdate=15 March 2015}}</ref>\n* The [[association football]] club [[Nex\u00f8 Boldklub Bornholm|Nex\u00f8]] was established in [[Nex\u00f8]], [[Denmark]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Club Info - History |url=http://live-10017-klubprojekt-18.umbraco-proxy.com/klubben/klubinfo/historie/ |website=Nex\u00f8 Boldklub Bornholm |accessdate=2 September 2019 |language=Danish}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Brother Roger]], Swiss religious leader, founder of the [[Taiz\u00e9 Community]], in [[Provence, Switzerland]] (d. [[2005]])\n* '''Died:''' [[William H. Forwood]], American army medical officer, 19th [[Surgeon General of the United States Army]] (b. 1838)\n\n== [[May 13]], 1915 (Thursday) ==\n* Italian Prime Minister [[Antonio Salandra]] offered his resignation in the face of growing public opposition of entering [[World War I]] in accordance with the [[Treaty of London (1915)|Treaty of London]], but opposition leader [[Giovanni Giolitti]], fearful of nationalist disorder that might break into open rebellion, declined to succeed him.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Clark|first1=Martin|title=Modern Italy: 1871 to the present|date=2008|publisher=Pearson Education|location=Harlow|isbn=1-4058-2352-6|page=217}}</ref>\n* U.S. President [[Woodrow Wilson]] sent [[Germany]] the first of three letters related to the [[Sinking of the RMS Lusitania|sinking of the RMS ''Lusitania'']] calling for [[Germany]] to abandon submarine warfare against commercial vessels.<ref>{{cite book| last = Zieger| first = Robert H.| title = America's Great War| year = 1972| publisher = Rowman & Littlefield| isbn = 978-0-8476-9645-1| pages = 24\u201325 }}</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Ypres]] \u2013 Canadian forces prevented the forward line at Frezenberg ridge from falling into German hands but suffered massive casualties. In particular, the [[Princess Patricia's Canadian Light Infantry]] saw its 700-man force reduced to 150 men when the battle ended. As a result, the unit's unofficial motto \u2013 \"Holding up the whole damn line\" \u2013 is still used today.{{sfn|Edmonds|Wynne|1927|pp=311\u2013326}}\n* British officer Captain [[Julian Grenfell]] was mortally wounded by shrapnel when a shell landed a few yards away from where he was standing while talking to fellow officers of the [[1st The Royal Dragoons]]. He was taken to a hospital in [[Boulogne-sur-Mer|Boulogne]], [[France]] where he died thirteen days later. His poem \"Into Battle\" was published in ''[[The Times]]'' the day after his death.<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=Nicholas Mosley|last=Mosley|first=Nicholas|year=1976|title=Julian Grenfell: His Life and the Times of his Death 1888\u20131915|location=London|publisher=Weidenfeld & Nicolson|isbn=0-297-77093-4}}</ref> His younger brother Gerald William (Billy) Grenfell was killed in action two months later.\n* In the facing of growing [[anti-German sentiment]] in [[Australia]] following the [[sinking of the RMS Lusitania|sinking of the Lusitania]], the [[German Club, Sydney|German Club in Sydney]] notified the [[List of Commissioners of New South Wales Police|Commissioner of New South Wales Police]] that it was the club's intention to voluntarily close given the heightened threat of damage and violence against Australians with German heritage.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article15579146 |title=GERMAN CLUBS. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |location=NSW |date=14 May 1915 |accessdate=16 December 2015 |page=8 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n* The Kyoto Dent\u014d Company extended the [[Katsuyama Eiheiji Line]] in the [[Fukui Prefecture]], [[Japan]], with station [[Oiwakeguchi Station|Oiwakeguchi]] serving the line.<ref>[http://www57.tok2.com/home/tram/echizen.html History of Katsuyama Eiheiji Line]</ref>\n\n== [[May 14]], 1915 (Friday) ==\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 French forces captured the village of [[Carency]] but stopped from advancing on [[Souchez]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Doughty |first=R. A. |title=Pyrrhic Victory: French Strategy and Operations in the Great War |location=Cambridge, MA |publisher=Belknap Press |year=2005 |isbn=0-674-01880-X|page=161}}</ref>\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013 The [[Central Powers]] forces reached the [[San (river)|San River]] in what is now southeastern [[Poland]].<ref>Wren 1971, p. 116</ref>\n* [[May 14 Revolt]] \u2013 A mutinous group of naval marines, army soldiers, and members of the [[National Republican Guard (Portugal)|National Republican Guard of Portugal]] took control of several naval ships in [[Lisbon]] harbor, including the [[Portuguese ironclad Vasco da Gama|battleship ''Vasco da Game'']], in a revolt against the presidency of [[Manuel de Arriaga]]. The resulting insurrection between soldiers, sailors, police and civilians resulted in 200 deaths and over 1,000 injuries.<ref>{{cite book|first=Jo\u00e3o Ant\u00f3nio|last=Correia dos Santos|title=Subs\u00eddios para a Hist\u00f3ria Pol\u00edtica e Militar da Revolu\u00e7\u00e3o de 14 de Maio de 1915|location=Lisbon, Portugal|publisher=Tipografia da Cooperativa Militar|year=1915|trans-title=Papers on a History of the Revolution of 14th May, 1915|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n* The first local of the [[Fraternal Order of Police]] was established in [[Pittsburgh]].<ref>\"[http://www.fop.net/about/history/index.shtml History] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924090042/http://www.fop.net/about/history/index.shtml |date=2008-09-24 }}.\" Fraternal Order of Police.</ref>\n* The [[Mille Lacs National Wildlife Refuge]] was established in central [[Minnesota]] to protecting breeding spaces for various bird species, and is the smallest [[National Wildlife Refuge]] in the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mile Lacs \u2013 About the Refuge| url=http://www.fws.gov/refuge/Mille_Lacs/about.html|website=U.S. Fish and Wildlife|publisher=U.S. Fish and Wildlife Services}}</ref>\n\n== [[May 15]], 1915 (Saturday) ==\n* [[Battle of Festubert]] \u2013 The [[First Army (United Kingdom)|British First Army]] under command of General [[Douglas Haig, 1st Earl Haig|Douglas Haig]] launched a night-time attack on a {{convert|3|mi|km|adj=on}} portion of the German line from [[Neuve-Chapelle]], [[France]] in the north to the village of [[Festubert]] in the south.{{sfn|Edmonds|1928|pp=49\u201352}}\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 The Germans halted any further French advances into their territory.{{sfn|The Times|1916|p=223}}\n* [[1915 Singapore Mutiny|Singapore Mutiny]] \u2013 The court of inquiry into a mutiny among the Indian [[5th Light Infantry]] in [[Singapore]] concluded causes for it were inconclusively established. More than 200 Indian soldiers and officer were tried and 47 were sentenced to execution by firing squad. The remaining 600 Indian soldiers and officers that did not mutiny were ordered to serve with [[Allies of World War I|Allied]] operations in [[Africa]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Sareen | first = T.R. | title = Secret Documents on Singapore Mutiny 1915 | publisher = New Delhi: Mounto Publishing House | year = 1995 | isbn = 81-7451-009-5 | page = Report Section II}}</ref>\n* The [[1915 Far Eastern Championship Games|second]] [[Far Eastern Championship Games]] were held in [[Shanghai]] with [[China]], [[Japan]] and the [[Philippines]] participating.<ref>Bell, Daniel (2003). ''Encyclopedia of International Games''. McFarland and Company, Inc. Publishers, Jefferson, North Carolina. {{ISBN|0-7864-1026-4}}.</ref>\n* The first reference of [[jazz]] in relation to music may have come from [[Tom Brown (trombonist)|Tom Brown]] and his [[New Orleans]] band as they began performing in [[Chicago]] and started advertising themselves as a \"Jass Band\".<ref>[http://www.redhotjazz.com/browns.html Tom Brown's Band from Dixie Land] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303202853/http://www.redhotjazz.com/browns.html |date=2016-03-03 }}. Accessed 17 April 2013.</ref>\n* ''[[The Gourock Times]]'' weekly newspaper began publishing in [[Gourock]], [[Scotland]]. It would fold in 1980.<ref>{{cite book|title=Newspaper Press Directory|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K57oAAAAMAAJ|year=1928|publisher=Benn Brothers}}</ref>\n* The [[association football]] club [[Real Uni\u00f3n]] was established in [[Irun]], [[Spain]].<ref>{{cite web |title=A little history about the club | url=https://www.realunionclub.com/historia |website=Real Uni\u00f3n |accessdate=13 September 2019 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Hilda Bernstein]], British-American writer and activist, author of ''[[The World That Was Ours]]'', in [[London]] (d. [[2006]]); [[Paul Samuelson]], American economist, recipient of the [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences]], author of ''[[Foundations of Economic Analysis]]'', in [[Gary, Indiana]] (d. [[2009]]); [[Shozo Makino (swimmer)|Shozo Makino]], Japanese swimmer, silver medalist at the [[1932 Summer Olympics]] and bronze medalist at the [[1936 Summer Olympics]], in [[Shizuoka Prefecture]], [[Japan]] (d. [[1987]])\n\n== [[May 16]], 1915 (Sunday) ==\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013 The [[Central Powers]] established bridgeheads over the [[San (river)|San]] River and prepared to assault [[Przemy\u015bl]] and the 44 forts that surrounded it.<ref>DiNardo, 2010, p. 99.</ref>\n* [[Defense of Van (1915)|Defense of Van]] \u2013 While evacuating women and children in [[Van, Turkey]] by way of port ships under cover of artillery fire, Ottoman soldiers massacred 6,000 Armenians.<ref>\"6000 Armenians Killed.\" ''New York Times''. London. 17 May 1915, reproduced in: ''The Armenian Genocide.'' Ed. Richard Diran Kloian. 1980. p. 17</ref>\n* [[Battle of Festubert]] \u2013 Renewed attacks on the German line only resulted in heavy losses for the British.{{sfn|Edmonds|1928|pp=59\u201373}}\n* Two [[Royal Naval Air Service]] planes intercepted two [[Imperial German Navy]] [[Zeppelin]]s, badly damaging one using bombs dropped on its envelope from above.<ref>Thetford, Owen, ''British Naval Aircraft Since 1912'', 6th ed., Annapolis, Maryland: Naval Institute Press, 1991, {{ISBN|1-55750-076-2}}, p. 33.</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Percy Charles Pickard]], British air force officer, commander of the [[No. 51 Squadron RAF|No. 51]] and [[No. 161 Squadron RAF|No. 161 Squadron]] during [[World War II]], recipient of the [[Distinguished Service Order]], [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]], and [[Czechoslovak War Cross 1939\u20131945|Czechoslovak War Cross]], in [[Handsworth, South Yorkshire]], [[England]] (d. [[1944]], killed in action)\n\n== [[May 17]], 1915 (Monday) ==\n[[File:RussianTroops Van1915.jpg|thumb|250px|Russian and Armenian relief forces arrive in [[Defense of Van (1915)|Van]].]]\n* The last purely [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] government in [[Great Britain]] ended when the prime minister [[H. H. Asquith]] formed an all-party [[coalition government]], in response to a cabinet split caused by fallout from the [[Shell Crisis of 1915|Shell Crisis]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Fraser|first1=Peter|title=The British 'Shells Scandal' of 1915|journal=Canadian Journal of History|date=1983|volume=1|issue=18|pages=77\u201394}}</ref>\n* [[Defense of Van (1915)|Defense of Van]] \u2013 Governor [[Djevdet Bey]] of the [[Van Province]] abandoned [[Van, Turkey]] and joined the [[1st Expeditionary Force (Ottoman Empire)|1st Expeditionary Force]] under the command of [[lieutenant colonel|Lieutenant Colonel]] [[Halil Kut]], leaving the city in temporary control of the Armenian militia.<ref>[[Ali \u0130hsan S\u00e2bis]], ''Birinci D\u00fcnya Harbi'', 2. cilt, Nehir Yay\u0131nlar\u0131, {{ISBN|975-551-067-2}}, p. 437. {{in lang|tr}}</ref>\n* [[Germany]] released a [[The German White Book|White Book]] that refuted the claims of German war-time atrocities made in a report by the [[Committee on Alleged German Outrages]] five days earlier while outline their reasons to going to war against the [[Triple Entente]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/pathways/firstworldwar/document_packs/p_whitebook.htm| title=German White Book|publisher=The National Archives| location=United Kingdom| accessdate=23 January 2017}}</ref>\n* Italian-American mob boss [[Giosue Gallucci]], head of one of the [[Camorra in New York City|Camorra gangs]] in [[New York City]], was shot along with his son Lucas in a coffee shop in [[East Harlem]]. His son died the next day and Gallucci died from his wounds fours days later. His murder created a power vacuum among the crime families, resulting in the [[Mafia\u2013Camorra War]] the following year.<ref>{{cite book| last1=Downey|first1=Patrick|title=Gangster City: The History of the New York Underworld, 1900\u20131935|date=2004|publisher=Barricade Books| location=Fort Lee, NJ|isbn=978-1-56980-361-5|pages=85\u201386}}</ref>\n\n== [[May 18]], 1915 (Tuesday) ==\n* [[Battle of Festubert]] \u2013 The [[1st Canadian Division]] was mobilized to attack the German line with support from a British division but failed to progress against enemy artillery.{{sfn|Edmonds|1928|pp=73\u201377}}\n* British submarine [[HMS E11|HMS ''E11'']] infiltrated Turkish waters past the [[Dardanelles]].<ref>{{cite book |last=O'Connell |first=John |title=Submarine Operational Effectiveness in the 20th Century: Part One (1900\u20131939) |year=2010 |location=New York |publisher=Universe |isbn=1-4502-3689-8|page=74}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Pitt |first1=Barrie |last2=Young|first2=Peter |title=History of the First World War|volume=3|year=1970 |location=London |publisher=B.P.C. Publishing |oclc=669723700|page=918}}</ref>\n* The [[4th Guards Infantry Division (German Empire)|4th Guards Infantry Division]] of the [[Imperial German Army]] was established.<ref>[http://www.1914-18.info/erster-weltkrieg.php?u=126 4. Garde-Infanterie-Division (Chronik 1915/1918)]</ref>\n* The [[Belgium]] monarchy created a civilian variant of the [[Civic Decoration]] medal for Belgian civilians and non-combatants that served with distinction during [[World War I]].<ref>{{cite web  | authorlink = Belgian government | title = Royal Decree of 18 May 1915 creating the Civic Decoration 1914\u20131915 | publisher = Belgian Government | date = 1915-05-18  }}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Neil W. Chamberlain]], American economist, known for his concepts on [[bargaining power]], in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]] (d. [[2006]])\n* '''Died:''' [[William Bridges (general)|William Bridges]], Australian army officer, commander of the [[1st Division (Australia)|1st Australian Division]] during the [[Gallipoli campaign]], succumbed to injuries sustained from sniper fire (b. [[1861]]); [[Amos W. Barber]], American politician, second [[List of governors of Wyoming|Governor of Wyoming]] (b. [[1861]])\n\n== [[May 19]], 1915 (Wednesday) ==\n[[File:Assault of Ottoman soldiers.jpg|thumb|250px|Turkish troops attacking during the [[Gallipoli campaign]].]]\n* [[Gallipoli campaign]] \u2013 The Ottoman army launched a [[third attack on Anzac Cove]] with 42,000 soldiers but were repelled by the 17,000 [[Australian and New Zealand Army Corps|ANZAC]] troops. Ottoman forces sustained 13,000 casualties including 3,000 killed, while [[Australian and New Zealand Army Corps|ANZAC]] forces had 468 wounded and 160 killed.<ref>Erickson 2001a, p. 87</ref> Among the noted casualties was Australian army medic [[John Simpson Kirkpatrick]], who innovated the use of mules as stretchers for transporting wounded across the rugged terrain.<ref>[http://www.anzacs.net/Simpson.htm ANZACS.net: Simpson \u2013 Australia's favourite hero] (''c.'' 2010). Retrieved on 19 June 2010.</ref><ref>[http://www.awm.gov.au/exhibitions/dawn/boat/simpson.asp Australian War Memorial: Simpson and his donkey] (2010). Retrieved on 18 June 2010.</ref><ref>[http://www.awm.gov.au/research/people/roll_of_honour/person.asp?p=484810 Australian War Memorial: Roll of Honour \u2013 John Simpson Kirkpatrick] (2010). Retrieved on 18 June 2010.</ref>\n* [[May 14 Revolt]] \u2013 After the revolt among the Portuguese military had been quelled, [[Manuel de Arriaga]] announced his decision to resign as [[President of Portugal]].<ref>*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PkH9wfKMqHwC&pg=PR11&dq=portugal+first+republic&hl=en&ei=5PU8TOWfHpCG4gaHjaj0CQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCwQ6AEwAA#v=snippet&q=pimenta%20de%20castro&f=false|first=Douglas L.|last=Wheeler|title=Republican Portugal: A Political History 1910\u20131926| publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|location=Madison, Wisconsin|isbn=0-299-07450-1|page=124}}</ref>\n* The [[Grosvenor Picture Palace]] opened in [[Manchester]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://manchesterhistory.net/manchester/tours/tour8/area8Apage23.html | title=The Grosvenor Picture Palace | accessdate=29 March 2015}}</ref>\n* The [[Shire of Mundubbera]] was established in [[Queensland]], [[Australia]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article20032100 |title=LOCAL GOVERNMENT. |newspaper=[[The Brisbane Courier]] |date=21 May 1915 |accessdate=23 September 2013 |page=9 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Ren\u00e9e Asherson]], British actress, known for Shakespearean stage performances with [[The Old Vic]], [[Liverpool Playhouse]], [[Westminster Theatre]], and films roles such as ''[[The Way Forward]]'', in [[London]] (d. [[2014]])\n\n== [[May 20]], 1915 (Thursday) ==\n* [[Battle of Festubert]] \u2013 A renewed British offensive started to yield success against the Germans, but it would take five more days of fighting before the French village of Festubert was captured.{{sfn|Edmonds|1928|p=76}}\n* [[Defense of Van (1915)|Defense of Van]] \u2013 Russian forces entered [[Van, Turkey]], providing needed relief for Armenians resisting the onslaught of Ottoman troops.<ref>{{Cite book | editor1-last = Reynolds | editor1-first = Joseph Francis | editor2-first = Allen Leon | editor2-last = Churchill | editor3-first = Francis Trevelyan | editor3-last = Miller | year = 1916 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=410PAAAAYAAJ | title = The Story of the Great War: History of the European War from Official Sources; Complete Historical Records of Events to Date | volume = 3 | publisher = P.F. Collier & Son| page=478}}</ref>\n* [[Cleveland Railway (Ohio)|Cleveland Railway]] opened the [[Courtland station|Courtyard]] and [[Eaton station|Eaton]] stations to serve the Shaker Boulevard rail line in [[Cleveland]].<ref>{{cite book  | last = Toman  | first = James  | authorlink =  | coauthors =  | title = The Shaker Heights Rapid Transit  | publisher = Interurban Press  | date = 1990  | location = Glendale, Calif.  | pages = 17\u201318 | url =  | doi =  | isbn = 0-916374-95-5 }}</ref>\n* The [[Tucum\u00e1n Lawn Tennis Club]] was formed in [[San Miguel de Tucum\u00e1n]], [[Argentina]]. Initially offering tennis and cricket, it was since expanded into a multi-sports club with its [[rugby union]] Tucum\u00e1n LT being its flagship team.<ref>{{cite web|title=Historia \u2013 Institucional|url=http://www.tucumanlawntennis.org.ar/historia/institucional|website=Tucum\u00e1n Lawn Tennis Club|publisher=Tucum\u00e1n Lawn Tennis Club|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n* The sports club [[APGS Amsterdam|Amsterdam]] was formed in [[Amsterdam]] which included rugby, badminton, and even basketball.<ref>[http://apgs-amsterdam.nl/vereniging/organisatie/ APGS organisation]</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Moshe Dayan]], Israeli military leader and politician, commander during the [[1948 Arab\u2013Israeli War]], [[Chief of the General Staff (Israel)|chief of staff]] of the [[Israel Defense Forces]] during the [[Suez Crisis]], and Defense Minister during the [[Six-Day War]] in 1967, in [[Kibbutz]], [[Ottoman Syria]] (d. [[1981]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Charles Francis Adams Jr.]], American rail executive, president of the [[Union Pacific Railroad]] from 1884 to 1890 (b. [[1835]])\n\n== [[May 21]], 1915 (Friday) ==\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 [[France]] consolidated their forces while under heavy German fire but lost key positions.<ref>Doughty 2005, p. 162.</ref>\n* Armenian leader [[Krikor Zohrab]] and another fellow deputy with the Ottoman Parliament were arrested and ordered to [[Aleppo]] to be held while awaiting court-martial, follow the leader's public protests of atrocities committed against Armenians from April 24. He would be murdered in July during the height of the [[Armenian Genocide]].<ref>\u00dcng\u00f6r, U\u011fur, ''The Making of Modern Turkey: Nation and State in Eastern Anatolia, 1913\u20131950''. Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2011, p. 84.</ref>\n* The [[SPAD S.A]] aircraft was first flown in [[France]], but its design proved challenging for most pilots and was replaced soon after.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bruce|first=J.M.|title=SPAD S.A-2/S.A-4|series=Windsock Mini Datafile 4|publisher=Albatros Publications|location=Hertfordshire, UK|year=1996|isbn=978-0948414824|pages=3\u20135}}</ref>\n\n== [[May 22]], 1915 (Saturday) ==\n[[File:QuintinshillILN1.jpg|thumb|250px|A burning carriage in the aftermath of a [[Quintinshill rail disaster|train collision at Quintinshill]], [[Scotland]].]]\n* A [[Quintinshill rail disaster|rail collision and fire in Quintinshill]], [[Scotland]] killed 226 people, most of them troops, in what was the largest number of fatalities in a [[List of rail accidents in the United Kingdom|rail accident in Great Britain]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rolt|first1=L. T. C.|last2=Kichenside|first2=G. M.|title=Red for Danger: A history of railway accidents and railway safety|date=1982|publisher=David & Charles|location=Newton Abbot, Devon|isbn=0-7153-8362-0|pages=207\u2013213|edition=4th}}</ref>\n* [[Lassen Peak]], one of the [[Cascade Volcanoes]] in [[California]], erupted sending an ash plume 30,000 feet in the air and devastating the nearby area with mudslides and hot gas clouds mixed with debris. It is the last volcano to erupt in the contiguous United States until the [[1980 eruption of Mount St. Helens]].<ref name=\"Eruptions of Lassen Peak\">{{cite web | url = http://pubs.usgs.gov/fs/1998/fs173-98/ | title = Eruptions of Lassen Peak, California, 1914 to 1917 | work = U.S. Geological Survey Fact Sheet 173-98 | publisher = [[United States Geological Survey|USGS]] | accessdate = August 23, 2012 }}</ref>\n* [[T. J. Ryan]] was [[1915 Queensland state election|elected]] [[Premier of Queensland]] in [[Australia]], defeating incumbent [[Digby Denham]] with 52% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.uwa.edu.au/elecdetail.lasso?keyvalue=776|title=Parliament of Queensland, Assembly election, 22 May 1915|author=Australian Government and Politics Database|accessdate=14 January 2009}}</ref>\n* Thoroughbred racehorse Tartarean ridden by jockey [[Harry Watts (jockey)|Harry Watts]] won the 56th running of [[Canada]]'s [[Queen's Plate|King's Plate]] race with time of 2:09.20.<ref>{{cite book|title=Morning Telegraph's Racing Chart Book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ciEPAAAAYAAJ|volume=34|year=1915|page=46|oclc=669176445}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title=Chester Krum Good Thing in the Chase| url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=22&dat=19150526&id=eR8BAAAAIBAJ&sjid=bCgDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3204,1144756| newspaper=The Toronto World| date=May 26, 1915| accessdate=November 26, 2013}}</ref>\n* The Italian [[Futurist]] magazine ''[[Lacerba]]'' published its last issue after a brief two-year run in [[Florence]].<ref>{{cite book| author=Alan Bartram| title=Futurist Typography and the Liberated Text|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jRC5KvV7EgEC&pg=PA117| accessdate=18 June 2015| year=2005| publisher=Yale University Press| isbn=0-300-11432-X|page=117}}</ref>\n\n== [[May 23]], 1915 (Sunday) ==\n[[File:Vonmuecke.JPG|right|150px|thumb|German naval officer [[Hellmuth von M\u00fccke]], first officer of the [[SMS Emden|SMS ''Emden'']].]]\n[[Image:Otto Parschau's A-16-15 Eindecker.jpg|thumb|right|150px|The model of the first Fokker Eindecker fighter plane flew by [[Otto Parschau]].]]\n* [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]] joined the [[Allies of World War I|Allies]] after they declared war on [[Austria-Hungary]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Duffy|first1=Michael|title=Who Declared War and When|url=http://www.firstworldwar.com/features/declarationsofwar.htm|website=First World War|accessdate=21 January 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Faisal I of Iraq|Faisal bin Hussein]] received the [[Damascus Protocol]] document while visiting the city during a diplomatic mission to [[Constantinople]]. Authored by Arab secret societies, the document outlined an Arab revolt against the [[Ottoman Empire]] with support of the British, resulting in an independent Arab nation state.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Herzog|first1=Jacob David|title=A People That Dwells Alone: Speeches and Writings of Yaacov Herzog|date=1975|publisher=Weidenfeld and Nicolson|page=213}}</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 French forces began to take ground from the Germans as they advanced of [[Souchez]].<ref>Krause 2013, pp. 106\u2013109</ref>\n* German submarine {{SMU|UB-3||6}} was lost in the [[Gulf of \u0130zmir]] {{convert|80|nmi|km}} off [[\u0130zmir]] with the loss of all fourteen crew.<ref>{{cite book | last = Messimer | first = Dwight R. | title = Verschollen: World War I U-boat losses | location = Annapolis, Maryland | publisher = Naval Institute Press | year = 2002 | pages=126\u201327 | isbn = 978-1-55750-475-3 | oclc = 231973419}}</ref>\n* The [[Austro-Hungarian Navy]] began [[Bombardment of Ancona|bombarding]] the port of [[Ancona]], [[Italy]] soon after the country declared war on the [[Central Powers]].<ref>{{cite book  |last1=Sondhaus  |first1=Lawrence  |title=The Naval Policy of Austria-Hungary, 1867-1918: Navalism, Industrial Development, and the Politics of Dualism  |date=1994  |publisher=Purdue University Press  |location=West Lafayette, IN  |isbn=1-55753-034-3| pages=266\u2013270}}</ref>\n* [[Hellmuth von M\u00fccke]], first officer of the [[SMS Emden|SMS ''Emden'']], safely led 48 members of his surviving landing party to [[Constantinople]] where he reported to the German admiral stationed there. From the time they were stranded on the [[Cocos (Keeling) Islands|Cocos Islands]] in the [[Indian Ocean]] to their arrival in the Ottoman capital, von M\u00fccke had successfully led his men 11,000&nbsp;km over sea and land, losing only four on the way. He and his men arrived in [[Germany]] later that summer as heroes.<ref>{{cite book| last1=Carlton| first1=Mike| title=First Victory: 1914| date=2013| publisher=William Heinemann| location=Australia| isbn=1-74275-763-4| pages=333\u201334}}</ref>\n* German pilot [[Otto Parschau]] flew the first of the [[Fokker Eindecker fighters]], designed by [[Anthony Fokker]], in [[Douai]], [[France]]. The aircraft's high maneuverability, combined with [[synchronization gear]] that allowed fighter pilots to fire mounted machine gun bullets between the plane's propellers, gave German air superiority over the [[Allies of World War I|Allies]] for most of 1915 and 1916, to the point the fighters were referred to as [[Fokker Scourge]].<ref>Dierikx, Marc. ''Fokker: A Transatlantic Biography''. Washington, DC: Smithsonian Institution Press, 1997. {{ISBN|1-56098-735-9}}, p. 31</ref>\n* The sports club [[\u00c4lvsj\u00f6 AIK|\u00c4lvsj\u00f6]] was established in [[Stockholm]]. Initially the club included [[association football]], [[bandy]], [[hockey]] and [[floorball]]. In 1993, [[association football]] separated and became its own club.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.sportnik.com/group/2882/page/histria |title= \u00c4lvsj\u00f6 AIK FF \u2013 Historia |format= |work= |accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref>\n* German noble [[Heinrich XXVII, Prince Reuss Younger Line|Prince Heinrich]] established the [[War Merit Cross (Reuss)|War Merit Cross]] to be awarded to all ranks for exemplary conduct in combat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ehrenzeichen-orden.de/deutsche-staaten/kriegsverdienstkreuz-1915-steckkreuz.html |title=Kriegsverdienstkreuz 1915 (Steckkreuz) |publisher=Ehrenzeichen-orden.de |date= |accessdate=2013-07-30}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[S. Donald Stookey]], American inventor, patented 60 inventions related to ceramics or glass, including FotoForm which is used by [[CorningWare]], in [[Hay Springs, Nebraska]] (d. 2014); [[Jim Chamberlin]], Canadian aerodynamic engineer, member of the design team of the [[Avro Canada CF-105 Arrow|Avro Arrow]] and later for the [[Apollo program]], in [[Kamloops]], [[British Columbia]] (d. 1981)\n\n== [[May 24]], 1915 (Monday) ==\n* The term \"crime against humanity\" is used for the first time by governments in joint public statement issued by the [[Allies of World War I|Allied]] governments to Ottoman government accusing them of [[Armenian Genocide|committing genocide on ethnic Armenians]] within the [[Ottoman Empire]].<ref>1915 declaration\n* [http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/cpquery/T?&report=hr933&dbname=106& Affirmation of the United States Record on the Armenian Genocide Resolution] 106th Congress,2nd Session, House of Representatives\n* [http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c109:H.RES.316: Affirmation of the United States Record on the Armenian Genocide Resolution (Introduced in House of Representatives)] 109th Congress, 1st Session, [http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d109:HE00316: H.RES.316], June 14, 2005. 15 September 2005 House Committee/Subcommittee:International Relations actions. Status: Ordered to be Reported by the Yeas and Nays: 40\u20137.\n* \"Crimes Against Humanity\", 23 British Yearbook of International Law (1946) p. 181\n* Schabas [[#References|References]] pp. 16-17\n* [http://www.armenian-genocide.org/Affirmation.160/current_category.7/affirmation_detail.html  Original source of the telegram sent by the Department of State, Washington containing the French, British and Russian joint declaration]</ref>\n* British military diplomat [[Aubrey Herbert]] and Ottoman senior army officer [[Mustafa Kemal Atat\u00fcrk]] agreed to call an eight-hour truce at [[Gallipoli campaign|Gallipoli]] so both sides could recover and bury the dead.<ref>Broadbent 2005, p. 156</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Ypres]] \u2013 Germans released a gas attack on British forces defending a {{convert|7|km|mi|adj=on}} front near [[Hooge, Ypres|Hooge]], [[Belgium]], forcing them to retreat.{{sfn|Edmonds|Wynne|1927|p=340}}\n* The [[Bombardment of Ancona|bombardment]] on [[Ancona]], [[Italy]] ended with 63 killed and at least one Italian destroyer damaged.<ref>Sondhaus 1994, pp. 266=270</ref>\n* Irish soldier [[John Condon (British Army soldier)|John Condon]] for the [[British Army]] was killed in action, becoming the youngest British soldier to die in [[World War I]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Reading Room Manchester |url=http://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/491331 |title=Commonwealth War Graves Commission database record for John Condon |publisher=Cwgc.org |date=1915-05-24 |accessdate=2014-04-12}}</ref>\n* The prototype for the [[Siemens-Schuckert R.I]] airplane was first flown in [[Berlin]] and delivered for military service the following month.<ref>{{cite book| last=Haddow |first=G.W. |author2=Peter M. Grosz  |title=The German Giants: The Story of the R-planes 1914\u20131919 |publisher=Putnam |location=London |year=1962|page=175}}</ref>\n* Stage actress [[Alice Brady]] made her first credited film debut in ''[[The Boss (1915 film)|The Boss]]'', produced by her father  [[William A. Brady]].<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/B/Boss1915.html ''The Boss'' at silentera.com]</ref><ref>[http://ibdb.com/production.php?id=6997 ''The Boss'' as produced on Broadway at the Astor Theatre, January 30, 1911 to April 1911, 88 performances; IBDb.com]</ref>\n\n== [[May 25]], 1915 (Tuesday) ==\n[[File:E11 in action.jpg|thumb|right|400px|[[Royal Navy]] submarine [[HMS E11|HMS ''E11'']] torpedoes the \"Stamboul\" off [[Constantinople]].]]\n* [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|China]] agreed to the [[Twenty-One Demands]] made by [[Japan]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gowen|first1=Robert Joseph|title=Great Britain and the Twenty-One Demands of 1915: Cooperation versus Effacement|journal=Journal of Modern History|date=1971|volume=1|issue=43|pages=76\u2013106|bibcode= }}</ref>\n* [[Russia]], [[China]] and [[Mongolia]] signed the [[Treaty of Kyakhta (1915)|Treaty of Kyakhta]] which recognized the autonomy of [[Outer Mongolia]]. However, most Mongolians opposed the treaty because it did not recognize an independent, [[Pan-Mongolism|all-Mongolian]] state. The treaty became moot following the 1917 [[October Revolution]] in [[Russia]].<ref>Batsaikhan, O. The Last King of Mongolia, Bogdo Jebtsundamba Khutuktu. Ulaanbaatar: Admon, 2008, p.290-293 - {{ISBN|978-99929-0-464-0}}</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 French forces launched assaults to take [[Andres, Pas-de-Calais]], [[France]] from the Germans.<ref>The Times 1916, p. 226</ref>\n* [[Battle of Festubert]] \u2013 The British captured the French village of [[Festubert]] from the Germans. After 10 days of fighting, British forces had only advanced three kilometres (1.9 miles) while losing over 16,000 casualties, while German defenses only sustained 5,000.{{sfn|Edmonds|1928|p=76}}\n* [[Second Battle of Ypres]] \u2013 The British failed in retaking trenches lost to the German gas attack the day before, forcing them to retreat {{convert|1|km|mi}} northwards. The battle ended with the Germans compressing the Ypres salient by {{convert|5|km|mi}}.{{sfn|Edmonds|Wynne|1927|pp=353\u2013359}} Casualties on both sides were massive, with the Germans suffering close to 35,000 while the British were worse at just over 59,000. French forces sustained close to 22,000 casualties while the Canadian forces had close to 6,000. The city of [[Ypres]] itself was completely demolished by artillery fire.{{sfn|Edmonds|Wynne|1927|pp=359, 284}}\n* British battleship {{HMS|Triumph|1903|6}} was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Dardanelles]] by {{SMU|U-21|Germany|6}} with the loss of 78 of her 803 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{HMS|Chelmer|1904|6}}.<ref>Burt 1988, p. 276</ref>\n* Dutch ocean liner {{USS|Rijndam|ID-2505|2}} collided with Norwegian ocean liner SS ''Joseph J. Cuneo'' in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] {{convert|10|nmi|km}} south of the [[Nantucket Shoals]] of the [[United States]]. Two hundred and thirty passengers were rescued by [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] ships {{USS|Louisiana|BB-19|6}}, {{USS|Michigan|BB-27|6}}, {{USS|South Carolina|BB-26|6}} and {{USS|Texas|BB-35|6}}. ''Rijndam'' was subsequently repaired and returned to service.\n* The [[Asquith coalition ministry]], a national wartime [[coalition government]] to lead [[Great Britain]], went into effect. However, Irish leader [[John Redmond]] chose not to join and garnered support from [[Irish Parliamentary Party]].<ref>{{cite journal| last1=Butler| first1=David| last2=Butler| first2=Gareth| title=Twentieth Century British Political Facts, 1900\u20132000| date=2000| publisher=St. Martin's}}</ref>\n* British submarine [[HMS E11|HMS ''E11'']] slipped in [[Constantinople]] harbor in a search for the German warships {{SMS|Goeben}} and {{SMS|Breslau}}, but instead torpedoed Turkish transport ship ''Stambou'' before escaping. The attack caused a panic in the city and forced the {{SMS|Breslau}} to relocate.<ref>O'Connell 2010, p. 74</ref><ref>Pitt & Young 1970, p. 918</ref>\n* [[Ross Sea party]] \u2013 The polar ship ''[[SY Aurora|Aurora]]'' drifted toward the [[Victoria Land]] coastline on the western side of the [[Ross Ice Shelf]] in the [[Antarctic]].<ref>{{cite book | authorlink = Ernest Shackleton | last = Shackleton | first = Ernest | title = South | publisher = Century Publishing | location = London | year = 1983 | isbn = 0-7126-0111-2| page=312}}</ref>\n* The [[French Army]] established the [[102nd Fortress Division (France)|102nd Fortress Division]] for the [[6th Army (France)|6th Army]].<ref>{{cite web| title=102e Division d' Infanterie Territoriale |url=http://sacarcheo.nuxit.net/regiment/102eDIT.PDF |accessdate=28 August 2009 | archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5jWCYsQRS?url=http://sacarcheo.nuxit.net/regiment/102eDIT.PDF |archivedate=3 September 2009 |url-status=live | df=dmy }}</ref>\n* An [[Kochrab Ashram|ashram]] for [[Mahatma Gandhi]] was prepared by Jivanlal Desai, barrister and friend to Gandhi, just outside the city of [[Ahmedabad]], [[India]]. However, Gandhi wanted to practice farming and other pursuits and would need more usable land, so the [[Sabarmati Ashram|ashram]] was relocated two years later to a suburb in [[Ahmedabad]] on the banks of the [[Sabarmati River]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Gandhi|first=Mohandas|title=Gandhi Ashram Official Website|url=http://www.gandhiashramsabarmati.org}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Robin Day (designer)|Robin Day]], British furniture designer, designed the [[polypropylene stacking chair]], in [[High Wycombe]], [[England]] (d. [[2010]])\n\n== [[May 26]], 1915 (Wednesday) ==\n* The German [[Army of the Niemen]] was formed under the command of General [[Otto von Below]], who had previously commanded a reserve corps unit under the [[8th Army (German Empire)|8th Army]]. The army was meant to create diversionary action against the Russian armies to distract them from [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] planned to break through the [[Eastern Front (World War I)|Eastern Front]]. The original 8th Army was dissolved in September, only to be renewed using the diversionary army under von Below.<ref>{{cite book | last = Cron | first = Hermann | year = 2002 | title = Imperial German Army 1914\u201318: Organisation, Structure, Orders-of-Battle [first published: 1937] | publisher = Helion & Co. | pages=82\u201383 | isbn = 1-874622-70-1}}</ref>\n* The [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Arauca]] was established in [[Arauca, Arauca|Arauca]], [[Colombia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Diocese of Arauca|url=http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/arau0.htm|website=GCatholic.org|publisher=GCatholic.org|accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Tommy Walker (footballer, born 1915)|Tommy Walker]], Scottish [[association football]] player, [[inside forward]] for [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Midlothian]] and the [[Scotland national football team]] from 1933 to 1948, in [[Livingston, West Lothian]], [[Scotland]] (d. 1993)\n* '''Died:''' [[Julian Grenfell]], English poet and army officer, author of the poem \"Into Battle\" (b. 1888)\n\n== [[May 27]], 1915 (Thursday) ==\n* The [[General Assembly of the Ottoman Empire]] passed the [[Tehcir Law]] which authorized the deportation of the entire [[Armenians in the Ottoman Empire|Armenian]] populations in the Empire.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fakulteler.atauni.edu.tr/ermenia/mndty.php?al=3 |title=''Sevk ve \u0130sk\u00e2n Kanunu'' |publisher=Research Centre for Turkish\u2013Armenian Relations, [[Ataturk University]] |accessdate=April 25, 2010 |language=Turkish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090426035934/http://fakulteler.atauni.edu.tr/ermenia/mndty.php?al=3 |archivedate=April 26, 2009 }}</ref>\n* [[Urfa Resistance|Armenian resistance]] against the [[Ottoman Empire]] began to be organized in [[Urfa]], [[Turkey]].<ref>[[Guenter Lewy|Lewy, Guenter]]. ''[[The Armenian Massacres in Ottoman Turkey: A Disputed Genocide]]'', p. 201. Salt Lake City: [[Utah University Press]], 2005. {{ISBN|0-87480-849-9}}.</ref>\n* British minelayer {{HMS|Princess Irene}} exploded and sank while loading mines off [[Sheerness]] with the loss of 352 lives.<ref>{{cite book|first=Roy |last=Ingleton |title=Kent Disasters |year=2010 |publisher=Pen & Sword |location= Barnsley |page=50|ISBN=978-1-84563-116-1}}</ref>\n* British battleship {{HMS|Majestic|1895|6}} was torpedoed and sunk by German submarine {{SMU|U-21|Germany|6}} in the [[Dardanelles]] and sank with the loss of 49 of her 672 crew.<ref>Burt 1988, p. 131</ref>\n* British [[sloop]] [[HMS Veronica (1915)|HMS ''Veronica'']] was launched at [[Dunlop Bremner & Company]] in [[Port Glasgow]], [[Scotland]] and would serve with the [[New Zealand Division of the Royal Navy]]. The ship notably rescued hundred of survivors following the [[1931 Hawke's Bay earthquake]] in [[New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=McDougall|first1=R. J.|title=New Zealand Naval Vessels|date=1989|publisher=Government Printing Office|location=Wellington|isbn=978-0-477-01399-4|pages=18\u201319}}</ref>\n* The ''[[Alpenkorps (German Empire)|Alpenkorps]]'' were established in the [[German Army (German Empire)|Imperial German Army]] as an elite mountain fighting unit.<ref>''Histories of Two Hundred and Fifty-One Divisions of the German Army which Participated in the War (1914\u20131918), compiled from records of Intelligence section of the General Staff, American Expeditionary Forces, at General Headquarters, Chaumont, France 1919,'' (1920)</ref>\n* A resistance group formed in [[Urfa Resistance|Urfa]], [[Turkey]] (now \u015eanl\u0131urfa) in response to the deportation of Armenians.<ref>{{cite book | last = Kurdoghlian | first = Mihran | title = Badmoutioun Hayots, Volume III | publisher = Hradaragoutioun Azkayin Oussoumnagan Khorhourti |year= 1996 | location = Athens, Greece | pages = 93\u201395|language=hy}}</ref>\n* The first edition of ''Pioneer-News'' was published with the headline \"Status of the New Townsite\" referring to what was to become [[Anchorage, Alaska]]. The paper eventually became the ''[[Anchorage Times]]''.<ref>{{cite book  | last = Atwood  | first = Evangeline  | title = Anchorage: Star of the North  | publisher = Continental Heritage Press | date = 1982  | isbn = 0-932986-25-0  | page = 37 }}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Herman Wouk]], American writer, author of ''[[The Caine Mutiny]]'', ''[[The Winds of War]]'' and ''[[War and Remembrance]]'', in [[New York City]] (d. 2019)\n\n== [[May 28]], 1915 (Friday) ==\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 The French failed to capture [[Andres, Pas-de-Calais]], [[France]] from the Germans.<ref>The Times 1916, p. 226.</ref>\n* [[Battle for No.3 Post]] \u2013 Soldiers with [[New Zealand Mounted Rifles Brigade]] fought members of the [[19th Infantry Division (Ottoman Empire)|Ottoman 19th Infantry Division]] to capture a strategic defense post on the ridge overlooking [[ANZAC Cove]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Wilkie|first=A. H.|title=Official War History of the Wellington Mounted Rifles Regiment, 1914\u20131919|publisher=Whitcombe and Tombs|year=1924|location=Auckland|isbn=978-1-84342-796-4|page=27}}</ref>\n* [[1915 Sinhalese-Muslim riots|Riots]] began to break out between the ethnic [[Sinhalese people|Sinhalese]] and [[Sri Lankan Moors|Muslims]] in [[Kandy]], [[British Ceylon]] before spreading to [[Colombo]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Perera |first1=Edward Walter |title=Memorandum upon recent disturbances in Ceylon |url=https://archive.org/details/memorandumuponre00pererich |website=Archive.org |accessdate=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n* The [[Royal Flying Corps]] opened a [[RAF Narborough|military aerodrome]] at [[Norfolk]], [[England]].<ref>{{cite book |last= Jefford |first= C.G. |title= RAF Squadrons |year=1988 |publisher= Airlife Publishing Ltd |isbn= 1-85310-053-6|page=158}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Morton Smith]], American academic, most known for the discovery of the [[Mar Saba letter]] which allegedly contained references to the ''[[Secret Gospel of Mark]]'', in [[Philadelphia]] (d. [[1991]]); [[Joseph Greenberg]], American linguist, leading expert in African languages, in [[New York City]] (d. [[2001]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Yenovk Shahen]], Armenian stage actor celebrated in the [[Ottoman Empire]] for his performances in [[Victor Hugo]]'s ''[[Le roi s'amuse]]'', ''[[Othello]]'', and ''[[The Merchant of Venice]]'', murdered during the [[Armenian Genocide]] (b. [[1881]])\n\n== [[May 29]], 1915 (Saturday) ==\n* [[Manuel de Arriaga]] officially resigned as president of [[First Portuguese Republic|Portugal]], allowing Prime Minister [[Te\u00f3filo Braga]] to take over as the second president of the country.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Luz|first1=Jos\u00e9 Lu\u00eds Brand\u00e3o da|title=Te\u00f3filo Braga e o Liceu de Ponta Delgada: A Prop\u00f3sito de uma Carta aos seus Estudantes|journal=Insulana|date=2002|issue=58|pages=29\u201334|publisher=\u00d3rg\u00e3o do Instituto Cultural de Ponta Delgada|location=Ponta Delgada|language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n* Ottoman troops attacked the [[15th Battalion (Australia)|15th Australian Battalion]] but were driven back, the last major offensive Ottoman forces would attempt during the [[Gallipoli campaign]].{{sfn|Broadbent|2005|pp=169\u2013170}}\n* [[Battle for No.3 Post]] \u2013 [[New Zealand]] forces successfully captured a key defense post overlooking [[ANZAC Cove]] and prepared to defend it from counterattacks by the Ottomans.<ref>Wilkie 1924, p. 27</ref>\n* British ocean liner {{SS|Merion||2}} was torpedoed and damaged in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] by German submarine [[SM UB-8|''UB-8'']] and sank two days later.<ref>{{cite web | last = Helgason | first = Gu\u00f0mundur | title = Ships hit during WWI: Merion | url = http://uboat.net/wwi/ships_hit/4093.html | work = U-Boat War in World War I | publisher = Uboat.net | date =  | accessdate = 3 March 2009 }}</ref>\n* British cruiser [[HMS Champion (1915)|HMS ''Champion'']] was launched by [[Hawthorn Leslie and Company]] in [[Tyneside]], [[England]]. It would participate in the [[Battle of Jutland]] the following year.<ref>Gardiner, Robert, ed., ''Conway's All the World's Fighting Ships, 1906\u20131921'', Annapolis, Maryland: Naval Institute Press, 1985, {{ISBN|0-87021-907-3}}, {{OCLC|423834653}}, {{LCCN|84042782 }}, p. 57, ([https://books.google.com/books?id=V2r_TBjR2TYC&pg=PA57 preview of 2006 reprint])</ref>\n* [[Goodall Park]] was opened for professional baseball in [[Sanford, Maine]] and is the current home for the ball team [[Sanford Mainers]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sullivan|first1=Shawn P.|title=Goodall Park at 100|url=http://www.fosters.com/article/20150603/NEWS/150609742|accessdate=26 February 2016|work=Sanford News|date=June 3, 2015}}</ref>\n* The city of [[Lake Alfred, Florida]] was established.<ref>{{cite web |title=Beginnings |url=http://mylakealfred.com/lake-alfred-profile/beginnings/ |website=My Lake Alfred |publisher=City of Lake Alfred |accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n* '''Died:''' [[John G. McCullough]], American politician, 49th [[Governor of Vermont]] (d. 1835)\n\n== [[May 30]], 1915 (Sunday) ==\n* [[Gorlice\u2013Tarn\u00f3w Offensive]] \u2013 Eleventh German Army's artillery began to bombard forts around [[Przemy\u015bl]].<ref>DiNardo, 2010, p. 99.</ref>\n* [[Battle for No.3 Post]] \u2013 Ottoman forces successfully recaptured a key defense post from [[New Zealand]] forces, ending the battle with 200 casualties for the Ottomans and 104 wounded and 42 dead among the [[New Zealand Mounted Rifles Brigade]].<ref>Wilkie 1924, p. 33</ref>\n* U.S. President [[Woodrow Wilson]] dedicated the [[USS Maine Mast Memorial|memorial site]] honoring those who died during the sinking of the [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] cruiser [[USS Maine (ACR-1)|USS ''Maine'']] in 1898 in the [[Arlington National Cemetery]], [[Virginia]].<ref>\"Honors For Hero Dead.\" ''Washington Post.'' May 16, 1915</ref>\n* Shinano Railway extended the [[\u014cito Line]] in the [[Nagano Prefecture]], [[Japan]], with station [[Nakagaya Station|Matsumoto]] serving the line.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Shinano Mainichi Shimbun |title=Nagano Prefecture All Railway Stations, revised edition (\u9577\u91ce\u770c\u9244\u9053\u5168\u99c5 \u5897\u88dc\u6539\u8a02\u7248) |date=2011 |publisher=Shinano Mainichi Shinbun Publishing |isbn=9784784071647 |page=97|language=ja}}</ref>\n* A [[Helensburgh railway station|rail station]] was opened in [[Helensburgh, New South Wales]] to serve the [[South Coast railway line, New South Wales|South Coast line]] in [[Australia]].<ref>{{cite NSW SHR|5012054|Helensburgh Railway Station group|hr=01168|accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Pearl City (Boca Raton)|Pearl City]] was established near [[Boca Raton, Florida]] as a segregated neighborhood for African-American workers.<ref>Evans and Lee, (1990).  Pearl City, Florida: A Black Community Remembers.  Boca Raton: Florida Atlantic UP/UP of Florida.</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Henry Aaron Hill]], American chemist, first African American president of the [[American Chemical Society]], in [[St. Joseph, Missouri]] (d. [[1979 in science|1979]]); [[Jerome Wiesner]], American academic and engineer, chair of the [[President's Science Advisory Committee]] during the [[John F. Kennedy]] administration, president of [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] from 1971 to 1980, in [[Detroit]] (d. [[1994]])\n* '''Born:''' [[Ray Crowe]], American basketball coach, head of the [[Crispus Attucks High School]] basketball team from 1950 and 1957, [[Indiana High School Boys Basketball Tournament]] champion in 1955, the first time an all-black high school team won the [[Indiana]] state championship, in [[Franklin, Indiana]] (d. 2003); [[Martin Manulis]], American television producer, best known for the 1950s [[CBS|CBS Television]] specials ''[[Playhouse 90]]'' and ''[[Studio One (American TV series)|Studio One]]'', in [[New York City]] (d. [[2007]]); [[Exterminator (horse)|Exterminator]], American racehorse, winner of the [[1918 Kentucky Derby]], in [[Lexington, Kentucky]] (d. [[1945]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Marcelo Azc\u00e1rraga Palmero]], Spanish state leader, 13th [[Prime Minister of Spain]] (b. [[1832]])\n\n== [[May 31]], 1915 (Monday) ==\n* [[Defense of Van (1915)|Defense of Van]] \u2013 Russian general [[Nikolai Yudenich]] arrived in [[Van, Turkey]] and arranged for Armenian resistance leader [[Aram Manukian]] to become governor of the [[Occupation of Western Armenia|Armenian provisional government]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Hinterhoff | first = Eugene | title = Illustrated Encyclopedia of World War I | volume = iv. Persia: The Stepping Stone To India | publisher = Marshall Cavendish | year = 1984 | location = New York | isbn = 0-86307-181-3 |pages=1153\u201357}}</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Artois]] \u2013 The Germans repulsed the French advance on [[Souchez]], [[France]] after six days of fighting.<ref>The Times 1916, pp. 225-226.</ref>\n* [[Battle of Amara]] \u2013 British Indian and Ottoman troops clashed in the marshes of the [[Tigris]] between the towns of [[Amarah|Amara]] and [[Al-Qurnah|Qurna]], [[Mesopotamia]] (now [[Iraq]]).<ref>Keogh, E.G. (1955) ''The River in the Desert'' p. 52-67. Melbourne, Wilke & Co. {{OCLC|12058974}}</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Garua]] \u2013 British and French colonial troops laid siege to German forts around [[Garoua|Garua]], [[German Cameroon]] (now [[Cameroon]]).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hilditch|first1=A. N.|title=Battle Sketches, 1914\u20131915|date=1915|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=39}}</ref>\n* The [[German Army (German Empire)|Imperial German Army]] carried out its first airship raid on [[London]] using the ''L38'' Zeppelin. It dropped {{convert|3000|lb|kg|disp=flip}} of bombs on the eastern suburb of the city, killing seven people and injuring 14.<ref>Robinson 1973, p. 103</ref><ref>{{cite book| last=Palmer| first=Alan| author2=Veronica| year=1992| title=The Chronology of British History| publisher=Century Ltd| location=London| pages=351\u2013352| isbn=0-7126-5616-2}}</ref>\n* The [[11th Indian Division]] was disbanded following the [[Raid on the Suez Canal]] and became primarily a defense force for the canal.<ref>{{cite book  | ref = harv  | last = Perry | first = F.W.  | year = 1993  | title = Order of Battle of Divisions Part 5B. Indian Army Divisions  | publisher = Ray Westlake Military Books  | location = Newport  | isbn = 1-871167-23-X|page=121}}</ref>\n* Italian race driver [[Ralph DePalma]] won the [[1915 Indianapolis 500|5th running]] of the [[Indianapolis 500]] at the [[Indianapolis Motor Speedway]] in a [[Mercedes (marque)|Mercedes 18/100]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Indianapolis 500 Historical Stats \u2013 1911\u20132015|url=https://www.indianapolismotorspeedway.com/events/indy500/history/historical-stats/race-stats/race-results/1915|website=Indianapolis Motor Speedway|publisher=IMS LLC|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Judith Wright]], Australian poet, known for her poetry collections such as ''Birds'', in [[Armidale, New South Wales]], [[Australia]] (d. [[2000 in poetry|2000]]); [[Jack Real]], American aerospace engineer, designer of many [[Lockheed Corporation|Lockheed]] aircraft, confidant to [[Howard Hughes]] from 1957 to the billionaire's death in 1976, in [[Calumet, Michigan]] (d. 2005); [[Carmen Herrera]], Cuban-American artist, member of the [[abstract expressionism]] in [[New York City]], in [[Havana]]\n* '''Died:''' [[Victor Child Villiers, 7th Earl of Jersey|Victor Child Villiers]], Australian statesman, 18th [[Governor of New South Wales]] (b. [[1845]])\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Events by month links}}\n\n[[Category:May|1915]]\n[[Category:1915|*1915-05]]\n[[Category:Months in the 1910s|*1915-05]]\n", "name_user": "Freeman1856", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMay 30, 1915 (Sunday)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/May_1915"}
{"title_page": "D. S. Senanayake", "text_new": "{{short description|Prime Minister of Sri Lanka}}\n{{redirect|Don Senanayake|the entrepreneur and philanthropist|Don Spater Senanayake}}\n{{More footnotes|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder         \n | honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]  \n | name             = Don Stephen Senanayake\n | native_name      = \u0daf\u0ddc\u0db1\u0dca \u0dc3\u0dca\u0da7\u0dd3\u0dc0\u0db1\u0dca \u0dc3\u0dda\u0db1\u0dcf\u0db1\u0dcf\u0dba\u0d9a \n | honorific-suffix = [[Member of parliament|MP]]\n | image            = [[File:Official Photographic Portrait of Don Stephen Senanayaka (1884-1952).jpg|250px]]\n | imagesize        =\n | caption          = D. S. Senanayake with his signature orchid lapel\n<!-- -->\n | office           = 1st [[Prime Ministers of Sri Lanka|Prime Minister of Ceylon]]\n | term_start       = 24 September 1947<ref name=\"posl-hbk\">''Parliament of Sri Lanka \u2013 Handbook of Parliament'', [http://www.parliament.lk/handbook_of_parliament/prime_ministers.jsp Prime Ministers] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080325034304/http://www.parliament.lk/handbook_of_parliament/prime_ministers.jsp |date=25 March 2008 }}</ref>\n | term_end         = 22 March 1952<ref name=\"posl-hbk\"/>\n | monarch          = [[George VI]]<br />[[Elizabeth II]] \n | governor_general = [[Henry Monck-Mason Moore]]<br />[[Herwald Ramsbotham, 1st Viscount Soulbury]]\n | predecessor      = Post created\n | successor        = [[Dudley Senanayake]]\n<!-- -->\n | office2          = [[Leader of the House (Sri Lanka)|Leader of the House]]\n | term_start2      = 2 December 1942 \n | term_end2        = 4 July 1947\n | predecessor2     = [[Don Baron Jayatilaka]]\n | successor2       = [[S. W. R. D. Bandaranaike]]\n<!-- -->\n | office3          = [[State Council of Ceylon|Minister of Agriculture and Lands]]\n | term_start3      = 1942\n | term_end3        = 1947\n | predecessor3     = Post created\n | successor3       = Dudley Senanayake\n<!-- -->\n | constituency_MP4 = [[Mirigama Electoral District|Mirigama]]\n | parliament4      = Ceylon\n | term_start4      = 14 October 1947\n | term_end4        = 22 March 1952\n | predecessor4     =   ''Constituency Created''\n | successor4       = [[J. E. Amaratunga|John Amaratunga]]\n<!-- -->\n | birth_date       = {{Birth date|1883|10|21|df=y}}\n | birth_place      = Botale, [[Mirigama]], [[British Ceylon]]\n | death_date       = {{death date and age|1952|3|22|1883|10|20|df=y}}\n | death_place      = [[Colombo]], [[Dominion of Ceylon]]\n | nationality      = [[Ceylonese]]\n | party            = [[United National Party]]\n | profession       = \n | father           = [[Don Spater Senanayake]]\n | mother           = Dona Catherina Elizabeth Perera Gunasekara\n | spouse           = Molly Dunuwila<ref name=\"rweb-fg\">''Sri Lankan Sinhalese Family Genealogy'', [http://www.rootsweb.com/~lkawgw/gen3001.html The Don Bartholomews Senanayake Family Tree]</ref>\n |children         = [[Dudley Senanayake]]<br />Robert Senanayake\n |alma_mater       = [[S. Thomas' College, Mount Lavinia]]\n | residence       = [[Woodlands, Colombo|Woodlands]]\n|}}\n<!--==================================================-->\n<!--| PER [[WP:LEAD]]: claims found in the lead of an  |-->\n<!--| article that are expanded upon and cited later   |-->\n<!--| in the article do not need citations in the lead |-->\n<!--| itself. Before asking for a citation for facts   |-->\n<!--| in the lead of this article, please check        |-->\n<!--| whether the fact is cited later.  Thank-you!     |-->\n<!--====================================================-->\n'''Don Stephen Senanayake''' ({{lang-si|\u0daf\u0ddc\u0db1\u0dca \u0dc3\u0dca\u0da7\u0dd3\u0dc0\u0db1\u0dca \u0dc3\u0dda\u0db1\u0dcf\u0db1\u0dcf\u0dba\u0d9a}}; {{lang-ta|\u0b9f\u0bbf. \u0b8e\u0bb8\u0bcd. \u0b9a\u0bc7\u0ba9\u0ba8\u0bbe\u0baf\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbe}}; 21 October 1883 \u2013 22 March 1952) was a [[Sri Lanka]]n statesman. He was the first [[Prime Minister of Sri Lanka]] having emerged as the leader of the [[Sri Lankan independence movement]] that led to the establishment of self-rule in Sri Lanka. He is considered as the \"[[Father of the Nation]]\".<ref name=\"ref1\">[http://www.dailymirror.lk/54491/d-s-senanayake-the-father-of-the-nation D. S. Senanayake \u2013 The Father of the Nation]</ref>\n\nA [[Plantation|planter]], Senanayake became active in the [[Temperance movement in Sri Lanka|temperance movement]] which grew into the [[Sri Lankan independence movement|independence movement]]. He was elected to the [[Legislative Council of Ceylon]] and thereafter to the [[State Council of Ceylon]], where he served as Minister of Agriculture and Lands. He was elected to the first [[Parliament of Ceylon]] forming a government and serving as Ceylon's first Prime Minister from 1947 until his death in 1952.\n\n==Early life and education==\n[[File:Senanayakes.jpg|thumb|200px|left|The Senanayake family.]]\n{{main|Senanayake family}}\nHe was born in the village of Botale in the Hapitigam Korale (currently known as [[Mirigama]]) on 21 October 1883 to [[Don Spater Senanayake]] (1847\u20131907) and Dona Catherina Elizabeth Perera Gunasekera Senanayake (1852\u20131949).<ref>''Don Stephen Senanayake, the first Prime Minister of Sri Lanka'' by H. A. J. Hulugalle</ref> Spater Senanayake had made his fortune in [[graphite]] [[mining]] and at the time he was expanding into plantations and investments in the [[arrack]] renting franchise, later he would be awarded the title of [[Sri Lankan Mudaliyars|Mudaliyar]] for his philanthropy.<ref name=Bourgeoisie>[https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Nobodies_to_Somebodies.html?id=9eISAQAAMAAJ Nobodies to Somebodies: The Rise of the Colonial Bourgeoisie in Sri Lanka], Kumari Jayawardena, pp. 192-3 & 267 (Zed) {{ISBN|9781842772287}}</ref> Stephen Senanayake had two elder brothers, Don Charles \"D. C.\" Senanayake and [[Fredrick Richard Senanayake|Fredrick Richard \"F. R.\" Senanayake]]; and one sister, Maria Frances Senanayake who married F. H. Dias Bandaranaike.<ref name=\"ref1\"/>\n\nBrought up in a devout [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] family, he entered the prestigious [[Anglican]] school [[S. Thomas' College, Mutwal]]. Never a studious student, he excelled in sports playing cricket and played in the [[Royal-Thomian]]. He later played cricket for the [[Sinhalese Sports Club]] and Nondescripts Cricket Club. His contemporaries at S. Thomas's includes [[D. R. Wijewardena]], [[Paul Pieris|Sir Paul Pieris]], [[Arthur Wijewardena|Sir Arthur Wijewardena]] and [[Alexander Francis Molamure|Sir Francis Molamure]].<ref>[http://archives.dailymirror.lk/2005/10/20/feat.asp DS hobnobbed with the mighty but kept the common touch] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130329230656/http://archives.dailymirror.lk/2005/10/20/feat.asp |date=29 March 2013 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.thesundayleader.lk/archive/20020317/review.htm Don Stephen Senanayake]</ref><ref name=\"island.lk\">[http://www.island.lk/2010/03/22/features7.html D. S. Senanayake: A leader with extraordinary vision]</ref><ref>[http://www.island.lk/2000/10/21/featur01.html Don Stephen Senanayake, First Prime Minister of Sri Lanka]</ref><ref>[http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=44637 The Sara Legend The launch of the autobiography of Manicasothy Saravanamuttu]</ref><ref>[http://www.dailynews.lk/2002/11/05/fea03.html Remembering the 'Father of the Nation'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030329210735/http://www.dailynews.lk/2002/11/05/fea03.html |date=29 March 2003 }}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nAfter completing schooling, he worked as a clerk in the [[Department of Survey (Sri Lanka)|Surveyor General's Department]], but left after a period of apprenticing. He joined his brother D. C. Senanayake in running his fathers extensive business holdings. He worked as a [[Plantation|planter]], introducing the new commercial crop of rubber to the family plantations. He managed the [[Kahatagaha Graphite Mine]] which was owned by his brother F. R. Senanayake wife's family. F. R. Senanayake had married the youngest daughter of Mudaliyar [[Don Charles Gemoris Attygalle]]. He was a member of the Low-Country Products Association and of the [[Orient Club]]. In 1914, he was appointed as a member of a government commission sent to [[Madagascar]] to study and report on their graphite mining industry.<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/534303/D-S-Senanayake D. S. Senanayake]</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n===Early political activism===\n[[File:Henry Pedris (1888-1915).jpg|150px|right|thumb|[[Henry Pedris]], a Captain in the Colombo Town Guard; was executed by the British on the account of treason.]]\nThe three Senanayake brothers were involved in the [[Temperance movement in Sri Lanka|temperance movement]] formed in 1912.  When [[World War I]] broke out in 1914 they joined the [[Colombo Town Guard]]. The brothers were arrested and imprisoned without charges during the [[1915 Ceylonese Riots|1915 riots]]. They faced the prospect of execution since the British Governor [[Robert Chalmers|Sir Robert Chalmers]] considered the temperance movement as [[seditious]]. He was released on a [[bail|bail bound]] after 46 days at the [[Welikada Prison]] without charges. Brutal suppression of the riots by the British initiated the [[Sri Lankan independence movement|modern independence movement]] led by the educated middle class.<ref name='SL1'>[http://www.thesundayleader.lk/2012/02/12/the-stalwarts-in-the-struggle-for-independence-in-sri-lanka/ The Stalwarts In The Struggle For Independence In Sri Lanka]</ref> Don Stephen and Don Charles were prominent members of the political party [[Lanka Mahajana Sabha]]. Fredrick Richard and Don Charles were committed supporters of the [[Young Men's Buddhist Association]].  D. S. Senanayake played an active role in the independence movement, initially in support of his brother Fredrick Richard.<ref name='SL1'/>\n\n===Legislative Council===\nIn 1924, Senanayake was elected unopposed to the [[Legislative Council of Ceylon]] from [[Negombo]]. He became the Secretary (similar to a [[Whip (politics)|whip]]) of the [[unofficial member]]s group of the Legislative Council, activity engaged in proceedings with a particular interest in subjects related to agriculture, lands and irrigation. He questioned in the Legislative Council the biased policies of the colonial administration in the plantain industry; the cost overruns of the [[Batticaloa line]] and the [[Trincomalee line]]; the delays in the [[Norton Dam|Norton Bridge Dam]] and advocated for the establishment of the first university in the island close to [[Kandy]]. In 1927, he acted on behalf of [[Gerard Wijeyekoon]] in the [[Executive Council of Ceylon|Executive Council]].<ref>[http://www.island.lk/2000/10/21/featur01.html Don Stephen Senanayake, First Prime Minister of Sri Lanka] by H. A. J. Hulugalle (The Island) Accessed 2015-11-08</ref><ref>[http://www.island.lk/2010/03/22/features7.html D. S. Senanayake: A leader with extraordinary vision] by Walter Wijenayake (The Island) Accessed 2015-11-08</ref> When his brother F.R. died on a pilgrimage to [[Buddha Gaya]] in 1925, Don Stephen assumed his leadership of the independence movement.\n\n===State Council of Ceylon===\n[[File:Ministers of the Second State Council of Ceylon with the Speaker in 1936.jpg|right|thumb|Ministers of the Second State Council of Ceylon with the Speaker in 1936.]]\nIn 1931 he was elected to the newly formed [[State Council of Ceylon]] representing the [[Ceylon National Congress]]. At the first siting of the State Council, he was elected as Minister of Agriculture and Lands to chair the state council committee on  Agriculture and Lands.<ref name=rajasingham/>\n\n====Minister of Agriculture and Lands====\nAs Minister of Agriculture and Lands, initiated a policy to effectively combated Ceylon's agricultural problems, established the ''Land Development Ordinance'', and introduced an agricultural policy to counter Ceylon's rice problems. This policy earned him respect of many, and he continued to be a minister for fifteen years, having been re-elected in 1936. He also enforced a productivity programme of \"Agricultural Modernisation\". He introduced the ''Land Bill'', expanded the [[Cooperative|Cooperativeco-operative movement]] in Ceylon, assisted in the founding of the [[Bank of Ceylon]]. In 1938, he introduced the ''Flora and Fauna Protection Ordinance '', establishing the [[Yala National Park]]. In 1940, following a heated discussion with the Governor which resulted from the [[Inspector General of Police]] refusing to follow a request by the Minister of Home Affairs, Senanayake gave his resignation which was followed by the other Ministers. The resignations were withdrawn shortly following settlement with the Governor.\n\n====World War II====\n[[File:Bristol Blenheim - Colombo - Royal Air Force Operations in the Far East, 1941-1945. CI105.jpg|thumb|An [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] [[Bristol Blenheim]] bomber takes off from [[Colombo Racecourse]]<!--note, the runway was the racecourse--> in Ceylon during the war.]]\nAt the onset of [[World War II]] in the far east, on 1 December 1941 a Civil Defence Department was formed with [[Oliver Ernest Goonetilleke|Oliver Goonetilleke]] as Commissioner.  D. S. Senanayake, as Minister of Agriculture and Lands and a member of the [[war cabinet|Ceylon war council]] took an active role in food supply and control. He was tasked with many defence projects, including rapid construction of an airfield at the [[Colombo Racecourse]], which he achieved; making it available for the defence of Ceylon during the [[Easter Sunday Raid]].\n\nDuring this time a close relationship developed between Senanayake and the deputy commissioner of civil defence, Dr [[Ivor Jennings]] who was the principal of the [[Ceylon University College]]. Dr Jennings, an expert on constitutional law, subsequently became Senanayake's adviser on constitutional reforms aimed at gaining independence for the island.<ref name=\"ref2\">[http://www.sundaytimes.lk/010204/plus2.html 'From 'half a loaf' to Independence]</ref>\n\n====Gaining independence====\n[[File:SL Independence.jpg|thumb|200px|left|The formal ceremony marking the start of self-rule, with the opening of the first parliament at [[Independence Square, Colombo|Independence Square]] by [[Prince Henry, Duke of Gloucester]] in the presence of D. S. Senanayake as first Prime Minister of Ceylon.]]\nIn December 1942, Senanayake became the [[Leader of the House (Sri Lanka)|Leader of the House]] and Vice Chairman of the Board of Ministers in the State Council, upon the retirement of [[Don Baron Jayatilaka|Sir Baron Jayatilaka]], Minister of Home Affairs.<ref>[http://www.sundaytimes.lk/030323/plus/6.html What caused the rift between D.S. and Sir Baron] by Drene Terana Sariffodeen (Sunday Times) Accessed 2015-11-08</ref> On 26 May 1943, the [[Government of the United Kingdom|British Government]] made the Whitehall Declaration of 1943 on Ceylon constitutional change, which enabled ministers to make submissions.<ref name=rajasingham>Rajasingham K. T. [http://www.atimes.com/ind-pak/CJ13Df01.html Sri Lanka: The Untold Story] ''[[Asia Times]]'', Ch. 10, 19 October 2001. Accessed 12 June 2015</ref>  This bypassed the Governor, who called for a commission from the colonial office to halt the activities of the ministers. Senanayake resigned from the National Congress disagreeing with its resolution on [[independence]] and instead approached the commission with his proposal of [[dominion]] status and they accepted the ministers' submissions, publishing these in the Sessional Paper XIV of 1944.<ref name=rajasingham/><ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6orPBJCSPhIC&q=Senanayake+resigns+from+congress+#v=snippet&q=Senanayake%20resigns%20from%20congress&f=false J.R. Jayewardene of Sri Lanka: 1906\u20131956] by K. M. De Silva, William Howard Wriggins, p. 127-8 & 168-70 (Univ of Hawaii) {{ISBN|9780824811839}}</ref> In 1944, the [[Soulbury Commission]] was formed. In 1945, he proceeded to London to meet the Secretary of State for the Colonies, [[Oliver Stanley]]. On his arrival in London he met instead the newly appointed [[George Henry Hall, 1st Viscount Hall|George Hall]] who had succeeded Stanley following Labour's win in the 1945 general election. He resigned his ministry in 1946 to push for full independence. That year he formed the [[United National Party]] (UNP) by amalgamating three right-leaning pro-Dominion parties.<ref name=\"ref2\"/>\n\nThe granting of independence to India in 1947 and the appointment of [[Arthur Creech Jones]] as Colonial Secretary gave a new window for Senanayake to push for his case using the new constitution that was recommended by the Soulbury Commission. In the negotiations that followed, the British government accepted Senanayake's proposals for constitutional change and self-rule. Senanayake presented the Soulbury Constitution to the State Council which voted it in with only three votes against it.\n\n[[1947 Ceylonese parliamentary election|Parliamentary elections]] were held from 23 August \u2013 20 September 1947. Senanayake was contested for the first time in the [[Mirigama Electoral District|Mirigama electorate]], having been elected uncontested in all previous elections. He won the seat by a majority of over 16,000 votes against [[Edmund Samarakkody]] of the [[Bolshevik\u2013Leninist Party of India, Ceylon and Burma]]. Senanayake's party the UNP fell short of a majority at the general election, but was able to form a government in coalition with the [[All Ceylon Tamil Congress]].\n\nOn September 24, 1947 he was invited by the [[Governor General of Ceylon]] [[Henry Monck-Mason Moore|Sir Henry Moore]] to form the island's first cabinet as its first Prime Minister. On 11 November 1947, Senanayake and Sir Henry signed agreements between Ceylon and Britain including a defence pact and public service agreements that paved the way for independence of Ceylon. The \"Independence Bill of Ceylon\" was passed in December 1947. On 4 February 1948, Ceylon marked its independence with a ceremonial opening of parliament.<ref name=\"ref2\"/><ref>[http://countrystudies.us/sri-lanka/68.htm ''Sinhalese Parties''], Country Studies, Federal Research Division of the Library of Congress</ref>\n\n==First prime minister==\n[[File:First Cabinet of Ceylon.jpg|right|thumb|D. S. Senanayake as Prime Minister with his Cabinet.]]\nWith his accession, Senanayake began the process of establishing institutions needed for an independent state. While most domestic institutions existed, Ceylon remained dependent on Britain for trade, defence and external affairs. He turned down a [[knighthood]], but maintained good relations with Britain and was the first Ceylonese to be appointed to the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]] in 1950.<ref name=\"gazette30december1949\">{{London Gazette |issue=38797 |date=30 December 1949 |page=1 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.ft.lk/columns/d-s-senanayaka-a-nations-father-undisputed-leader-of-all-time/4-532356 D.S. Senanayake \u2013 A nation\u2019s father, undisputed leader of all time]</ref>\n\n===National development===\nHe boldly made plans to spread out the population, and his [[Gal Oya]] scheme relocated over 250,000 people. He expanded the agrarian policies he had initiated during his tenure as Minister of Agriculture and Lands, a post now held by his son Dudley Senanayake. With a rapidly expanding population and food shortages faced during the war, Senanayake aimed to increase local food production to be self sustainable. Renovation of sites of historic importance in [[Anuradhapura]] and [[Polonnaruwa]] took place at this time. Senanayake also proposaled expansion of hydro-electric power in the island.<ref>{{cite news|title=D. S. SENANAYAKE A NATION'S FATHER and Undisputed Leader|url=http://www.dailynews.lk/?q=2016/03/22/features/77157}}</ref>\n\n===Citizenship===\nSenanayake's government introduced the [[Ceylon Citizenship Act]] which was passed by parliament on 20 August 1948 and became law on 15 November 1948. Only about 5,000 Indian Tamils qualified for citizenship. More than 700,000 people, about 11% of the population, were denied citizenship and made [[statelessness|stateless]]. The bill had been opposed fiercely in Parliament by the [[Ceylon Workers' Congress|Ceylon Indian Congress]], which represented the Indian Tamils, and the Sinhalese [[leftist]] parties, as well as the [[All Ceylon Tamil Congress]], which represented the [[Sri Lankan Tamils]], including its leader [[G.G. Ponnambalam]].<ref>{{cite web|title=103rd Birth Anniversary today : G. G. Ponnambalam - Founder of ACTC |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2003/11/08/fea08.html |date=8 November 2003 |publisher=Daily News, Sri Lanka |accessdate=20 June 2009 |author=Apparthuray Vinayagamoorthy |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604163811/http://www.dailynews.lk/2003/11/08/fea08.html |archivedate=4 June 2011 }}</ref> This was followed by the '' Indian and Pakistani Residents (Citizenship) Act No.3 of 1949'' and the ''Ceylon (Parliamentary Elections) Amendment Act No.48 of 1949''<ref>[http://www.ices.lk/sl_database/ethnic_conflict/time_line.shtml Ethnic Conflict of Sri Lanka: Time Line - From Independence to 1999] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091212123102/http://www.ices.lk/sl_database/ethnic_conflict/time_line.shtml |date=2009-12-12 }}, International Centre for Ethnic Studies</ref>\n\n===Foreign policy===\nSenanayake held the portfolio of [[Ministry of External Affairs and Defence]]. He developed Ceylon's post-independence foreign policy, establishing formal relations with foreign nations. Initially gaining membership of the [[Commonwealth]] and establishing diplomatic ties other member countries, he established diplomatic relations with the United States and Japan. He established the [[Ceylon Overseas Service]] to build a carder of career diplomats. He hosted the Commonwealth Conference of Foreign Ministers, held in Colombo in January 1950. One of the significant outcomes of this conference was the establishment of the [[Colombo Plan]].\n\n===Defence===\n[[File:PM visits the 1st Bn CLI.jpg|thumb|right|D. S. Senanayake visiting the 1st battalion of the [[Sri Lanka Light Infantry|CLI]] at the [[Echelon Barracks|Echelon Square.]]]]\nAlthough Ceylon had maintained a [[Ceylon Defence Force|small volunteer force]] for the defense of coloney, Senanayake introduced the Army Act (1949), Navy Act (1950) and the Air Force Act (1951) establishing the [[Sri Lanka Armed Forces|Armed forces of Ceylon]]. Having engaged in Defence Agreement with Britain when gaining independence, Senanayake retained British bases in Ceylon and gain her assistance in training and arming its new military.\n\n===Political challenges===\nIn the early years of Senanayake's premiership he faced opposition and criticism from many of the [[Sri Lanka leftist parties|leftist parties]]. He soon had difficulties with one of the strongest members of his cabinet and leader of the largest factions of his party, [[S. W. R. D. Bandaranaike]]. Bandaranaike joined his [[Sinhala Maha Sabha]] in forming the UNP in 1947 having given the impression that Senanayake would soon retire and he would succeed him. With no signs of Senanayake retiring and conflicts with Senanayake on hard line nationalist policies of he had, in 1951, Bandaranaike resigned from his posts and dissolved the Sinhala Maha Sabha and established the [[Sri Lanka Freedom Party]] (SLFP). Senanayake assumed the portfolio of Health and Local Government held by Bandaranaike and began countering his break in parliament for the next few months.<ref>Richardson (2005), ''Paradise Poisoned'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=-sIRxpjfd-EC&pg=PA145 p. 145.]</ref>\n\n==Death==\nOn the morning of Friday, 21 March 1952, Senanayake took his usual pre-breakfast ride on [[Galle Face Green]], a short distance from his official residence [[Temple Trees]]. He was riding the one of his favorite horses ''Chitra'' a [[mare]] belonging to the [[mounted police]]. Accompanying him on that day was [[Richard Aluwihare|Sir Richard Aluwihare]], the [[Inspector General of Police|IGP]]; [[G.G. Ponnambalam]], a cabinet minister and [[Inspector of Police|Inspector]] [[Eddie Grey]]. The horse broke into a gallop from a canter and went on for a mile, when suddenly the Prime Minister fell off the saddle.\n\nHe was taken to a nursing home where he remained unconscious for the next thirty-two hours. It was believed that he had suffered a [[stroke]]. He was treated by Dr M. V. P. Pieris, Ceylon's senior surgeon and a team of Professors from the [[University of Manitoba]] who had been visiting Ceylon as part of a [[WHO]] medical mission. A radio message was sent for [[Hugh Cairns (surgeon)|Sir Hugh Cairns]], who decided to fly out to Ceylon to attend the Prime Minister. [[Winston Churchill]] order a [[RAF]] [[Handley Page Hastings|Hastings]] with a double crew to take Sir Hugh. However the aircraft with three more doctors and two nurses was taxiing to take off when the message was received that it was too late as the Prime Minister's situation was deteriorating. Two more neurosurgeons from India and Pakistan had reached Colombo, it was too late. Senanayake died at 3:30 pm on 22 March 1952.<ref>[http://www.rootsweb.com/~lkawgw/appreciation06.htm In memory of their kindness<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n<!--Ref In Sinhala:- http://www.lankadeepa.lk/Section/diyatha/28062009/main.htm {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090704125616/http://www.lankadeepa.lk/Section/diyatha/28062009/main.htm |date=4 July 2009 }} -->\n\nHis remains were taken to Temple Trees, where they lay till the next morning when they were moved to the [[Old Parliament Building, Colombo|House of Representatives]]  where it [[Lying in state|lay in state]], with over half a million persons showing their respects. His state funeral followed with over 32,000 people taking part in the funeral procession with the stage barring the coffin drawn by sailors of the [[Royal Ceylon Navy]]. The procession ended at [[Independence Memorial Hall|Independence Square]] where the remains were cremated.\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Wedding of D. S. Senanayake and Mollie Dunuwille in 1910.jpg|150px|thumb|left|Wedding of D. S. Senanayake and Mollie Dunuwille in 1910.]]\nSenanayake cared for animals and owned a wide range of pets such as [[elephant]]s, [[horse]]s, [[pig]]s, [[cattle]]; many kept in his estate and at the [[Bothale Walawwa]]. A keen horticulturist, he grew orchids and would typically wear an orchid in the lapel of his suit. He suffered from diabetes most of his later life.\n\n===Marriage and children===\nD. S. Senanayake married [[Mollie Dunuwila Senanayake|Molly Dunuwila]] in 1910. She was the daughter of R. R. Dunuwila, then Secretary of the [[Colombo Municipal Council]] and Grace Jayatilaka, daughter of Frederick Jayatilaka of the [[Ceylon Civil Service]] and District Judge of Kalutara. They had two sons, [[Dudley Shelton Senanayake]] (19 June 1911 \u2013 13 April 1973) and Robert Parakrama Senanayake (8 April 1913 \u2013 26 April 1986).<ref name=\"island.lk\"/> His eldest son, Dudley Shelton Senanayake, succeeded him as Prime Minister in 1952, followed by his nephew, Sir [[John Kotelawala]] (1897\u20131980) in 1953, but this nine-year family dynasty ended with the [[landslide victory]] of [[Solomon West Ridgeway Dias Bandaranaike]] in 1956, campaigning under the \"[[Sinhala Only Act|Sinhala Only]]\" slogan. Dudley Senanayake regained the premiership in 1960, and served again from 1965 to 1970. [[Rukman Senanayake]], one of his grandsons, is a former cabinet minister, former chairman of the UNP, current member of parliament, and assistant leader of the UNP.\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Rt.Hon Don Stephen Senanayaka Laying the Foundation Stone of Poramadulla Central College on 1st June 1951..jpg|150px|right|thumb|D. S. Senanayake laying the foundation stone of [[Poramadulla Central College]].]]\nD. S. Senanayake is respected by [[Sinhalese people|Sinhalese]] and some [[Sri Lankan Muslims|Muslims]]. However, [[Tamil people|Tamil]]s were not happy with his citizenship laws, which disenfranchised virtually all [[Sri Lanka Tamils (Indian origin)|Tamils of recent Indian origin]] living in the central highlands. His bold agricultural plans and pro-Western policies drew criticism for their modern and untraditional nature. Under his family's leadership, Sri Lanka's economy flourished, and he is still known as \"The Father of Sri Lanka\".\n\nStatues of D. S. Senanayake have been erected in many parts of the island, including one at the [[Independence Memorial Hall]] and at the [[Old Parliament Building, Colombo]].<ref>[http://www.sundaytimes.lk/070812/Plus/pls11.html Moulding forever]</ref> The lake created by the Gal Oya Dam has been named as the [[Senanayake Samudraya]] after him. Many schools, libraries and public buildings have been named in his honor and the ''Rt Hon D S Senanayake Memorial Shield'' is awarded at the [[Royal\u2013Thomian]] in which he played for S. Thomas' in 1901 and 1902.\n\n==Titles and honours==\n* Mr Don Stephen Senanayake MLC (1924\u20131931)\n* Mr Don Stephen Senanayake (1931\u20131947)\n* ''[[The Honourable|Hon]]'' Don Stephen Senanayake MP (1947\u20131950)\n* ''[[The Right Honourable|The Rt Hon]]'' Don Stephen Senanayake MP (1950\u20131952)\n\n===Appointments===\n* [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Councillor]] (1950)\n\n===Educational===\n*{{flagicon|Ceylon}} [[Legum Doctor|LLD]] (honorary) - [[University of Ceylon]] - 1949\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of political families in Sri Lanka]]\n*''[[Nidahase Piya DS]]'', a biographical film based on DS's life\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.worldgenweb.org/lkawgw/gen3001.html The Senanayake Ancestry]\n*[http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~lkawgw/dsspic.html   The Senanayake Clan]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160129230919/http://www.nation.lk/2008/10/19/newsfe4.htm  Remembering D S of  Botale Walauwa]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080325034304/http://www.parliament.lk/handbook_of_parliament/prime_ministers.jsp Website of the Parliament of Sri Lanka]\n*[http://unitednationalparty.tripod.com/ United National Party website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081012040351/http://www.lankadeepa.lk/Section/rajaweediya/29052008/01.html  DS Senanayake in Sinhala]\n*[http://www.divaina.com/2008/08/04/mano06.html   Methek Kathawa  '''Divaina''']\n*[http://www.divaina.com/2008/10/27/mano04.html  Methek Kathawa  '''Divaina''']\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J_-7fEdspXs Funeral Of D.S. Senanayake 1952]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Prime Minister of Ceylon]] | before=\u2013 | after=[[Dudley Senanayake]] | years=1947\u20131952}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Sri Lankan Prime Ministers}}\n{{Sri Lankan foreign ministers}}\n{{Sri Lankan defence ministers}}\n{{Leaders of the House (Sri Lanka)}}\n{{Members of the 2nd State Council of Ceylon}}\n{{Members of 1st Parliament of Ceylon}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Senanayake, Don Stephen}}\n[[Category:1884 births]]\n[[Category:1952 deaths]]\n[[Category:National Heroes of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the United National Party]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Ceylonese military personnel]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan independence movement]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan mining businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of British Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Members of the 1st State Council of Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Members of the Legislative Council of Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Members of the 1st Parliament of Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Converts to Buddhism]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese politicians]]\n[[Category:People of British Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Alumni of S. Thomas' College, Mount Lavinia]]\n[[Category:Defence ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Ceylonese people of World War II]]\n[[Category:Senanayake family|DS]]\n[[Category:Members of the 2nd State Council of Ceylon]]\n[[Category:People who died in office]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Prime Minister of Sri Lanka}}\n{{redirect|Don Senanayake|the entrepreneur and philanthropist|Don Spater Senanayake}}\n{{More footnotes|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder         \n | honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]  \n | name             = Don Stephen Senanayake\n | native_name      = \u0daf\u0ddc\u0db1\u0dca \u0dc3\u0dca\u0da7\u0dd3\u0dc0\u0db1\u0dca \u0dc3\u0dda\u0db1\u0dcf\u0db1\u0dcf\u0dba\u0d9a \n | honorific-suffix = [[Member of parliament|MP]]\n | image            = [[File:Official Photographic Portrait of Don Stephen Senanayaka (1884-1952).jpg|250px]]\n | imagesize        =\n | caption          = D. S. Senanayake with his signature orchid lapel\n<!-- -->\n | office           = 1st [[Prime Ministers of Sri Lanka|Prime Minister of Ceylon]]\n | term_start       = 24 September 1947<ref name=\"posl-hbk\">''Parliament of Sri Lanka \u2013 Handbook of Parliament'', [http://www.parliament.lk/handbook_of_parliament/prime_ministers.jsp Prime Ministers] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080325034304/http://www.parliament.lk/handbook_of_parliament/prime_ministers.jsp |date=25 March 2008 }}</ref>\n | term_end         = 22 March 1952<ref name=\"posl-hbk\"/>\n | monarch          = [[George VI]]<br />[[Elizabeth II]] \n | governor_general = [[Henry Monck-Mason Moore]]<br />[[Herwald Ramsbotham, 1st Viscount Soulbury]]\n | predecessor      = Post created\n | successor        = [[Dudley Senanayake]]\n<!-- -->\n | office2          = [[Leader of the House (Sri Lanka)|Leader of the House]]\n | term_start2      = 2 December 1942 \n | term_end2        = 4 July 1947\n | predecessor2     = [[Don Baron Jayatilaka]]\n | successor2       = [[S. W. R. D. Bandaranaike]]\n<!-- -->\n | office3          = [[State Council of Ceylon|Minister of Agriculture and Lands]]\n | term_start3      = 1942\n | term_end3        = 1947\n | predecessor3     = Post created\n | successor3       = Dudley Senanayake\n<!-- -->\n | constituency_MP4 = [[Mirigama Electoral District|Mirigama]]\n | parliament4      = Ceylon\n | term_start4      = 14 October 1947\n | term_end4        = 22 March 1952\n | predecessor4     =   ''Constituency Created''\n | successor4       = [[J. E. Amaratunga|John Amaratunga]]\n<!-- -->\n | birth_date       = {{Birth date|1883|10|21|df=y}}\n | birth_place      = Botale, [[Mirigama]], [[British Ceylon]]\n | death_date       = {{death date and age|1952|3|22|1883|10|20|df=y}}\n | death_place      = [[Colombo]], [[Dominion of Ceylon]]\n | nationality      = [[Ceylonese]]\n | party            = [[United National Party]]\n | profession       = \n | father           = [[Don Spater Senanayake]]\n | mother           = Dona Catherina Elizabeth Perera Gunasekara\n | spouse           = Molly Dunuwila<ref name=\"rweb-fg\">''Sri Lankan Sinhalese Family Genealogy'', [http://www.rootsweb.com/~lkawgw/gen3001.html The Don Bartholomews Senanayake Family Tree]</ref>\n |children         = [[Dudley Senanayake]]<br />Robert Senanayake\n |alma_mater       = [[S. Thomas' College, Mount Lavinia]]\n | residence       = [[Woodlands, Colombo|Woodlands]]\n|}}\n<!--==================================================-->\n<!--| PER [[WP:LEAD]]: claims found in the lead of an  |-->\n<!--| article that are expanded upon and cited later   |-->\n<!--| in the article do not need citations in the lead |-->\n<!--| itself. Before asking for a citation for facts   |-->\n<!--| in the lead of this article, please check        |-->\n<!--| whether the fact is cited later.  Thank-you!     |-->\n<!--====================================================-->\n'''Don Stephen Senanayake''' ({{lang-si|\u0daf\u0ddc\u0db1\u0dca \u0dc3\u0dca\u0da7\u0dd3\u0dc0\u0db1\u0dca \u0dc3\u0dda\u0db1\u0dcf\u0db1\u0dcf\u0dba\u0d9a}}; {{lang-ta|\u0b9f\u0bbf. \u0b8e\u0bb8\u0bcd. \u0b9a\u0bc7\u0ba9\u0ba8\u0bbe\u0baf\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbe}}; 21 October 1883 \u2013 22 March 1952) was a [[Sri Lanka]]n statesman. He was the first [[Prime Minister of Sri Lanka]] having emerged as the leader of the [[Sri Lankan independence movement]] that led to the establishment of self-rule in Sri Lanka. He is considered as the \"[[Father of the Nation]]\".<ref name=\"ref1\">[http://www.dailymirror.lk/54491/d-s-senanayake-the-father-of-the-nation D. S. Senanayake \u2013 The Father of the Nation]</ref>\n\nA [[Plantation|planter]], Senanayake became active in the [[Temperance movement in Sri Lanka|temperance movement]] which grew into the [[Sri Lankan independence movement|independence movement]]. He was elected to the [[Legislative Council of Ceylon]] and thereafter to the [[State Council of Ceylon]], where he served as Minister of Agriculture and Lands. He was elected to the first [[Parliament of Ceylon]] forming a government and serving as Ceylon's first Prime Minister from 1947 until his death in 1952.\n\n==Early life and education==\n[[File:Senanayakes.jpg|thumb|200px|left|The Senanayake family.]]\n{{main|Senanayake family}}\nHe was born in the village of Botale in the Hapitigam Korale (currently known as [[Mirigama]]) on 21 October 1883 to [[Don Spater Senanayake]] (1847\u20131907) and Dona Catherina Elizabeth Perera Gunasekera Senanayake (1852\u20131949).<ref>''Don Stephen Senanayake, the first Prime Minister of Sri Lanka'' by H. A. J. Hulugalle</ref> Spater Senanayake had made his fortune in [[graphite]] [[mining]] and at the time he was expanding into plantations and investments in the [[arrack]] renting franchise, later he would be awarded the title of [[Sri Lankan Mudaliyars|Mudaliyar]] for his philanthropy.<ref name=Bourgeoisie>[https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Nobodies_to_Somebodies.html?id=9eISAQAAMAAJ Nobodies to Somebodies: The Rise of the Colonial Bourgeoisie in Sri Lanka], Kumari Jayawardena, pp. 192-3 & 267 (Zed) {{ISBN|9781842772287}}</ref> Stephen Senanayake had two elder brothers, Don Charles \"D. C.\" Senanayake and [[Fredrick Richard Senanayake|Fredrick Richard \"F. R.\" Senanayake]]; and one sister, Maria Frances Senanayake who married F. H. Dias Bandaranaike.<ref name=\"ref1\"/>\n\nBrought up in a devout [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] family, he entered the prestigious [[Anglican]] school [[S. Thomas' College, Mutwal]]. Never a studious student, he excelled in sports playing cricket and played in the [[Royal-Thomian]]. He later played cricket for the [[Sinhalese Sports Club]] and Nondescripts Cricket Club. His contemporaries at S. Thomas's includes [[D. R. Wijewardena]], [[Paul Pieris|Sir Paul Pieris]], [[Arthur Wijewardena|Sir Arthur Wijewardena]] and [[Alexander Francis Molamure|Sir Francis Molamure]].<ref>[http://archives.dailymirror.lk/2005/10/20/feat.asp DS hobnobbed with the mighty but kept the common touch] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130329230656/http://archives.dailymirror.lk/2005/10/20/feat.asp |date=29 March 2013 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.thesundayleader.lk/archive/20020317/review.htm Don Stephen Senanayake]</ref><ref name=\"island.lk\">[http://www.island.lk/2010/03/22/features7.html D. S. Senanayake: A leader with extraordinary vision]</ref><ref>[http://www.island.lk/2000/10/21/featur01.html Don Stephen Senanayake, First Prime Minister of Sri Lanka]</ref><ref>[http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=44637 The Sara Legend The launch of the autobiography of Manicasothy Saravanamuttu]</ref><ref>[http://www.dailynews.lk/2002/11/05/fea03.html Remembering the 'Father of the Nation'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030329210735/http://www.dailynews.lk/2002/11/05/fea03.html |date=29 March 2003 }}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nAfter completing schooling, he worked as a clerk in the [[Department of Survey (Sri Lanka)|Surveyor General's Department]], but left after a period of apprenticing. He joined his brother D. C. Senanayake in running his fathers extensive business holdings. He worked as a [[Plantation|planter]], introducing the new commercial crop of rubber to the family plantations. He managed the [[Kahatagaha Graphite Mine]] which was owned by his brother F. R. Senanayake wife's family. F. R. Senanayake had married the youngest daughter of Mudaliyar [[Don Charles Gemoris Attygalle]]. He was a member of the Low-Country Products Association and of the [[Orient Club]]. In 1914, he was appointed as a member of a government commission sent to [[Madagascar]] to study and report on their graphite mining industry.<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/534303/D-S-Senanayake D. S. Senanayake]</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n===Early political activism===\n[[File:Henry Pedris (1888-1915).jpg|150px|right|thumb|[[Henry Pedris]], a Captain in the Colombo Town Guard; was executed by the British on the account of treason.]]\nThe three Senanayake brothers were involved in the [[Temperance movement in Sri Lanka|temperance movement]] formed in 1912.  When [[World War I]] broke out in 1914 they joined the [[Colombo Town Guard]]. The brothers were arrested and imprisoned without charges during the [[1915 Ceylonese Riots|1915 riots]]. They faced the prospect of execution since the British Governor [[Robert Chalmers|Sir Robert Chalmers]] considered the temperance movement as [[seditious]]. He was released on a [[bail|bail bound]] after 46 days at the [[Welikada Prison]] without charges. Brutal suppression of the riots by the British initiated the [[Sri Lankan independence movement|modern independence movement]] led by the educated middle class.<ref name='SL1'>[http://www.thesundayleader.lk/2012/02/12/the-stalwarts-in-the-struggle-for-independence-in-sri-lanka/ The Stalwarts In The Struggle For Independence In Sri Lanka]</ref> Don Stephen and Don Charles were prominent members of the political party [[Lanka Mahajana Sabha]]. Fredrick Richard and Don Charles were committed supporters of the [[Young Men's Buddhist Association]].  D. S. Senanayake played an active role in the independence movement, initially in support of his brother Fredrick Richard.<ref name='SL1'/>\n\n===Legislative Council===\nIn 1924, Senanayake was elected unopposed to the [[Legislative Council of Ceylon]] from [[Negombo]]. He became the Secretary (similar to a [[Whip (politics)|whip]]) of the [[unofficial member]]s group of the Legislative Council, activity engaged in proceedings with a particular interest in subjects related to agriculture, lands and irrigation. He questioned in the Legislative Council the biased policies of the colonial administration in the plantain industry; the cost overruns of the [[Batticaloa line]] and the [[Trincomalee line]]; the delays in the [[Norton Dam|Norton Bridge Dam]] and advocated for the establishment of the first university in the island close to [[Kandy]]. In 1927, he acted on behalf of [[Gerard Wijeyekoon]] in the [[Executive Council of Ceylon|Executive Council]].<ref>[http://www.island.lk/2000/10/21/featur01.html Don Stephen Senanayake, First Prime Minister of Sri Lanka] by H. A. J. Hulugalle (The Island) Accessed 2015-11-08</ref><ref>[http://www.island.lk/2010/03/22/features7.html D. S. Senanayake: A leader with extraordinary vision] by Walter Wijenayake (The Island) Accessed 2015-11-08</ref> When his brother F.R. died on a pilgrimage to [[Buddha Gaya]] in 1925, Don Stephen assumed his leadership of the independence movement.\n\n===State Council of Ceylon===\n[[File:Ministers of the Second State Council of Ceylon with the Speaker in 1936.jpg|right|thumb|Ministers of the Second State Council of Ceylon with the Speaker in 1936.]]\nIn 1931 he was elected to the newly formed [[State Council of Ceylon]] representing the [[Ceylon National Congress]]. At the first siting of the State Council, he was elected as Minister of Agriculture and Lands to chair the state council committee on  Agriculture and Lands.<ref name=rajasingham/>\n\n====Minister of Agriculture and Lands====\nAs Minister of Agriculture and Lands, initiated a policy to effectively combated Ceylon's agricultural problems, established the ''Land Development Ordinance'', and introduced an agricultural policy to counter Ceylon's rice problems. This policy earned him respect of many, and he continued to be a minister for fifteen years, having been re-elected in 1936. He also enforced a productivity programme of \"Agricultural Modernisation\". He introduced the ''Land Bill'', expanded the [[Cooperative|Cooperativeco-operative movement]] in Ceylon, assisted in the founding of the [[Bank of Ceylon]]. In 1938, he introduced the ''Flora and Fauna Protection Ordinance '', establishing the [[Yala National Park]]. In 1940, following a heated discussion with the Governor which resulted from the [[Inspector General of Police]] refusing to follow a request by the Minister of Home Affairs, Senanayake gave his resignation which was followed by the other Ministers. The resignations were withdrawn shortly following settlement with the Governor.\n\n====World War II====\n[[File:Bristol Blenheim - Colombo - Royal Air Force Operations in the Far East, 1941-1945. CI105.jpg|thumb|An [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] [[Bristol Blenheim]] bomber takes off from [[Colombo Racecourse]]<!--note, the runway was the racecourse--> in Ceylon during the war.]]\nAt the onset of [[World War II]] in the far east, on 1 December 1941 a Civil Defence Department was formed with [[Oliver Ernest Goonetilleke|Oliver Goonetilleke]] as Commissioner.  D. S. Senanayake, as Minister of Agriculture and Lands and a member of the [[war cabinet|Ceylon war council]] took an active role in food supply and control. He was tasked with many defence projects, including rapid construction of an airfield at the [[Colombo Racecourse]], which he achieved; making it available for the defence of Ceylon during the [[Easter Sunday Raid]].\n\nDuring this time a close relationship developed between Senanayake and the deputy commissioner of civil defence, Dr [[Ivor Jennings]] who was the principal of the [[Ceylon University College]]. Dr Jennings, an expert on constitutional law, subsequently became Senanayake's adviser on constitutional reforms aimed at gaining independence for the island.<ref name=\"ref2\">[http://www.sundaytimes.lk/010204/plus2.html 'From 'half a loaf' to Independence]</ref>\n\n====Gaining independence====\n[[File:SL Independence.jpg|thumb|200px|left|The formal ceremony marking the start of self-rule, with the opening of the first parliament at [[Independence Square, Colombo|Independence Square]] by [[Prince Henry, Duke of Gloucester]] in the presence of D. S. Senanayake as first Prime Minister of Ceylon.]]\nIn December 1942, Senanayake became the [[Leader of the House (Sri Lanka)|Leader of the House]] and Vice Chairman of the Board of Ministers in the State Council, upon the retirement of [[Don Baron Jayatilaka|Sir Baron Jayatilaka]], Minister of Home Affairs.<ref>[http://www.sundaytimes.lk/030323/plus/6.html What caused the rift between D.S. and Sir Baron] by Drene Terana Sariffodeen (Sunday Times) Accessed 2015-11-08</ref> On 26 May 1943, the [[Government of the United Kingdom|British Government]] made the Whitehall Declaration of 1943 on Ceylon constitutional change, which enabled ministers to make submissions.<ref name=rajasingham>Rajasingham K. T. [http://www.atimes.com/ind-pak/CJ13Df01.html Sri Lanka: The Untold Story] ''[[Asia Times]]'', Ch. 10, 19 October 2001. Accessed 12 June 2015</ref>  This bypassed the Governor, who called for a commission from the colonial office to halt the activities of the ministers. Senanayake resigned from the National Congress disagreeing with its resolution on [[independence]] and instead approached the commission with his proposal of [[dominion]] status and they accepted the ministers' submissions, publishing these in the Sessional Paper XIV of 1944.<ref name=rajasingham/><ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6orPBJCSPhIC&q=Senanayake+resigns+from+congress+#v=snippet&q=Senanayake%20resigns%20from%20congress&f=false J.R. Jayewardene of Sri Lanka: 1906\u20131956] by K. M. De Silva, William Howard Wriggins, p. 127-8 & 168-70 (Univ of Hawaii) {{ISBN|9780824811839}}</ref> In 1944, the [[Soulbury Commission]] was formed. In 1945, he proceeded to London to meet the Secretary of State for the Colonies, [[Oliver Stanley]]. On his arrival in London he met instead the newly appointed [[George Henry Hall, 1st Viscount Hall|George Hall]] who had succeeded Stanley following Labour's win in the 1945 general election. He resigned his ministry in 1946 to push for full independence. That year he formed the [[United National Party]] (UNP) by amalgamating three right-leaning pro-Dominion parties.<ref name=\"ref2\"/>\n\nThe granting of independence to India in 1947 and the appointment of [[Arthur Creech Jones]] as Colonial Secretary gave a new window for Senanayake to push for his case using the new constitution that was recommended by the Soulbury Commission. In the negotiations that followed, the British government accepted Senanayake's proposals for constitutional change and self-rule. Senanayake presented the Soulbury Constitution to the State Council which voted it in with only three votes against it.\n\n[[1947 Ceylonese parliamentary election|Parliamentary elections]] were held from 23 August \u2013 20 September 1947. Senanayake was contested for the first time in the [[Mirigama Electoral District|Mirigama electorate]], having been elected uncontested in all previous elections. He won the seat by a majority of over 16,000 votes against [[Edmund Samarakkody]] of the [[Bolshevik\u2013Leninist Party of India, Ceylon and Burma]]. Senanayake's party the UNP fell short of a majority at the general election, but was able to form a government in coalition with the [[All Ceylon Tamil Congress]].\n\nOn September 24, 1947 he was invited by the [[Governor General of Ceylon]] [[Henry Monck-Mason Moore|Sir Henry Moore]] to form the island's first cabinet as its first Prime Minister. On 11 November 1947, Senanayake and Sir Henry signed agreements between Ceylon and Britain including a defence pact and public service agreements that paved the way for independence of Ceylon. The \"Independence Bill of Ceylon\" was passed in December 1947. On 4 February 1948, Ceylon marked its independence with a ceremonial opening of parliament.<ref name=\"ref2\"/><ref>[http://countrystudies.us/sri-lanka/68.htm ''Sinhalese Parties''], Country Studies, Federal Research Division of the Library of Congress</ref>\n\n==First prime minister==\n[[File:First Cabinet of Ceylon.jpg|right|thumb|D. S. Senanayake as Prime Minister with his Cabinet.]]\nWith his accession, Senanayake began the process of establishing institutions needed for an independent state. While most domestic institutions existed, Ceylon remained dependent on Britain for trade, defence and external affairs. He turned down a [[knighthood]], but maintained good relations with Britain and was the first Ceylonese to be appointed to the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]] in 1950.<ref name=\"gazette30december1949\">{{London Gazette |issue=38797 |date=30 December 1949 |page=1 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.ft.lk/columns/d-s-senanayaka-a-nations-father-undisputed-leader-of-all-time/4-532356 D.S. Senanayake \u2013 A nation\u2019s father, undisputed leader of all time]</ref>\n\n===National development===\nHe boldly made plans to spread out the population, and his [[Gal Oya]] scheme relocated over 250,000 people. He expanded the agrarian policies he had initiated during his tenure as Minister of Agriculture and Lands, a post now held by his son Dudley Senanayake. With a rapidly expanding population and food shortages faced during the war, Senanayake aimed to increase local food production to be self sustainable. Renovation of sites of historic importance in [[Anuradhapura]] and [[Polonnaruwa]] took place at this time. Senanayake also proposaled expansion of hydro-electric power in the island.<ref>{{cite news|title=D. S. SENANAYAKE A NATION'S FATHER and Undisputed Leader|url=http://www.dailynews.lk/?q=2016/03/22/features/77157}}</ref>\n\n===Citizenship===\nSenanayake's government introduced the [[Ceylon Citizenship Act]] which was passed by parliament on 20 August 1948 and became law on 15 November 1948. Only about 5,000 Indian Tamils qualified for citizenship. More than 700,000 people, about 11% of the population, were denied citizenship and made [[statelessness|stateless]]. The bill had been opposed fiercely in Parliament by the [[Ceylon Workers' Congress|Ceylon Indian Congress]], which represented the Indian Tamils, and the Sinhalese [[leftist]] parties, as well as the [[All Ceylon Tamil Congress]], which represented the [[Sri Lankan Tamils]], including its leader [[G.G. Ponnambalam]].<ref>{{cite web|title=103rd Birth Anniversary today : G. G. Ponnambalam - Founder of ACTC |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2003/11/08/fea08.html |date=8 November 2003 |publisher=Daily News, Sri Lanka |accessdate=20 June 2009 |author=Apparthuray Vinayagamoorthy |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604163811/http://www.dailynews.lk/2003/11/08/fea08.html |archivedate=4 June 2011 }}</ref> This was followed by the '' Indian and Pakistani Residents (Citizenship) Act No.3 of 1949'' and the ''Ceylon (Parliamentary Elections) Amendment Act No.48 of 1949''<ref>[http://www.ices.lk/sl_database/ethnic_conflict/time_line.shtml Ethnic Conflict of Sri Lanka: Time Line - From Independence to 1999] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091212123102/http://www.ices.lk/sl_database/ethnic_conflict/time_line.shtml |date=2009-12-12 }}, International Centre for Ethnic Studies</ref>\n\n===Foreign policy===\nSenanayake held the portfolio of [[Ministry of External Affairs and Defence]]. He developed Ceylon's post-independence foreign policy, establishing formal relations with foreign nations. Initially gaining membership of the [[Commonwealth]] and establishing diplomatic ties other member countries, he established diplomatic relations with the United States and Japan. He established the [[Ceylon Overseas Service]] to build a carder of career diplomats. He hosted the Commonwealth Conference of Foreign Ministers, held in Colombo in January 1950. One of the significant outcomes of this conference was the establishment of the [[Colombo Plan]].\n\n===Defence===\n[[File:PM visits the 1st Bn CLI.jpg|thumb|right|D. S. Senanayake visiting the 1st battalion of the [[Sri Lanka Light Infantry|CLI]] at the [[Echelon Barracks|Echelon Square.]]]]\nAlthough Ceylon had maintained a [[Ceylon Defence Force|small volunteer force]] for the defense of coloney, Senanayake introduced the Army Act (1949), Navy Act (1950) and the Air Force Act (1951) establishing the [[Sri Lanka Armed Forces|Armed forces of Ceylon]]. Having engaged in Defence Agreement with Britain when gaining independence, Senanayake retained British bases in Ceylon and gain her assistance in training and arming its new military.\n\n===Political challenges===\nIn the early years of Senanayake's premiership he faced opposition and criticism from many of the [[Sri Lanka leftist parties|leftist parties]]. He soon had difficulties with one of the strongest members of his cabinet and leader of the largest factions of his party, [[S. W. R. D. Bandaranaike]]. Bandaranaike joined his [[Sinhala Maha Sabha]] in forming the UNP in 1947 having given the impression that Senanayake would soon retire and he would succeed him. With no signs of Senanayake retiring and conflicts with Senanayake on hard line nationalist policies of he had, in 1951, Bandaranaike resigned from his posts and dissolved the Sinhala Maha Sabha and established the [[Sri Lanka Freedom Party]] (SLFP). Senanayake assumed the portfolio of Health and Local Government held by Bandaranaike and began countering his break in parliament for the next few months.<ref>Richardson (2005), ''Paradise Poisoned'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=-sIRxpjfd-EC&pg=PA145 p. 145.]</ref>\n\n==Death==\nOn the morning of Friday, 21 March 1952, Senanayake took his usual pre-breakfast ride on [[Galle Face Green]], a short distance from his official residence [[Temple Trees]]. He was riding the one of his favorite horses ''Chitra'' a [[mare]] belonging to the [[mounted police]]. Accompanying him on that day was [[Richard Aluwihare|Sir Richard Aluwihare]], the [[Inspector General of Police|IGP]]; [[G.G. Ponnambalam]], a cabinet minister and [[Inspector of Police|Inspector]] [[Eddie Grey]]. The horse broke into a gallop from a canter and went on for a mile, when suddenly the Prime Minister fell off the saddle.\n\nHe was taken to a nursing home where he remained unconscious for the next thirty-two hours. It was believed that he had suffered a [[stroke]]. He was treated by Dr M. V. P. Pieris, Ceylon's senior surgeon and a team of Professors from the [[University of Manitoba]] who had been visiting Ceylon as part of a [[WHO]] medical mission. A radio message was sent for [[Hugh Cairns (surgeon)|Sir Hugh Cairns]], who decided to fly out to Ceylon to attend the Prime Minister. [[Winston Churchill]] order a [[RAF]] [[Handley Page Hastings|Hastings]] with a double crew to take Sir Hugh. However the aircraft with three more doctors and two nurses was taxing to take off when the message was received that it was too late as the Prime Minister's situation was deteriorating. Two more neurosurgeons from India and Pakistan had reached Colombo, it was too late. Senanayake died at 3:30 pm on 22 March 1952.<ref>[http://www.rootsweb.com/~lkawgw/appreciation06.htm In memory of their kindness<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n<!--Ref In Sinhala:- http://www.lankadeepa.lk/Section/diyatha/28062009/main.htm {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090704125616/http://www.lankadeepa.lk/Section/diyatha/28062009/main.htm |date=4 July 2009 }} -->\n\nHis remains were taken to Temple Trees, where they lay till the next morning when they were moved to the [[Old Parliament Building, Colombo|House of Representatives]]  where it [[Lying in state|lay in state]], with over half a million persons showing their respects. His state funeral followed with over 32,000 people taking part in the funeral procession with the stage barring the coffin drawn by sailors of the [[Royal Ceylon Navy]]. The procession ended at [[Independence Memorial Hall|Independence Square]] where the remains were cremated.\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Wedding of D. S. Senanayake and Mollie Dunuwille in 1910.jpg|150px|thumb|left|Wedding of D. S. Senanayake and Mollie Dunuwille in 1910.]]\nSenanayake cared for animals and owned a wide range of pets such as [[elephant]]s, [[horse]]s, [[pig]]s, [[cattle]]; many kept in his estate and at the [[Bothale Walawwa]]. A keen horticulturist, he grew orchids and would typically wear an orchid in the lapel of his suit. He suffered from diabetes most of his later life.\n\n===Marriage and children===\nD. S. Senanayake married [[Mollie Dunuwila Senanayake|Molly Dunuwila]] in 1910. She was the daughter of R. R. Dunuwila, then Secretary of the [[Colombo Municipal Council]] and Grace Jayatilaka, daughter of Frederick Jayatilaka of the [[Ceylon Civil Service]] and District Judge of Kalutara. They had two sons, [[Dudley Shelton Senanayake]] (19 June 1911 \u2013 13 April 1973) and Robert Parakrama Senanayake (8 April 1913 \u2013 26 April 1986).<ref name=\"island.lk\"/> His eldest son, Dudley Shelton Senanayake, succeeded him as Prime Minister in 1952, followed by his nephew, Sir [[John Kotelawala]] (1897\u20131980) in 1953, but this nine-year family dynasty ended with the [[landslide victory]] of [[Solomon West Ridgeway Dias Bandaranaike]] in 1956, campaigning under the \"[[Sinhala Only Act|Sinhala Only]]\" slogan. Dudley Senanayake regained the premiership in 1960, and served again from 1965 to 1970. [[Rukman Senanayake]], one of his grandsons, is a former cabinet minister, former chairman of the UNP, current member of parliament, and assistant leader of the UNP.\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Rt.Hon Don Stephen Senanayaka Laying the Foundation Stone of Poramadulla Central College on 1st June 1951..jpg|150px|right|thumb|D. S. Senanayake laying the foundation stone of [[Poramadulla Central College]].]]\nD. S. Senanayake is respected by [[Sinhalese people|Sinhalese]] and some [[Sri Lankan Muslims|Muslims]]. However, [[Tamil people|Tamil]]s were not happy with his citizenship laws, which disenfranchised virtually all [[Sri Lanka Tamils (Indian origin)|Tamils of recent Indian origin]] living in the central highlands. His bold agricultural plans and pro-Western policies drew criticism for their modern and untraditional nature. Under his family's leadership, Sri Lanka's economy flourished, and he is still known as \"The Father of Sri Lanka\".\n\nStatues of D. S. Senanayake have been erected in many parts of the island, including one at the [[Independence Memorial Hall]] and at the [[Old Parliament Building, Colombo]].<ref>[http://www.sundaytimes.lk/070812/Plus/pls11.html Moulding forever]</ref> The lake created by the Gal Oya Dam has been named as the [[Senanayake Samudraya]] after him. Many schools, libraries and public buildings have been named in his honor and the ''Rt Hon D S Senanayake Memorial Shield'' is awarded at the [[Royal\u2013Thomian]] in which he played for S. Thomas' in 1901 and 1902.\n\n==Titles and honours==\n* Mr Don Stephen Senanayake MLC (1924\u20131931)\n* Mr Don Stephen Senanayake (1931\u20131947)\n* ''[[The Honourable|Hon]]'' Don Stephen Senanayake MP (1947\u20131950)\n* ''[[The Right Honourable|The Rt Hon]]'' Don Stephen Senanayake MP (1950\u20131952)\n\n===Appointments===\n* [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Councillor]] (1950)\n\n===Educational===\n*{{flagicon|Ceylon}} [[Legum Doctor|LLD]] (honorary) - [[University of Ceylon]] - 1949\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of political families in Sri Lanka]]\n*''[[Nidahase Piya DS]]'', a biographical film based on DS's life\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.worldgenweb.org/lkawgw/gen3001.html The Senanayake Ancestry]\n*[http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~lkawgw/dsspic.html   The Senanayake Clan]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160129230919/http://www.nation.lk/2008/10/19/newsfe4.htm  Remembering D S of  Botale Walauwa]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080325034304/http://www.parliament.lk/handbook_of_parliament/prime_ministers.jsp Website of the Parliament of Sri Lanka]\n*[http://unitednationalparty.tripod.com/ United National Party website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081012040351/http://www.lankadeepa.lk/Section/rajaweediya/29052008/01.html  DS Senanayake in Sinhala]\n*[http://www.divaina.com/2008/08/04/mano06.html   Methek Kathawa  '''Divaina''']\n*[http://www.divaina.com/2008/10/27/mano04.html  Methek Kathawa  '''Divaina''']\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J_-7fEdspXs Funeral Of D.S. Senanayake 1952]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Prime Minister of Ceylon]] | before=\u2013 | after=[[Dudley Senanayake]] | years=1947\u20131952}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Sri Lankan Prime Ministers}}\n{{Sri Lankan foreign ministers}}\n{{Sri Lankan defence ministers}}\n{{Leaders of the House (Sri Lanka)}}\n{{Members of the 2nd State Council of Ceylon}}\n{{Members of 1st Parliament of Ceylon}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Senanayake, Don Stephen}}\n[[Category:1884 births]]\n[[Category:1952 deaths]]\n[[Category:National Heroes of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Leader