ov 21, 2019 |website=The Verge |accessdate=Nov 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"vg247 dota2 beta\">{{cite web |url=http://www.vg247.com/2011/08/23/dota-2-beta-press-to-be-added-in-a-few-weeks/ |title=DOTA 2 beta: Press to be added in \"a few weeks\" |work=[[VG247]] |first=Patrick |last=Garratt |date=August 21, 2013 |accessdate=May 15, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908085114/http://www.vg247.com/2011/08/23/dota-2-beta-press-to-be-added-in-a-few-weeks/ |url-status=live |archivedate=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"vg247 dota2 mac linux\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vg247.com/2013/07/19/dota-2-releases-on-mac-and-linux-system-specs-patch-notes-inside/ |title=Dota 2 releases on Mac and Linux, system specs & patch notes inside |work=[[VG247]] |first=Dave |last=Cook |date=July 19, 2013 |accessdate=May 15, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908040956/http://www.vg247.com/2013/07/19/dota-2-releases-on-mac-and-linux-system-specs-patch-notes-inside/ |url-status=live |archivedate=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"vg247 portal2 linux\">{{cite web |url=http://www.vg247.com/2014/02/26/portal-2-linux-now-in-open-beta/ |title=Portal 2 Linux now in open beta |work=[[VG247]] |first=Brenna |last=Hillier |date=February 26, 2014 |accessdate=May 15, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503145346/http://www.vg247.com/2014/02/26/portal-2-linux-now-in-open-beta/ |url-status=live |archivedate=May 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"videogamer gmod\">{{cite web |url=https://www.videogamer.com/news/garrys-mod-on-steam-from-nov-29 |title=Garry's Mod on Steam from Nov 29 |work=VideoGamer.com |first=James |last=Orry |date=November 28, 2006 |accessdate=November 4, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104115110/https://www.videogamer.com/news/garrys-mod-on-steam-from-nov-29 |archivedate=November 4, 2017 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"wired portal mac\">{{cite web |url=https://www.wired.com/2010/05/free-portal/ |title=Steam Arrives on Mac, Includes Free Portal |work=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |first=Chris |last=Kohler |date=May 12, 2010 |accessdate=May 15, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222224446/https://www.wired.com/2010/05/free-portal/ |url-status=live |archivedate=December 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Valve}}\n\n{{featured list}}\n\n[[Category:Valve Corporation games| ]]\n[[Category:Video game lists by company|Valve]]\n", "name_user": "IceWelder", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGames", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Valve_games"}
{"title_page": "Calvin University", "text_new": "{{about||the Presbyterian university in South Korea|Calvin University (South Korea)|the Swiss secondary school|Coll\u00e8ge Calvin}}\n{{primary sources|date=November 2016}}\n{{Coord|42|55|49|N|85|35|17|W|type:edu_region:US|display=title}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = Calvin University\n| former_name = Calvin College\n| image = Calvin College seal.svg\n| image_size = 150px\n| image_name = \n| motto = My heart I offer to you, O Lord, promptly and sincerely\n| religious_affiliation = [[Christian Reformed Church in North America|Christian Reformed Church]]\n| established = 1876\n| type = [[Private university|Private]]\n| faculty = 328<ref name=\"Faculty\">{{Cite web | title = 2019 Fall Day 10 Report | work = | publisher = Calvin University | url = https://calvin.edu/offices-services/enrollment-research/reports/archives/2019/2019-fall-census-day-10-report.pdf | accessdate = April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n| president = [[Michael K. Le Roy]]\n| students = 3,570<ref name=day10report>{{Cite web | title = Fall Census (Day 10) Report | work = | publisher = Calvin University | url = https://calvin.edu/offices-services/enrollment-research/reports/| format = | accessdate = 20 November 2019}}</ref>\n| city = [[Grand Rapids, Michigan|Grand Rapids]]\n| state = [[Michigan]]\n| country = United States\n| endowment = $160.8 million (2018)<ref name=usnwr>{{Cite web | title = Calvin University | work =  | publisher = US News | url = https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/calvin-university-2241| format = | accessdate = April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n| campus = [[Suburban]] (390 acres)\n| athletics = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[NCAA Division III|Division III]] \u2013 [[Michigan Intercollegiate Athletic Association|MIAA]]\n| nickname = [[Calvin Knights|Knights]]\n| colors = Maroon and Gold  {{color box|maroon}}&nbsp;{{color box|gold}}\n| affiliations = {{hlist | [[Calvin Theological Seminary]] | [[Council for Christian Colleges and Universities|CCCU]] | [[Council of Independent Colleges|CIC]] | [[International Association for Promotion of Christian Higher Education|IAPCHE]]}}\n| website = {{official URL}}\n| logo = \n}}\n\n'''Calvin University,''' formerly '''Calvin College''',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://calvin.edu/vision2030/|title=Vision 2030|last=University|first=Calvin|last2=3201 Burton SE|first2=Grand Rapids|website=Calvin University|language=en|access-date=2019-07-09|last3=Info@calvin.edu|first3=(616) 526-6000 {{!}} 1-800-688-0122 {{!}}}}</ref><ref name=\"woodtv.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.woodtv.com/news/grand-rapids/calvin-college-changing-to-university/|title=Calvin College changing to university|date=2019-07-08|website=WOODTV.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref> is a private [[Christianity|Christian]] [[university]]<ref name=\"woodtv.com\"/> in [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]]. Founded in 1876, Calvin University is an educational institution of the [[Christian Reformed Church in North America|Christian Reformed Church]] and stands in the [[Reformed churches|Reformed tradition]] of [[Protestantism]].<ref name=usnwr /> Known as Calvin College for most of its history, the school is named after [[John Calvin]], the 16th-century [[Protestant Reformation|Protestant Reformer]].\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n==History==\nThe [[Christian Reformed Church in North America]] founded the school on August 4, 1876, as part of ''Calvin College and Theological Seminary'' (with the seminary becoming [[Calvin Theological Seminary]]) to train church ministers. The college and seminary began with seven students, in a rented upper room on Spring Street, in Grand Rapids, Michigan. The initial six-year [[curriculum]] included four years of literary studies and two years of [[theology]]. In 1892, the campus moved to the intersection of Madison Avenue and Franklin Street (Fifth Avenue) in Grand Rapids. In September 1894, the school expanded the curriculum for those who were not pre-theological students, effectually making the institution a preparatory school. In 1900, the curriculum further broadened, making it more attractive to students interested in teaching or preparing for professional courses at universities.  In 1901, Calvin admitted the first women to the school.<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web  | last =   | first =   | authorlink =   | coauthors =   | title = History  | work =   | publisher = Calvin University  | date =  | url = https://calvin.edu/about/history/   | doi =   | accessdate = 30 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1906, the literary department of the college became known as ''John Calvin Junior College'' and the college held its first commencement.<ref name=\"History\"/>  The student newspaper ''Chimes'' was first published in 1907. Around 1910, the West Michigan cities of Muskegon and Kalamazoo fought to have Calvin relocate to their respective cities. Muskegon offered [[US$]]10,000 (approximately $260,000 in 2015 dollars) and a tract of land to attract the college. The city of Grand Rapids countered with its own $10,000 offer and the junior college chose to stay in Grand Rapids. In time, the two-year college became a four-year college, and the preparatory department was discontinued. In 1917, John Calvin Junior College moved to the Franklin Street Campus, which was the southeast edge of Grand Rapids at the time. Two years later the college appointed its first president, the [[John Hiemenga|Rev. J.J. Hiemenga]]. Then a year later, in 1920, the college officially transitioned into a four-year college following the liberal arts philosophy of the [[Vrije Universiteit|Free University]] in [[Amsterdam]] as laid out by Dutch theologian and statesman Abraham Kuyper.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kuyper|first=Abraham|title=Lectures on Calvinism: The Stone Lectures of 1898|year=2008|publisher=Hendrickson Publishers|isbn=9781598562989|pages=197|url=http://www.reformationalpublishingproject.com/pdf_books/Scanned_Books_PDF/LecturesOnCalvinism.pdf}}</ref> The next year the college awarded its first bachelor's degree. In 1924, with the opening of [[Grand Rapids Christian High School]], the college offered its last year of preparatory education, turned its focus exclusively to higher education, and opened its first dormitory. In 1925, the college began a teacher training program and, in 1926, appointed its first female faculty member, Johanna Timmer, as Dean of Women. The college dedicated its library, the Hekman Library on March 8, 1928. The college later dedicated its seminary building at the Franklin Street Campus on October 29, 1930. Still under the leadership of Rev. Hiemenga the college faced significant trouble during the [[Great Depression]] as financial hardship beset the college.<ref name=rbkuiper>{{cite web|title=Rienk B. Kuiper|url=http://www.calvin.edu/hh/seminary_presidents/semm_pres_kuiper.htm|website=Calvin University|accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the school grew slowly in these early years, by 1930 it had reached its pre-[[World War I]] size of 350-450 students. Like many colleges in the United States, the end of the war led to the fastest enrollment increase in Calvin's history.  By 1950 the enrollment had climbed to 1,270 and Calvin joined the [[Michigan Intercollegiate Athletic Association|M.I.A.A.]]. The enrollment increase led to space limitations at the Franklin Campus. William Spoelhoef became president of Calvin in 1951.<ref name=\"History\" />\n\nIn 1956, the [[Synod]] of the Christian Reformed Church authorized the college to purchase the Knollcrest Farm from J.C. Miller for $400,000 (approximately $3.6 million in 2018). Located beyond the Grand Rapids city limits at the time, the Knollcrest farm increased Calvin's campus from approximately one large city block to {{nowrap|{{convert|390|acre|km2|abbr=on}}}} with a {{nowrap|{{convert|100|acre|km2|abbr=on}}}} nature preserve.  Many were reticent about the project and the college's ability to finance it, but Spoelhof pursued the initiative. The Theological Seminary was first to move to the new campus since it did not need to be close to the rest of college,  building a new academic building and holding classes there starting in 1960. As space constraints became more noticeable on the Franklin campus, the college built its first academic building on the Knollcrest Campus and first held classes there in 1962. For the next 10 years, the college continued to operate at both the Knollcrest and Franklin campuses, until fully transitioning to the Knollcrest Campus in 1973. During the latter decades of the 20th century, Calvin grew to around 4,200 students. In 1991, the seminary and the college established separate boards of trustees.\n\nAt the turn of the millennium, Calvin began several new construction projects.  Among these were a new communications and political science building, a conference center and hotel. In 2006, Calvin announced an expansion of the Fieldhouse which was completed in the spring of 2009.<ref>{{cite web  | last = Anderson  | first = Myrna  | authorlink =   | coauthors =   | title = Calvin dedicates new fieldhouse | work =   | publisher = Calvin College  | date = 2009-02-24 | url = http://www.calvin.edu/news/2008-09/SFC-dedication/   | format =   | doi =   | accessdate = 2009-03-10|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608130957/http://www.calvin.edu/news/2008-09/SFC-dedication/|archivedate=2011-06-08}}</ref> Shortly after, in 2010, Calvin completed an extensive renovation and expansion of the Fine Arts Center, thereafter rededicated as the Covenant Fine Arts Center.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vision & Priorities: Covenant Fine Arts Center|url=http://www.calvin.edu/campaign/priorities/fac/|work=The Campaign for Calvin College|publisher=Calvin College|accessdate=26 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130531232749/http://www.calvin.edu/campaign/priorities/fac/|archive-date=31 May 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe curriculum has expanded to include professional training in a variety of fields, but the college maintains a strong commitment to a liberal arts curriculum, which the college views as a means to develop students' understanding of God's world and their place in it.\n\nThe school made national headlines in 2005 when [[President of the United States|US President]] [[George W. Bush]] served as commencement speaker.  Reactions among students and faculty were mixed.  According to the ''[[Washington Post]]'', more than 800 faculty members, alumni, students and friends of the school signed a full-page ad in the ''[[Grand Rapids Press]]'', saying that Bush's policies \"...violate many deeply held principles of Calvin College.\"<ref name=\"Fletcher\">{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/05/21/AR2005052100719.html | work=[[The Washington Post]] | title=Bush Issues Call to Service at Michigan College | first=Michael A. | last=Fletcher | date=May 22, 2005 | accessdate=April 28, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2008, ''The Capella of Calvin College'', the concert choir of Calvin under the direction of professor Joel Navarro, earned two third prizes in the Mixed and Free Category at the 37th Florilege Vocal de Tours Competition in [[Tours]], France.<ref name=florilege>{{cite web|title=2008 Choral Singing Competition's Prize List|url=http://www.florilegevocal.com/files/File/palmares_37eme_edition_GB.pdf|website=37th Florilege Vocal de Tours|accessdate=2 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325070827/http://www.florilegevocal.com/files/File/palmares_37eme_edition_GB.pdf|archive-date=2012-03-25|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2009, the college's Board of Trustees issued a controversial memo to all employees that said that faculty were prohibited from teaching, writing about, or advocating on behalf of [[homosexuality]] or homosexual issues such as [[same-sex marriage]]. Many faculty members were critical of the policy and of the way it was adopted without consultation by the board.<ref name=\"Memo\">{{cite news  | last =Murray   | first =Dave   | title = Calvin College professors call for discussion about memo warning against homosexual advocacy  | newspaper = The Grand Rapids Press  | date = August 28, 2009 | url = http://www.mlive.com/news/grand-rapids/index.ssf/2009/08/calvin_college_professors_call.html  }}</ref> The Faculty Senate, by a vote of 36-4, asked the Board to withdraw the memo.<ref>{{cite web|last=Harger|first=Jim (Oct. 1, 2009)|title=Calvin College Senate asks college to drop order on teaching about homosexuality and same-sex marriage|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/grand-rapids/index.ssf/2009/10/calvin_college_faculty_senate.html|publisher=MLive.com|accessdate=Jan 5, 2013}}</ref> The official policy of the college continues to be that the \"proper place\" for sexual relations is a \"marriage relationship between a man and a woman\".<ref>{{cite web|title=LGBT + Students and Homosexuality FAQ|url=https://calvin.edu/events/sexuality-series/lgbt-homosexuality-faq.html?dotcmsredir=1|website=Calvin University|accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, the Synod of the Christian Reformed Church of North America voted to appoint Michael K. Le Roy as the president of Calvin College,<ref>{{Cite news | title = Calvin College's New President| work = Calvin College| date = June 12, 2012 | url = http://www.calvin.edu/admin/president/inauguration/| accessdate = June 12, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120903013000/http://www.calvin.edu/admin/president/inauguration/|archivedate=2012-09-03}}</ref> succeeding President [[Gaylen J. Byker]].\nWithin months of assuming office, President Le Roy disclosed that Calvin faced a financial crisis, with $117 million in debt at the time.<ref>{{cite web|last=McVicar|first=Brian|title=Calvin College has $115 million in long-term debt, report shows|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/grand-rapids/index.ssf/2013/03/calvin_college_financial_troub.html|work=mLive|accessdate=26 August 2013|date=1 March 2013}}</ref>  As part of the debt reduction plan, Calvin successfully raised $25 million in eight months to reduce its long-term debt to $90 million and continues to implement cost-cutting measures.<ref>{{cite web|last=McVicar|first=Brian|title=How Calvin College convinced donors to give $25 million for debt relief|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/grand-rapids/index.ssf/2014/05/how_calvin_college_convinced_d.html|work=mLive|accessdate=13 August 2015|date=11 May 2014}}</ref> In September 2015, four lightly enrolled majors were reduced to minors and one minor eliminated, marking the final step in academic division prioritization.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Le Roy|first1=Michael|title=Prioritization Process Update|url=http://www.calvin.edu/admin/president/finances/|website=Calvin College|accessdate=31 December 2016|date=October 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151010084929/http://www.calvin.edu/admin/president/finances/|archivedate=2015-10-10}}</ref>\n\nCalvin College rebranded itself Calvin University on July 10, 2019, a date that matches the birthday of John Calvin, the college's namesake.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://calvin.edu/news/archive/calvin-university-coming-in-july-2019|title=Calvin University coming in July 2019|last=Kucinski|first=Matt|date=November 29, 2018|website=Calvin University|language=en|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref> As a school that already had numerous departments and centers, it was determined that a name change to Calvin University would make the college more attractive to potential students, as internationally, colleges are considered a lower academic category than a university.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://calvinchimes.org/2018/10/05/calvin-to-become-university-by-2020/|title=Calvin admin. lays groundwork for university|last=Hofman|first=Michelle|date=October 5, 2018|website=Calvin College Chimes|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nCalvin University is accredited by the [[Higher Learning Commission]] of the [[North Central Association of Colleges and Secondary Schools]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Calvin College|url=http://www.ncahlc.org/component/com_directory/Action,ShowBasic/Itemid,/instid,1312/|work=The Higher Learning Commission|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref> \nCalvin offers majors or minors in 109 academic or pre-professional fields.<ref>{{cite web|title=Majors, Minors and Programs|url=http://www.calvin.edu/academics/majors-minors/|work=Calvin University|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref> The most popular majors are engineering, business, and nursing.<ref name=princeton>{{cite web|title=Calvin College|url=http://www.princetonreview.com/schools/1023196/college/calvin-college|work=The Princeton Review|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref> Calvin is a member of the [[Council for Christian Colleges and Universities]]<ref name=cccu>{{cite web|title=Members & Affiliates|url=http://www.cccu.org/members_and_affiliates?camp_init=C|work=Council for Christian Colleges & Universities|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref>  and as an institution in the [[Reformed churches|Reformed tradition of Christianity]], subscribes to a robust theology that produces a high regard for participating in and forming culture.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thefish.com/music/reviews/11617510/Newsflash%3a-Christian-colleges-discover-secular-music!/ | title=Newsflash: Christian colleges discover secular music! | publisher=[[Christianity Today International]] | accessdate=November 29, 2011 | author=Kate Bowman}}</ref>\n\n===Core curriculum===\nBecause Calvin is a liberal arts college, it has established a core curriculum with three parts: Gateway, Competencies and Studies, and Capstone.  The average student takes 45 hours of core courses in the course of a four-year degree at Calvin.\n\nWhen students matriculate into Calvin, they begin their studies with a first-year, ''Core Gateway'' seminar which introduces students to issues of learning, identity, vocation, discernment, and awareness through discussions and presentations. Students also take Developing a Christian Mind (DCM) in the discipline of their choice, a course which (through the lenses of various academic disciplines)  introduces the idea of Christian worldview and faith-based engagement with culture.\n\nCalvin students are required to take a number of essential classes focusing on ''Core Competencies and Core Studies''.  Core Competencies, such as written rhetoric, world language, and information technology, develop skills essential to success in the academic and professional worlds. Core studies courses introduce students to a variety of disciplines, providing them with a greater understanding of the world and integration of ideas essential to a well-rounded liberal arts education. Typically a number of core courses will overlap with major and minor requirements.\n\nThe ''Capstone'' course, generally taken during the senior year, draws together themes and concepts from the core curriculum. Some Capstone course are intended for students of specific majors, while others may be unrelated to a student's chosen major(s) and minor(s), such as PHIL 205: Ethics, which can qualify as the capstone course for students of any major, including non-philosophy majors.<ref>https://catalog.calvin.edu/content.php?catoid=15&navoid=483</ref>\n\n===Off-campus programs===\nCalvin offers a large number of off-campus programs and ranks 2nd out of baccalaureate institutions for the number of students who study abroad each year.<ref name=\"Study Abroad Ranking\">{{cite web|title=Open Doors Data|url=http://www.iie.org/Research-and-Publications/Open-Doors/Data/US-Study-Abroad/Leading-Institutions-by-Institutional-Type/2013-14/|work=Institute of International Education|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Semester programs====\nCalvin runs 11 of its own off-campus semester programs.  These programs are led by Calvin faculty to ensure that students receive the same caliber of education that they would receive on campus.  These programs are currently offered in the [[United Kingdom]], [[China]], [[France]], [[Germany]], [[Ghana]], [[Honduras]], [[Hungary]], [[Peru]], [[Spain]], and [[Washington, D.C.]].<ref name=\"Off Campus\">{{cite web|title=Off-Campus Programs|url=https://calvin.edu/offices-services/off-campus-programs/programs/semester-programs/|work=Calvin University|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, Calvin works with numerous other colleges to offer dozens of other off-campus programs around the world.<ref name=\"Non-Calvin Programs\">{{cite web|title=Non-Calvin Programs|url=https://calvin.edu/offices-services/off-campus-programs/programs/non-calvin-programs/|work=Calvin University|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Off-campus interim====\nCalvin also offers a variety of off-campus programs during the one-month interim term that takes place each January.  In January 2017, Calvin offered 33 different off-campus programs around the world (this number fluctuates slightly each year).<ref name=\"Off-Campus Interim\">{{cite web|title=Off-Campus Interim|url=https://calvin.edu/offices-services/off-campus-programs/programs/interim-programs/all-interims/|work=Calvin University|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n[[File:Calvin aerial.jpg|thumb|Aerial view of Calvin's campus]]\n\nCalvin acquired the {{convert|166|acre|km2|adj=on}} property in the mid-1950s and began a process of turning a biologically diverse farm into a center for Christian higher education.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rosendale|first=Lynn Bolt|title=50 Candles for Knollcrest|url=http://www.calvin.edu/publications/spark/2006/fall/knollcrest.htm|work=Spark|publisher=Calvin College|accessdate=26 August 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210191220/http://www.calvin.edu/publications/spark/2006/fall/knollcrest.htm|archivedate=2013-12-10}}</ref>  The master plan for the site was developed in 1957 by William Beye Fyfe, an adherent of the [[Prairie School]] of architecture.<ref name=master>{{cite news|title=Master Plan designer dies|url=http://www.calvin.edu/publications/spark/fall01/fyfe.htm|accessdate=20 March 2012|newspaper=The Calvin Spark|date=October 2001}}</ref> Working with President Spoelhof, Fyfe came up with a set of design principles for the campus aimed to both symbolically represent and physically promote such ideals as the [[integration of faith and learning]]; integration of administration, faculty, and students; and the inter-relatedness of all the disciplines.<ref name=\"master\" /> The integration of knowledge is symbolized in the arrangement of the academic buildings. Unlike many college campuses which feature an impressive structure, like a chapel, tower, or administrative hall, at the center of campus, Calvin has no central building. The major buildings on campus form a great circle around the Commons Lawn. The lawn was intended and serves as the common point of interaction between faculty, students, and administration.  Following the ideal of an integrated community, most buildings serve a variety of purposes. Administration is mixed with classrooms, faculty offices and lecture halls. Departments are not sequestered from other departments in separate buildings; instead many departments share facilities to encourage the solidarity of purpose and unity contributing to a strong inter-departmental character and strong Christian community.\n\n===Academic buildings===\nCalvin has nine academic buildings on campus.\n\nThe first to be constructed was Hiemenga Hall, named after John Hiemenga and built in 1961.  Hiemenga Hall houses numerous academic departments including modern languages, [[history]], [[philosophy]], classical languages, gender studies, and [[theology|religion]].  The building also houses some programs and offices.  It is connected to the campus chapel and the Spoelhof Center via tunnels.\n\nThe Spoelhof Center, named after president emeritus [[William Spoelhof]], houses the [[art]], [[education]], [[social work]] and [[sociology]] departments, the Office of the President, and several other administrative departments.  The Gezon Auditorium is also housed in the Spoelhof Center.  Dedicated in 1974, the Gezon Auditorium primarily serves as the main stage for the Calvin Theatre Company.  Like the CFAC, it has flexible lighting and sound systems and serves as a venue for concerts, lectures and other events. The Spoelhof Center connects to the Science Building and Hiemenga Hall via tunnels.\n\nThe Science Building houses many of the science departments at Calvin, including [[engineering]], [[physics]], [[astronomy]], [[psychology]] and [[nursing]].  The building also includes half of the [[Calvin-Rehoboth Robotic Observatory]].  When there are favorable skies, the observatory is open to the public on most weeknights.<ref>{{cite web|title=Calvin Observatory|url=http://www.calvin.edu/academic/phys/observatory/|work=Physics and Astronomy|publisher=Calvin University|accessdate=20 March 2012}}</ref> The Science Building is also distinctive for having been designed in the shape of a hexagon, emulating the [[benzene]] ring. In 2009, it was the backdrop for scenes of the film ''[[The Genesis Code]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Serba|first=John|title='Genesis Code' shoot on Calvin College campus has actors dressed in winter garb|url=http://www.mlive.com/entertainment/grand-rapids/index.ssf/2009/08/grand_rapids_hopefully_movie.html|accessdate=7 April 2012|newspaper=The Grand Rapids Press|date=4 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nConstructed in 1998, DeVries Hall houses classrooms, faculty offices, research labs and a greenhouse.  In addition to the [[biology]] and [[chemistry]] departments, the building houses the West Michigan Regional Lab, a consortium between the college and local hospital, Spectrum Health.\n\nAttached to DeVries Hall and the Science Building is North Hall, which houses several departments including [[economics]], [[business]], [[geology]], [[geography]], [[environmental studies]], [[computer science]], and [[mathematics]].\n\nTo the west of North Hall is the Engineering Building which consists of the Prince Engineering Design Center and the Vermeer Engineering Projects Center.  The Engineering Building was constructed in 1999 and houses faculty and student research facilities, metal and wood shops, a wind tunnel, a three-dimensional printer, and an [[anechoic chamber]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Engineering Facilities|url=http://www.calvin.edu/academic/engineering/about/facilities/|work=Calvin College|accessdate=26 August 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140406112734/http://www.calvin.edu/academic/engineering/about/facilities/|archivedate=2014-04-06}}</ref>\n\nThe Spoelhof Fieldhouse Complex, located on the north end of campus, houses a number of classrooms and houses the [[Kinesiology]] department. The fieldhouse underwent a major renovation and expansion in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=Spoelhof Fieldhouse Complex|url=http://www.calvin.edu/map/sfc/|work=Campus Map|publisher=Calvin University|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Covenant Fine Arts Center is one of the most recognizable buildings on campus, given its giant heptagon shape.  Designed around the central auditorium, which seats 1,011, the CFAC houses the [[Music]] and [[English language|English]] departments.  The CFAC auditorium is the preeminent musical performance space on campus featuring exceptional acoustics.  At the back of the stage is the 39 rank, 32 stop mechanical action organ built by [http://www.schlickerorgans.com/about.htm Schlicker] [[Organ (music)|Organ]] Company in 1966. Since its opening, the CFAC has hosted over 18,000 events. The auditorium is designed for versatility and is equipped with acoustical curtains, shifting acoustic deflection panels, a stage lift, and three catwalks. The building was closed for 2009-2010 for extensive remodeling.\n\n[[File:Calvin Crossing in Winter.jpg|thumb|right|Calvin Crossing]]\n\nIn 2002, the DeVos Communication Center was constructed across the East Beltline Road.  It is connected to west campus by the Calvin Crossing bridge. The building's upper level houses department and faculty offices for both the political science and communications arts and sciences departments.  Additionally, there is a suite of audiology and speech pathology classrooms and facilities including a working clinic.  The lower level of the building features media production and consumption facilities such as the Bytwerk Video Theatre, an audio studio, [[sound stage]], control room, and editing suites for audio and video production.  The ground floor features classrooms, a public atrium, and a snack shop.\n\n===Hekman Library===\n\nBeginning in 1917 with 3,500 volumes, Calvin's \"library room\" eventually became the modern Hekman Library now boasting over one million volumes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Library Statistics|url=https://library.calvin.edu/about/statistics|work=Hekman Library|publisher=Calvin University|accessdate=20 November 2019}}</ref> The collection's emphasis is on works in the traditional liberal arts disciplines. The library's strongest collections are in [[Theology]], [[Religion]], [[American literature]], [[British literature]], and [[Philosophy]].\n\nIn terms of books, serial backfiles, and other paper materials held, Hekman Library is currently the largest private academic library in the state.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hekman Library|url=http://www.wolframalpha.com/input/?i=biggest+libraries+in+michigan|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe H. Henry Meeter Center for Calvin Studies is located in the Hekman Library.  The center specializes in John Calvin and Calvinism.  With many rare items, books, manuscripts, articles and literature, the Meeter Center is the largest collection of Calvin materials in North America.<ref>{{cite web|title=Meeter Center|url=http://www.calvin.edu/meeter/about/|publisher=Calvin University|accessdate=20 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Athletic facilities==\nThe Spoelhof Fieldhouse Complex is home to the combined health, physical education, recreation, dance and sport department.  In Spring 2007, the college began a $50 million construction project to renovate and expand the Calvin Fieldhouse.  The fieldhouse reopened in Spring 2009 as the Spoelhof Fieldhouse Complex. The {{convert|362000|sqft|m2}} facility includes a new 5,000 seat arena ([[Van Noord Arena]]) which is currently the largest arena in a Division III school, an Olympic-regulation swimming pool (Venema Aquatic Center) which seats about 550, a tennis and track center (Huizenga Tennis and Track Center) containing 4 tennis courts and a 200-meter track, {{convert|14000|sqft|m2}} of weight training rooms and a custom made rock climbing wall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://calvin.edu/athletics/facilities/|title=Athletic Facilities|publisher=calvin.edu|accessdate=2019-04-05}}</ref> The Hoogenboom Health and Recreation Center contains the original renovated gym that is now used for basketball, volleyball, PE classes, intramurals, and many concerts.  The Hoogenboom Center also has two dance studios as well as racquetball courts and exercise science laboratories.\n\n===Chapel===\n[[File:Calvin Chapel.jpg|thumb|left|Calvin University Chapel]]\n\nThough always part of the master plan, the Chapel was not built until the late 1980s.  The chapel holds daily services in a protected time slot to ensure that all students and faculty members are able to attend the 20 minute worship services if they so choose. Chapel services follow a weekly rhythm and each day of the week has a different theme (Believe, Behold, Belong, Be Still, and Be Loud).<ref>{{cite web|title=Chapel|url=http://www.calvin.edu/faith/worship/chapel.html|work=Calvin University|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nDesigned by GMB Architects, the chapel sits at the highest point of the academic circle and its spire rises above all of the academic buildings.  Shaped as an octagon, with seating in the round, the Chapel offers exceptional acoustics for both instrumental and vocal music, in addition to the spoken word.  The Chapel also features a large organ built by [[Dobson Pipe Organ Builders]].  The three manual instrument features mechanical key action with a detached console.  The facade pipes, made of 75% burnished tin, conceal some 2,500 pipes.  In addition to the sanctuary, the Chapel has small prayer rooms, meeting spaces, a kitchen, theatre storage and rehearsal spaces.\n\nA tunnel system connecting to the Spoelhof Center creates an outdoor plaza at ground level and the multi-use Lab Theatre below.  The Lab Theatre is a blackbox theatre built in 1988 as a part of the chapel building project.<ref>{{cite web|title=Theater Locations: Behind the Scenes|url=http://www.calvin.edu/academic/cas/ctc/theaters/more-info.html|work=Calvin Theatre Company|publisher=Calvin University|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Bunker Interpretive Center===\nThe Bunker Interpretive Center is located in Calvin's nature preserve and serves as the home base for formal programs and an educational resource for the approximately 5,000 casual visitors that the Calvin University Ecosystem Preserve & Native Gardens receives annually.  The Bunker Interpretive Center is Gold [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] certified.<ref>{{cite web|title=Calvin College Bunker Interpretive Center|url=http://www.usgbc.org/projects/calvin-college-bunker-interpretive-cente|work=U.S. Green Building Council|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n\n===Residence life===\n\nCalvin has seven residence halls on campus which house the majority of the [[freshman]] and [[Sophomore year|sophomore]] classes, as the college has a policy that forces most first and second year students to live on campus. First and second year students may live off-campus if they lodge with their parents, it has been more than two years since their high school graduation date, or if they qualify for a rare exception.\n\nOne of the most notable events put on by residence life is \"Chaos Day\", during which the residents of each of the halls have their own theme, decorate their dorm, and dress in costumes to compete in a number of relay races and similar games.<ref>{{cite news|last=Struyk|first=Ryan|title=Underclassmen, dorm leadership rally for Chaos Day|url=http://www.calvin.edu/chimes/2012/09/06/underclassmen-dorm-leadership-rally-for-chaos-day/|accessdate=26 August 2013|newspaper=Chimes|date=7 September 2012}}</ref> The dorm building Schultze-Eldersveld has traditionally dominated the Chaos Day competition and has the most victories of any hall.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Buitenhuis|first1=Ericka|title=45 Years of Chaos Day: The Making of Calvin\u2019s Coveted Competition|url=http://www.calvin.edu/chimes/2014/09/13/45-years-of-chaos-day-the-making-of-calvins-coveted-competition/|website=Chimes|accessdate=31 December 2016|date=12 September 2014}}</ref> Floor Serenades, when one floor goes around campus singing songs to other floors,<ref>{{cite web|last=Graff|first=Allison R.|title=After-hours at Calvin|url=http://www.calvin.edu/verge/2012/fall/after-hours-at-calvin|work=Verge|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref> and Floor Dates, when two or more floors plan an activity together in order to meet new people, are common occurrences on campus.\n\n===Student Activities Office and The Calvin Concert Series===\n\nThe Student Activities Office at Calvin plans and hosts many films, concerts, and lectures aimed to foster cultural engagement and discernment in a Christian context.  The Student Activities Office shows a wide variety of popular and lesser-known films throughout the year.  Admission to these films, hosted in the Covenant Fine Arts Center, is $1.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://www.calvin.edu/sao/about-us.html|work=Student Activities Office|publisher=Calvin University|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ben Harper at Calvin College.jpg|thumb|[[Ben Harper and the Innocent Criminals]] live at Calvin College, 2000|345x345px]]\n\nCalvin is also notable for its extensive concert series. Before each concert, Calvin hosts a question and answer session with students and the artist. These sessions are meant to give artists a way to converse with students about their music and art. Calvin has hosted a variety of acts including:<ref>{{cite web|title=Calendar|url=http://www.calvin.edu/sao/calendar/|work=Student Activities Office|publisher=Calvin University|access-date=30 December 2016|date=September 2016}}</ref> Fun., Switchfoot, Death Cab for Cutie, Sufjan Stevens, MuteMath, Gungor, MGMT, the Soil & the Sun, Twin Forks, Ingrid Michaelson, Home Free, Regina Spektor, Over the Rhine, Anberlin, Jon Foreman, Peter Rollins and David Bazan, Kishi Bashi, All Sons & Daughters, NEEDTOBREATHE, Shad, Miracles of Modern Science, Diego Garcia, San Fermin, The Brilliance, Delorean, Pop Scholars, Okkervil River, The Head and The Heart, The National, Julianna Barwick, Lone Bellow, The Milk Carton Kids, Lily & Madeleine, Lecrae. The January Series also offers a wide selection of authors, singers, and musicians.\n\nBecause of its extensive and varied concert series, the Student Activities Office has faced controversy over the years.  In September 2010, the college canceled a concert by Canadian indie rock band, [[The New Pornographers]]. According to an official statement released by Calvin, the concert was cancelled after several complaints were made due to the band's name referring to pornography.<ref>{{cite news|title=Calvin College CANCELS New Pornographers Concert Over Band's Name|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/09/15/calvin-college-cancels-ne_n_717494.html|accessdate=26 August 2013|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=15 September 2010}}</ref> [[Fun (band)|Fun.]]'s advocacy of changed marriage laws when Calvin hosted them in 2012 was also met with significant controversy.<ref name=\"Fun. Concert Controversy\">{{cite web|last=Struyk|first=Ryan|title=Role of gay marriage advocacy at Fun. concert raises concerns|url=http://www.calvin.edu/chimes/2012/10/31/role-of-gay-marriage-advocacy-at-fun-concert-raises-concerns/|accessdate=July 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Safety===\n\nCampus security and parking policy enforcement services are provided Calvin University's Campus Safety Department. Some Calvin University campus safety officers have been armed with firearms since 2008,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.campussafetymagazine.com/news/calvin-college-officers-to-carry-firearms/|title=Calvin College Officers to Carry Firearms|date=2008-04-16|website=Campus Safety Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref> a decision that the Campus Safety Department director William Corner describes as a response to concerns that the College was not adequately prepared to respond to a similar event following the 2007 Virginia Tech campus shooting.<ref name=\"calvinchimes.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://calvinchimes.org/2016/11/05/calvin-a-model-for-armed-campus-safety-officers-at-christian-colleges/|title=Calvin a model for armed campus safety officers at Christian colleges|last=Hughey|first=Maddie|date=November 5, 2016|website=Calvin College Chimes|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref> Initially, only Campus Safety supervisors who were former law enforcement and fully licensed to carry firearms on a school campus were permitted to carry firearms on Calvin's campus. At that time, all campus safety supervisors were issued collapsible batons, chemical spray and handcuffs as standard policy, even if they were not armed with a firearm.\n\nAt the time and until 2017, non-supervisory Campus Safety officers were student employees who performed their duties unarmed. In 2017, the Campus Safety Department made the decision to discontinue hiring students for non-supervisory campus safety officer roles, electing instead to hire former law enforcement officers who were licensed to carry firearms on campus. The Department continued to employ students employees as dispatchers, building security officers and customer service staff. The Campus Safety Department director, William Corner, stated that student officers were not fully qualified for the risk level of some of the incidents they were responding too. \u201cWe were putting the students in positions that, honestly, I was not comfortable with for their safety and their level of experience.\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://calvinchimes.org/2017/09/29/campus-safety-increases-staff-student-hires/|title=Campus safety increases staff, hires fewer students|last=Butler|first=Hannah|date=September 29, 2017|website=Calvin College Chimes|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, full-time, non-student Calvin College campus safety personnel began wearing body cameras while on duty. Officers are required to turn on the cameras in specific circumstances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://calvinchimes.org/2014/09/25/campus-safety-recordings-hold-both-sides-accountable/|title=Campus Safety recordings hold both sides accountable|last=Bullis|first=Jenny|date=September 25, 2014|website=Calvin College Chimes|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Calvin College was described as being a model for the arming of campus security staff at other smaller college institution in the United States.<ref name=\"calvinchimes.org\"/>\n\nA Calvin College campus safety supervisor was criminally charged with \"reckless use of a firearm\" after a November 2016 on-duty incident.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlive.com/news/grand-rapids/2017/02/calvin_campus_safety_patrol_su.html|title=Calvin campus safety patrol supervisor charged over gun incident with pedestrian|last=Tunison|first=John|date=February 16, 2017|website=mlive.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref> The armed supervisor, Lee Swafford allegedly did not fire his duty firearm in the incident that resulted in his arrest, but after a routine review of body camera footage by the Campus Safety Department director William Corner, the decision was made to place Swafford on administrative leave pending the outcome of an internal investigation. Swafford was fired by Calvin College on December 6, 2016 after an internal investigation that led to all evidence being forwarded to the Grand Rapids Police Department and then charged by Kent County persecutors in February 2017. Swafford turned himself in to police after a warrant was issued for his arrest and was then released on bail.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://calvinchimes.org/2017/02/15/campus-safety-officer-charged/|title=Former campus safety officer charged with misdemeanor|last=Hughey|first=Maddie|date=February 16, 2017|website=Calvin College Chimes|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref> In an open letter to college students, faculty, staff and visitors, College president Michael Le Roy described the officer's actions as \"deeply disappointing to me.\" He also stated that the incident had involved a campus visitor, not a student or staff member.<ref>https://calvin.edu/dotAsset/0b0c3205-a868-4753-884f-50c11e586217.pdf</ref>\n\nCalvin University implemented a \"one button\" campus lockdown system in 2017. The new [[UTC Climate, Controls & Security|Lenel]] system can lockdown every exterior door on the college campus with the push of a single button. The college has also offered active shooting training to some staff and students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://calvinchimes.org/2017/10/13/calvin-prepared-for-active-shooter/|title=Calvin prepared for active shooter|last=Ford|first=Peter|date=October 13, 2017|website=Calvin College Chimes|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n<!-- U.S. rankings -->\n| Forbes        = 266\n<!-- Regional -->\n| USNWR_REG     = 3\n}}\n\nCalvin University has approximately 3,570 students, 53.6% female and 46.4% male.<ref name=day10report /> The average class size is 24, and there is a 13:1 student/faculty ratio.<ref name=classsizeandfacultystudentratio>{{cite web|title=Key Facts|url=https://calvin.edu/about/key-facts/|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref> Michigan students comprise 55% of the student body and 12% of the students are from other countries.<ref name=day10report /> The college has an 84.6% retention rate from first to second year and a six-year graduation rate of 75.7%.<ref name=day10report /> 224 full-time faculty teach at the college and 90.6% have the terminal degree in their field.<ref name=day10report />\n\nThe middle 50% of incoming first year students at the college have a [[GPA]] (4.0 scale) between 3.45 and 3.99, an [[ACT (examination)|ACT]] composite score between 23 and 30, and a [[SAT]] Critical Reading and Math score between 1060 and 1315.<ref name=\"financialaid\">{{cite web|title=Key Facts|url=https://calvin.edu/about/key-facts/#student-profile|website=Calvin University|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nTuition is currently $33,100, room and board is $9,990, and yearly fees are about $235. Approximately 99% of students receive some sort of financial aid.<ref name=\"financialaid\"/>\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Alumni===\n{{main category|Calvin University alumni}}\n*[[Dave Agema]], 1971, Republican National Committeeman\n*[[Jon Vander Ark]], president of [[Republic Services]]\n*[[William Brashler]], author of ''The Bingo Long Traveling All-Stars and Motor Kings''<ref>https://archives.calvin.edu/?p=collections/findingaid&id=21&q=&rootcontentid=9146</ref>\n*[[Meindert DeJong]], a Dutch-born American writer of children's books who won the Hans Christian Andersen Award.\n*[[Betsy DeVos]], former chair of the Republican party in Michigan and current Secretary of Education<ref>{{cite web|last1=Westervelt|first1=Ed|title=Trump Chooses Betsy DeVos For Education Secretary|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/ed/2016/11/23/499642077/trump-chooses-betsy-devos-for-education-secretary|website=nprEd|accessdate=31 December 2016|date=23 November 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Keith DeRose]], Allison Foundation Professor of Philosophy at Yale University\n*[[Richard DeVos]], founder of Amway and Orlando Magic CEO\n*[[William K. Frankena]] 1930, moral philosopher, Chairman UofM philosophy department, Distinguished Alumnus\n*[[Hans Halvorson]], Stuart Professor of Philosophy at Princeton University\n*[[Wayne Huizenga]], businessman (attended)\n*[[Bill Huizenga]], U.S. Congressman\n*[[Rose Ibiama]] 2005, member of Academy Award-winning DreamWorks Animation teams<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://calvin.edu/publication/spark/2015/03/01/dressing-up-anna-and-elsa?dotcmsredir=1|title=Dressing up Anna and Elsa|last=|first=|date=1 March 2015|website=Spark|access-date=9 July 2017}}</ref>\n*[[M.I Abaga]], Nigerian Musician\n*[[Peter Kreeft]], Professor of Philosophy and Theology at Boston College\n*[[Marc Evan Jackson]] 1992, actor and comedian\n*[[Todd Martinez]] 1989, theoretical chemist and professor\n*[[Jeannine Oppewall]] 1968, Academy Award-nominated production designer\n*[[Alvin Plantinga]], prominent (theistic) contemporary philosopher of religion\n*[[Patricia Rozema]] 1981, filmmaker\n*[[Paul Schrader]] 1968, Academy Award-nominated screenwriter and filmmaker\n*[[Carl Strikwerda]], President of [[Elizabethtown College]]\n*[[Jay Van Andel]] Businessman, co-founder of Amway\n*[[John Van Engen]] 1969, Professor of History and [[Haskins Medal]] winner\n*[[John Witte Jr.]] 1982, [[Robert W. Woodruff Professor]] at [[Emory University School of Law]]\n\n===Faculty===\n*[[Lionel Basney]], Professor of English, poet, author, critic\n*[[Johannes Broene]], 1908-1925 teaching primarily in Philosophy and Education but also classes in History, Civics, Government, Chemistry, and Psychology\n*[[Brian Diemer]], 1986\u2013Present, Head Cross Country Coach\n*[[Vern Ehlers]], 1966\u20131982, Professor of Physics, served as U.S. Representative from Grand Rapids\n*[[John E. Hare]], 1989\u20132003, Professor of Philosophy\n*[[Paul B. Henry]], 1970\u20131978, Professor of Political Science\n*[[William Harry Jellema]], 1920\u20131936, 1948-1963 founder of Calvin's Philosophy Department\n*[[George Marsden]], 1965\u20131986, 2010\u2013present, Professor of History\n*[[Richard Mouw]], 1968\u20131985, Professor of Philosophy\n*[[Alvin Plantinga]], 1963\u20131981, Professor of Philosophy\n*[[H. Evan Runner]], 1951\u20131981, Professor of Philosophy\n*[[Gary D. Schmidt|Gary Schmidt]], 1986\u2013present, Professor of English, awarded two [[Newbery Medal|Newbery Honor]] awards for his young-adult fiction\n*[[James K.A. Smith]], 2002\u2013present, Professor of Philosophy\n*[[William Spoelhof]], 1946\u20131951, Professor of History and Political Science\n*[[Ralph Stob]], 1915\u20131964, Professor of Classics\n*[[Howard J. Van Till]], Emeritus Professor of Physics\n*[[Nicholas Wolterstorff]], 1959\u20131989, Professor of Philosophy\n\n==Athletics==\n{{Main|Calvin Knights}}\nCalvin University fields ten men's and ten women's intercollegiate teams and several club sports, known as the [[Calvin Knights]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sports & Recreation|url=http://www.calvin.edu/community/sports.html|work=Calvin University|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nStudents at Calvin publish a weekly student newspaper, ''Chimes'',<ref>{{cite web|title=TCalvin Chimes|url=https://calvin.edu/offices-services/student-organizations/calvin-chimes|publisher=Calvin University|accessdate=20 November 2019}}</ref>  and a monthly journal of arts and letters commentary, ''Dialogue''. A yearbook, ''Prism'', is also published for each school year. Student filmmakers have also made many short films and videos, like the popular [http://vimeo.com/11201881 Lipdub at Calvin College] and the super-low-budget adaptation of Homer's ''[[Iliad]]'', ''Meynin'', both in 2010.\n\nThe school distributes ''Knightfile'', a seasonal magazine on sports at the college,<ref>{{cite web|title=Knightfile|url=http://www.calvin.edu/publications/knight/|publisher=Calvin College|accessdate=20 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120127141026/http://www.calvin.edu/publications/knight/|archive-date=27 January 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>  ''Uncompressed'', a cultural discussion publication, and ''Spark'',<ref>{{cite web|title=The Calvin Spark|url=http://www.calvin.edu/spark/|publisher=Calvin University|accessdate=20 March 2012}}</ref>  a magazine for alumni and friends.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of presidents of Calvin University]]\n* [[Cornelius Van Til]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Calvin University (Michigan)}}\n* {{Official website}}\n{{Grand Rapids, Michigan}}\n{{Colleges and universities in Michigan}}\n{{CCCU}}\n{{Michigan Intercollegiate Athletic Association navbox}}\n{{Portal bar|Calvinism|Michigan|Education}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Calvin University| ]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1876]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges affiliated with the Christian Reformed Church]]\n[[Category:Education in Grand Rapids, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Kent County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Grand Rapids, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Evangelicalism in Michigan]]\n[[Category:1876 establishments in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Council for Christian Colleges and Universities]]\n", "text_old": "{{for2|the Presbyterian university in South Korea|[[Calvin University (South Korea)]]|the Swiss secondary school|[[Coll\u00e8ge Calvin]]}}\n{{primary sources|date=November 2016}}\n{{Coord|42|55|49|N|85|35|17|W|type:edu_region:US|display=title}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = Calvin University\n| former_name = Calvin College\n| image = Calvin College seal.svg\n| image_size = 150px\n| image_name = \n| motto = My heart I offer to you, O Lord, promptly and sincerely\n| religious_affiliation = [[Christian Reformed Church in North America|Christian Reformed Church]]\n| established = 1876\n| type = [[Private university|Private]]\n| faculty = 328<ref name=\"Faculty\">{{Cite web | title = 2019 Fall Day 10 Report | work = | publisher = Calvin University | url = https://calvin.edu/offices-services/enrollment-research/reports/archives/2019/2019-fall-census-day-10-report.pdf | accessdate = April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n| president = [[Michael K. Le Roy]]\n| students = 3,570<ref name=day10report>{{Cite web | title = Fall Census (Day 10) Report | work = | publisher = Calvin University | url = https://calvin.edu/offices-services/enrollment-research/reports/| format = | accessdate = 20 November 2019}}</ref>\n| city = [[Grand Rapids, Michigan|Grand Rapids]]\n| state = [[Michigan]]\n| country = United States\n| endowment = $160.8 million (2018)<ref name=usnwr>{{Cite web | title = Calvin University | work =  | publisher = US News | url = https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/calvin-university-2241| format = | accessdate = April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n| campus = [[Suburban]] (390 acres)\n| athletics = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[NCAA Division III|Division III]] \u2013 [[Michigan Intercollegiate Athletic Association|MIAA]]\n| nickname = [[Calvin Knights|Knights]]\n| colors = Maroon and Gold  {{color box|maroon}}&nbsp;{{color box|gold}}\n| affiliations = {{hlist | [[Calvin Theological Seminary]] | [[Council for Christian Colleges and Universities|CCCU]] | [[Council of Independent Colleges|CIC]] | [[International Association for Promotion of Christian Higher Education|IAPCHE]]}}\n| website = {{official URL}}\n| logo = \n}}\n\n'''Calvin University,''' formerly '''Calvin College''',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://calvin.edu/vision2030/|title=Vision 2030|last=University|first=Calvin|last2=3201 Burton SE|first2=Grand Rapids|website=Calvin University|language=en|access-date=2019-07-09|last3=Info@calvin.edu|first3=(616) 526-6000 {{!}} 1-800-688-0122 {{!}}}}</ref><ref name=\"woodtv.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.woodtv.com/news/grand-rapids/calvin-college-changing-to-university/|title=Calvin College changing to university|date=2019-07-08|website=WOODTV.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref> is a private [[Christianity|Christian]] [[university]]<ref name=\"woodtv.com\"/> in [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]]. Founded in 1876, Calvin University is an educational institution of the [[Christian Reformed Church in North America|Christian Reformed Church]] and stands in the [[Reformed churches|Reformed tradition]] of [[Protestantism]].<ref name=usnwr /> Known as Calvin College for most of its history, the school is named after [[John Calvin]], the 16th-century [[Protestant Reformation|Protestant Reformer]].\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n==History==\nThe [[Christian Reformed Church in North America]] founded the school on August 4, 1876, as part of ''Calvin College and Theological Seminary'' (with the seminary becoming [[Calvin Theological Seminary]]) to train church ministers. The college and seminary began with seven students, in a rented upper room on Spring Street, in Grand Rapids, Michigan. The initial six-year [[curriculum]] included four years of literary studies and two years of [[theology]]. In 1892, the campus moved to the intersection of Madison Avenue and Franklin Street (Fifth Avenue) in Grand Rapids. In September 1894, the school expanded the curriculum for those who were not pre-theological students, effectually making the institution a preparatory school. In 1900, the curriculum further broadened, making it more attractive to students interested in teaching or preparing for professional courses at universities.  In 1901, Calvin admitted the first women to the school.<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web  | last =   | first =   | authorlink =   | coauthors =   | title = History  | work =   | publisher = Calvin University  | date =  | url = https://calvin.edu/about/history/   | doi =   | accessdate = 30 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1906, the literary department of the college became known as ''John Calvin Junior College'' and the college held its first commencement.<ref name=\"History\"/>  The student newspaper ''Chimes'' was first published in 1907. Around 1910, the West Michigan cities of Muskegon and Kalamazoo fought to have Calvin relocate to their respective cities. Muskegon offered [[US$]]10,000 (approximately $260,000 in 2015 dollars) and a tract of land to attract the college. The city of Grand Rapids countered with its own $10,000 offer and the junior college chose to stay in Grand Rapids. In time, the two-year college became a four-year college, and the preparatory department was discontinued. In 1917, John Calvin Junior College moved to the Franklin Street Campus, which was the southeast edge of Grand Rapids at the time. Two years later the college appointed its first president, the [[John Hiemenga|Rev. J.J. Hiemenga]]. Then a year later, in 1920, the college officially transitioned into a four-year college following the liberal arts philosophy of the [[Vrije Universiteit|Free University]] in [[Amsterdam]] as laid out by Dutch theologian and statesman Abraham Kuyper.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kuyper|first=Abraham|title=Lectures on Calvinism: The Stone Lectures of 1898|year=2008|publisher=Hendrickson Publishers|isbn=9781598562989|pages=197|url=http://www.reformationalpublishingproject.com/pdf_books/Scanned_Books_PDF/LecturesOnCalvinism.pdf}}</ref> The next year the college awarded its first bachelor's degree. In 1924, with the opening of [[Grand Rapids Christian High School]], the college offered its last year of preparatory education, turned its focus exclusively to higher education, and opened its first dormitory. In 1925, the college began a teacher training program and, in 1926, appointed its first female faculty member, Johanna Timmer, as Dean of Women. The college dedicated its library, the Hekman Library on March 8, 1928. The college later dedicated its seminary building at the Franklin Street Campus on October 29, 1930. Still under the leadership of Rev. Hiemenga the college faced significant trouble during the [[Great Depression]] as financial hardship beset the college.<ref name=rbkuiper>{{cite web|title=Rienk B. Kuiper|url=http://www.calvin.edu/hh/seminary_presidents/semm_pres_kuiper.htm|website=Calvin University|accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the school grew slowly in these early years, by 1930 it had reached its pre-[[World War I]] size of 350-450 students. Like many colleges in the United States, the end of the war led to the fastest enrollment increase in Calvin's history.  By 1950 the enrollment had climbed to 1,270 and Calvin joined the [[Michigan Intercollegiate Athletic Association|M.I.A.A.]]. The enrollment increase led to space limitations at the Franklin Campus. William Spoelhoef became president of Calvin in 1951.<ref name=\"History\" />\n\nIn 1956, the [[Synod]] of the Christian Reformed Church authorized the college to purchase the Knollcrest Farm from J.C. Miller for $400,000 (approximately $3.6 million in 2018). Located beyond the Grand Rapids city limits at the time, the Knollcrest farm increased Calvin's campus from approximately one large city block to {{nowrap|{{convert|390|acre|km2|abbr=on}}}} with a {{nowrap|{{convert|100|acre|km2|abbr=on}}}} nature preserve.  Many were reticent about the project and the college's ability to finance it, but Spoelhof pursued the initiative. The Theological Seminary was first to move to the new campus since it did not need to be close to the rest of college,  building a new academic building and holding classes there starting in 1960. As space constraints became more noticeable on the Franklin campus, the college built its first academic building on the Knollcrest Campus and first held classes there in 1962. For the next 10 years, the college continued to operate at both the Knollcrest and Franklin campuses, until fully transitioning to the Knollcrest Campus in 1973. During the latter decades of the 20th century, Calvin grew to around 4,200 students. In 1991, the seminary and the college established separate boards of trustees.\n\nAt the turn of the millennium, Calvin began several new construction projects.  Among these were a new communications and political science building, a conference center and hotel. In 2006, Calvin announced an expansion of the Fieldhouse which was completed in the spring of 2009.<ref>{{cite web  | last = Anderson  | first = Myrna  | authorlink =   | coauthors =   | title = Calvin dedicates new fieldhouse | work =   | publisher = Calvin College  | date = 2009-02-24 | url = http://www.calvin.edu/news/2008-09/SFC-dedication/   | format =   | doi =   | accessdate = 2009-03-10|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608130957/http://www.calvin.edu/news/2008-09/SFC-dedication/|archivedate=2011-06-08}}</ref> Shortly after, in 2010, Calvin completed an extensive renovation and expansion of the Fine Arts Center, thereafter rededicated as the Covenant Fine Arts Center.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vision & Priorities: Covenant Fine Arts Center|url=http://www.calvin.edu/campaign/priorities/fac/|work=The Campaign for Calvin College|publisher=Calvin College|accessdate=26 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130531232749/http://www.calvin.edu/campaign/priorities/fac/|archive-date=31 May 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe curriculum has expanded to include professional training in a variety of fields, but the college maintains a strong commitment to a liberal arts curriculum, which the college views as a means to develop students' understanding of God's world and their place in it.\n\nThe school made national headlines in 2005 when [[President of the United States|US President]] [[George W. Bush]] served as commencement speaker.  Reactions among students and faculty were mixed.  According to the ''[[Washington Post]]'', more than 800 faculty members, alumni, students and friends of the school signed a full-page ad in the ''[[Grand Rapids Press]]'', saying that Bush's policies \"...violate many deeply held principles of Calvin College.\"<ref name=\"Fletcher\">{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/05/21/AR2005052100719.html | work=[[The Washington Post]] | title=Bush Issues Call to Service at Michigan College | first=Michael A. | last=Fletcher | date=May 22, 2005 | accessdate=April 28, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2008, ''The Capella of Calvin College'', the concert choir of Calvin under the direction of professor Joel Navarro, earned two third prizes in the Mixed and Free Category at the 37th Florilege Vocal de Tours Competition in [[Tours]], France.<ref name=florilege>{{cite web|title=2008 Choral Singing Competition's Prize List|url=http://www.florilegevocal.com/files/File/palmares_37eme_edition_GB.pdf|website=37th Florilege Vocal de Tours|accessdate=2 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325070827/http://www.florilegevocal.com/files/File/palmares_37eme_edition_GB.pdf|archive-date=2012-03-25|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2009, the college's Board of Trustees issued a controversial memo to all employees that said that faculty were prohibited from teaching, writing about, or advocating on behalf of [[homosexuality]] or homosexual issues such as [[same-sex marriage]]. Many faculty members were critical of the policy and of the way it was adopted without consultation by the board.<ref name=\"Memo\">{{cite news  | last =Murray   | first =Dave   | title = Calvin College professors call for discussion about memo warning against homosexual advocacy  | newspaper = The Grand Rapids Press  | date = August 28, 2009 | url = http://www.mlive.com/news/grand-rapids/index.ssf/2009/08/calvin_college_professors_call.html  }}</ref> The Faculty Senate, by a vote of 36-4, asked the Board to withdraw the memo.<ref>{{cite web|last=Harger|first=Jim (Oct. 1, 2009)|title=Calvin College Senate asks college to drop order on teaching about homosexuality and same-sex marriage|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/grand-rapids/index.ssf/2009/10/calvin_college_faculty_senate.html|publisher=MLive.com|accessdate=Jan 5, 2013}}</ref> The official policy of the college continues to be that the \"proper place\" for sexual relations is a \"marriage relationship between a man and a woman\".<ref>{{cite web|title=LGBT + Students and Homosexuality FAQ|url=https://calvin.edu/events/sexuality-series/lgbt-homosexuality-faq.html?dotcmsredir=1|website=Calvin University|accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, the Synod of the Christian Reformed Church of North America voted to appoint Michael K. Le Roy as the president of Calvin College,<ref>{{Cite news | title = Calvin College's New President| work = Calvin College| date = June 12, 2012 | url = http://www.calvin.edu/admin/president/inauguration/| accessdate = June 12, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120903013000/http://www.calvin.edu/admin/president/inauguration/|archivedate=2012-09-03}}</ref> succeeding President [[Gaylen J. Byker]].\nWithin months of assuming office, President Le Roy disclosed that Calvin faced a financial crisis, with $117 million in debt at the time.<ref>{{cite web|last=McVicar|first=Brian|title=Calvin College has $115 million in long-term debt, report shows|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/grand-rapids/index.ssf/2013/03/calvin_college_financial_troub.html|work=mLive|accessdate=26 August 2013|date=1 March 2013}}</ref>  As part of the debt reduction plan, Calvin successfully raised $25 million in eight months to reduce its long-term debt to $90 million and continues to implement cost-cutting measures.<ref>{{cite web|last=McVicar|first=Brian|title=How Calvin College convinced donors to give $25 million for debt relief|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/grand-rapids/index.ssf/2014/05/how_calvin_college_convinced_d.html|work=mLive|accessdate=13 August 2015|date=11 May 2014}}</ref> In September 2015, four lightly enrolled majors were reduced to minors and one minor eliminated, marking the final step in academic division prioritization.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Le Roy|first1=Michael|title=Prioritization Process Update|url=http://www.calvin.edu/admin/president/finances/|website=Calvin College|accessdate=31 December 2016|date=October 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151010084929/http://www.calvin.edu/admin/president/finances/|archivedate=2015-10-10}}</ref>\n\nCalvin College rebranded itself Calvin University on July 10, 2019, a date that matches the birthday of John Calvin, the college's namesake.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://calvin.edu/news/archive/calvin-university-coming-in-july-2019|title=Calvin University coming in July 2019|last=Kucinski|first=Matt|date=November 29, 2018|website=Calvin University|language=en|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref> As a school that already had numerous departments and centers, it was determined that a name change to Calvin University would make the college more attractive to potential students, as internationally, colleges are considered a lower academic category than a university.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://calvinchimes.org/2018/10/05/calvin-to-become-university-by-2020/|title=Calvin admin. lays groundwork for university|last=Hofman|first=Michelle|date=October 5, 2018|website=Calvin College Chimes|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nCalvin University is accredited by the [[Higher Learning Commission]] of the [[North Central Association of Colleges and Secondary Schools]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Calvin College|url=http://www.ncahlc.org/component/com_directory/Action,ShowBasic/Itemid,/instid,1312/|work=The Higher Learning Commission|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref> \nCalvin offers majors or minors in 109 academic or pre-professional fields.<ref>{{cite web|title=Majors, Minors and Programs|url=http://www.calvin.edu/academics/majors-minors/|work=Calvin University|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref> The most popular majors are engineering, business, and nursing.<ref name=princeton>{{cite web|title=Calvin College|url=http://www.princetonreview.com/schools/1023196/college/calvin-college|work=The Princeton Review|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref> Calvin is a member of the [[Council for Christian Colleges and Universities]]<ref name=cccu>{{cite web|title=Members & Affiliates|url=http://www.cccu.org/members_and_affiliates?camp_init=C|work=Council for Christian Colleges & Universities|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref>  and as an institution in the [[Reformed churches|Reformed tradition of Christianity]], subscribes to a robust theology that produces a high regard for participating in and forming culture.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thefish.com/music/reviews/11617510/Newsflash%3a-Christian-colleges-discover-secular-music!/ | title=Newsflash: Christian colleges discover secular music! | publisher=[[Christianity Today International]] | accessdate=November 29, 2011 | author=Kate Bowman}}</ref>\n\n===Core curriculum===\nBecause Calvin is a liberal arts college, it has established a core curriculum with three parts: Gateway, Competencies and Studies, and Capstone.  The average student takes 45 hours of core courses in the course of a four-year degree at Calvin.\n\nWhen students matriculate into Calvin, they begin their studies with a first-year, ''Core Gateway'' seminar which introduces students to issues of learning, identity, vocation, discernment, and awareness through discussions and presentations. Students also take Developing a Christian Mind (DCM) in the discipline of their choice, a course which (through the lenses of various academic disciplines)  introduces the idea of Christian worldview and faith-based engagement with culture.\n\nCalvin students are required to take a number of essential classes focusing on ''Core Competencies and Core Studies''.  Core Competencies, such as written rhetoric, world language, and information technology, develop skills essential to success in the academic and professional worlds. Core studies courses introduce students to a variety of disciplines, providing them with a greater understanding of the world and integration of ideas essential to a well-rounded liberal arts education. Typically a number of core courses will overlap with major and minor requirements.\n\nThe ''Capstone'' course, generally taken during the senior year, draws together themes and concepts from the core curriculum. Some Capstone course are intended for students of specific majors, while others may be unrelated to a student's chosen major(s) and minor(s), such as PHIL 205: Ethics, which can qualify as the capstone course for students of any major, including non-philosophy majors.<ref>https://catalog.calvin.edu/content.php?catoid=15&navoid=483</ref>\n\n===Off-campus programs===\nCalvin offers a large number of off-campus programs and ranks 2nd out of baccalaureate institutions for the number of students who study abroad each year.<ref name=\"Study Abroad Ranking\">{{cite web|title=Open Doors Data|url=http://www.iie.org/Research-and-Publications/Open-Doors/Data/US-Study-Abroad/Leading-Institutions-by-Institutional-Type/2013-14/|work=Institute of International Education|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Semester programs====\nCalvin runs 11 of its own off-campus semester programs.  These programs are led by Calvin faculty to ensure that students receive the same caliber of education that they would receive on campus.  These programs are currently offered in the [[United Kingdom]], [[China]], [[France]], [[Germany]], [[Ghana]], [[Honduras]], [[Hungary]], [[Peru]], [[Spain]], and [[Washington, D.C.]].<ref name=\"Off Campus\">{{cite web|title=Off-Campus Programs|url=https://calvin.edu/offices-services/off-campus-programs/programs/semester-programs/|work=Calvin University|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, Calvin works with numerous other colleges to offer dozens of other off-campus programs around the world.<ref name=\"Non-Calvin Programs\">{{cite web|title=Non-Calvin Programs|url=https://calvin.edu/offices-services/off-campus-programs/programs/non-calvin-programs/|work=Calvin University|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Off-campus interim====\nCalvin also offers a variety of off-campus programs during the one-month interim term that takes place each January.  In January 2017, Calvin offered 33 different off-campus programs around the world (this number fluctuates slightly each year).<ref name=\"Off-Campus Interim\">{{cite web|title=Off-Campus Interim|url=https://calvin.edu/offices-services/off-campus-programs/programs/interim-programs/all-interims/|work=Calvin University|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n[[File:Calvin aerial.jpg|thumb|Aerial view of Calvin's campus]]\n\nCalvin acquired the {{convert|166|acre|km2|adj=on}} property in the mid-1950s and began a process of turning a biologically diverse farm into a center for Christian higher education.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rosendale|first=Lynn Bolt|title=50 Candles for Knollcrest|url=http://www.calvin.edu/publications/spark/2006/fall/knollcrest.htm|work=Spark|publisher=Calvin College|accessdate=26 August 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210191220/http://www.calvin.edu/publications/spark/2006/fall/knollcrest.htm|archivedate=2013-12-10}}</ref>  The master plan for the site was developed in 1957 by William Beye Fyfe, an adherent of the [[Prairie School]] of architecture.<ref name=master>{{cite news|title=Master Plan designer dies|url=http://www.calvin.edu/publications/spark/fall01/fyfe.htm|accessdate=20 March 2012|newspaper=The Calvin Spark|date=October 2001}}</ref> Working with President Spoelhof, Fyfe came up with a set of design principles for the campus aimed to both symbolically represent and physically promote such ideals as the [[integration of faith and learning]]; integration of administration, faculty, and students; and the inter-relatedness of all the disciplines.<ref name=\"master\" /> The integration of knowledge is symbolized in the arrangement of the academic buildings. Unlike many college campuses which feature an impressive structure, like a chapel, tower, or administrative hall, at the center of campus, Calvin has no central building. The major buildings on campus form a great circle around the Commons Lawn. The lawn was intended and serves as the common point of interaction between faculty, students, and administration.  Following the ideal of an integrated community, most buildings serve a variety of purposes. Administration is mixed with classrooms, faculty offices and lecture halls. Departments are not sequestered from other departments in separate buildings; instead many departments share facilities to encourage the solidarity of purpose and unity contributing to a strong inter-departmental character and strong Christian community.\n\n===Academic buildings===\nCalvin has nine academic buildings on campus.\n\nThe first to be constructed was Hiemenga Hall, named after John Hiemenga and built in 1961.  Hiemenga Hall houses numerous academic departments including modern languages, [[history]], [[philosophy]], classical languages, gender studies, and [[theology|religion]].  The building also houses some programs and offices.  It is connected to the campus chapel and the Spoelhof Center via tunnels.\n\nThe Spoelhof Center, named after president emeritus [[William Spoelhof]], houses the [[art]], [[education]], [[social work]] and [[sociology]] departments, the Office of the President, and several other administrative departments.  The Gezon Auditorium is also housed in the Spoelhof Center.  Dedicated in 1974, the Gezon Auditorium primarily serves as the main stage for the Calvin Theatre Company.  Like the CFAC, it has flexible lighting and sound systems and serves as a venue for concerts, lectures and other events. The Spoelhof Center connects to the Science Building and Hiemenga Hall via tunnels.\n\nThe Science Building houses many of the science departments at Calvin, including [[engineering]], [[physics]], [[astronomy]], [[psychology]] and [[nursing]].  The building also includes half of the [[Calvin-Rehoboth Robotic Observatory]].  When there are favorable skies, the observatory is open to the public on most weeknights.<ref>{{cite web|title=Calvin Observatory|url=http://www.calvin.edu/academic/phys/observatory/|work=Physics and Astronomy|publisher=Calvin University|accessdate=20 March 2012}}</ref> The Science Building is also distinctive for having been designed in the shape of a hexagon, emulating the [[benzene]] ring. In 2009, it was the backdrop for scenes of the film ''[[The Genesis Code]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Serba|first=John|title='Genesis Code' shoot on Calvin College campus has actors dressed in winter garb|url=http://www.mlive.com/entertainment/grand-rapids/index.ssf/2009/08/grand_rapids_hopefully_movie.html|accessdate=7 April 2012|newspaper=The Grand Rapids Press|date=4 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nConstructed in 1998, DeVries Hall houses classrooms, faculty offices, research labs and a greenhouse.  In addition to the [[biology]] and [[chemistry]] departments, the building houses the West Michigan Regional Lab, a consortium between the college and local hospital, Spectrum Health.\n\nAttached to DeVries Hall and the Science Building is North Hall, which houses several departments including [[economics]], [[business]], [[geology]], [[geography]], [[environmental studies]], [[computer science]], and [[mathematics]].\n\nTo the west of North Hall is the Engineering Building which consists of the Prince Engineering Design Center and the Vermeer Engineering Projects Center.  The Engineering Building was constructed in 1999 and houses faculty and student research facilities, metal and wood shops, a wind tunnel, a three-dimensional printer, and an [[anechoic chamber]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Engineering Facilities|url=http://www.calvin.edu/academic/engineering/about/facilities/|work=Calvin College|accessdate=26 August 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140406112734/http://www.calvin.edu/academic/engineering/about/facilities/|archivedate=2014-04-06}}</ref>\n\nThe Spoelhof Fieldhouse Complex, located on the north end of campus, houses a number of classrooms and houses the [[Kinesiology]] department. The fieldhouse underwent a major renovation and expansion in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=Spoelhof Fieldhouse Complex|url=http://www.calvin.edu/map/sfc/|work=Campus Map|publisher=Calvin University|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Covenant Fine Arts Center is one of the most recognizable buildings on campus, given its giant heptagon shape.  Designed around the central auditorium, which seats 1,011, the CFAC houses the [[Music]] and [[English language|English]] departments.  The CFAC auditorium is the preeminent musical performance space on campus featuring exceptional acoustics.  At the back of the stage is the 39 rank, 32 stop mechanical action organ built by [http://www.schlickerorgans.com/about.htm Schlicker] [[Organ (music)|Organ]] Company in 1966. Since its opening, the CFAC has hosted over 18,000 events. The auditorium is designed for versatility and is equipped with acoustical curtains, shifting acoustic deflection panels, a stage lift, and three catwalks. The building was closed for 2009-2010 for extensive remodeling.\n\n[[File:Calvin Crossing in Winter.jpg|thumb|right|Calvin Crossing]]\n\nIn 2002, the DeVos Communication Center was constructed across the East Beltline Road.  It is connected to west campus by the Calvin Crossing bridge. The building's upper level houses department and faculty offices for both the political science and communications arts and sciences departments.  Additionally, there is a suite of audiology and speech pathology classrooms and facilities including a working clinic.  The lower level of the building features media production and consumption facilities such as the Bytwerk Video Theatre, an audio studio, [[sound stage]], control room, and editing suites for audio and video production.  The ground floor features classrooms, a public atrium, and a snack shop.\n\n===Hekman Library===\n\nBeginning in 1917 with 3,500 volumes, Calvin's \"library room\" eventually became the modern Hekman Library now boasting over one million volumes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Library Statistics|url=https://library.calvin.edu/about/statistics|work=Hekman Library|publisher=Calvin University|accessdate=20 November 2019}}</ref> The collection's emphasis is on works in the traditional liberal arts disciplines. The library's strongest collections are in [[Theology]], [[Religion]], [[American literature]], [[British literature]], and [[Philosophy]].\n\nIn terms of books, serial backfiles, and other paper materials held, Hekman Library is currently the largest private academic library in the state.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hekman Library|url=http://www.wolframalpha.com/input/?i=biggest+libraries+in+michigan|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe H. Henry Meeter Center for Calvin Studies is located in the Hekman Library.  The center specializes in John Calvin and Calvinism.  With many rare items, books, manuscripts, articles and literature, the Meeter Center is the largest collection of Calvin materials in North America.<ref>{{cite web|title=Meeter Center|url=http://www.calvin.edu/meeter/about/|publisher=Calvin University|accessdate=20 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Athletic facilities==\nThe Spoelhof Fieldhouse Complex is home to the combined health, physical education, recreation, dance and sport department.  In Spring 2007, the college began a $50 million construction project to renovate and expand the Calvin Fieldhouse.  The fieldhouse reopened in Spring 2009 as the Spoelhof Fieldhouse Complex. The {{convert|362000|sqft|m2}} facility includes a new 5,000 seat arena ([[Van Noord Arena]]) which is currently the largest arena in a Division III school, an Olympic-regulation swimming pool (Venema Aquatic Center) which seats about 550, a tennis and track center (Huizenga Tennis and Track Center) containing 4 tennis courts and a 200-meter track, {{convert|14000|sqft|m2}} of weight training rooms and a custom made rock climbing wall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://calvin.edu/athletics/facilities/|title=Athletic Facilities|publisher=calvin.edu|accessdate=2019-04-05}}</ref> The Hoogenboom Health and Recreation Center contains the original renovated gym that is now used for basketball, volleyball, PE classes, intramurals, and many concerts.  The Hoogenboom Center also has two dance studios as well as racquetball courts and exercise science laboratories.\n\n===Chapel===\n[[File:Calvin Chapel.jpg|thumb|left|Calvin University Chapel]]\n\nThough always part of the master plan, the Chapel was not built until the late 1980s.  The chapel holds daily services in a protected time slot to ensure that all students and faculty members are able to attend the 20 minute worship services if they so choose. Chapel services follow a weekly rhythm and each day of the week has a different theme (Believe, Behold, Belong, Be Still, and Be Loud).<ref>{{cite web|title=Chapel|url=http://www.calvin.edu/faith/worship/chapel.html|work=Calvin University|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nDesigned by GMB Architects, the chapel sits at the highest point of the academic circle and its spire rises above all of the academic buildings.  Shaped as an octagon, with seating in the round, the Chapel offers exceptional acoustics for both instrumental and vocal music, in addition to the spoken word.  The Chapel also features a large organ built by [[Dobson Pipe Organ Builders]].  The three manual instrument features mechanical key action with a detached console.  The facade pipes, made of 75% burnished tin, conceal some 2,500 pipes.  In addition to the sanctuary, the Chapel has small prayer rooms, meeting spaces, a kitchen, theatre storage and rehearsal spaces.\n\nA tunnel system connecting to the Spoelhof Center creates an outdoor plaza at ground level and the multi-use Lab Theatre below.  The Lab Theatre is a blackbox theatre built in 1988 as a part of the chapel building project.<ref>{{cite web|title=Theater Locations: Behind the Scenes|url=http://www.calvin.edu/academic/cas/ctc/theaters/more-info.html|work=Calvin Theatre Company|publisher=Calvin University|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Bunker Interpretive Center===\nThe Bunker Interpretive Center is located in Calvin's nature preserve and serves as the home base for formal programs and an educational resource for the approximately 5,000 casual visitors that the Calvin University Ecosystem Preserve & Native Gardens receives annually.  The Bunker Interpretive Center is Gold [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] certified.<ref>{{cite web|title=Calvin College Bunker Interpretive Center|url=http://www.usgbc.org/projects/calvin-college-bunker-interpretive-cente|work=U.S. Green Building Council|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n\n===Residence life===\n\nCalvin has seven residence halls on campus which house the majority of the [[freshman]] and [[Sophomore year|sophomore]] classes, as the college has a policy that forces most first and second year students to live on campus. First and second year students may live off-campus if they lodge with their parents, it has been more than two years since their high school graduation date, or if they qualify for a rare exception.\n\nOne of the most notable events put on by residence life is \"Chaos Day\", during which the residents of each of the halls have their own theme, decorate their dorm, and dress in costumes to compete in a number of relay races and similar games.<ref>{{cite news|last=Struyk|first=Ryan|title=Underclassmen, dorm leadership rally for Chaos Day|url=http://www.calvin.edu/chimes/2012/09/06/underclassmen-dorm-leadership-rally-for-chaos-day/|accessdate=26 August 2013|newspaper=Chimes|date=7 September 2012}}</ref> The dorm building Schultze-Eldersveld has traditionally dominated the Chaos Day competition and has the most victories of any hall.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Buitenhuis|first1=Ericka|title=45 Years of Chaos Day: The Making of Calvin\u2019s Coveted Competition|url=http://www.calvin.edu/chimes/2014/09/13/45-years-of-chaos-day-the-making-of-calvins-coveted-competition/|website=Chimes|accessdate=31 December 2016|date=12 September 2014}}</ref> Floor Serenades, when one floor goes around campus singing songs to other floors,<ref>{{cite web|last=Graff|first=Allison R.|title=After-hours at Calvin|url=http://www.calvin.edu/verge/2012/fall/after-hours-at-calvin|work=Verge|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref> and Floor Dates, when two or more floors plan an activity together in order to meet new people, are common occurrences on campus.\n\n===Student Activities Office and The Calvin Concert Series===\n\nThe Student Activities Office at Calvin plans and hosts many films, concerts, and lectures aimed to foster cultural engagement and discernment in a Christian context.  The Student Activities Office shows a wide variety of popular and lesser-known films throughout the year.  Admission to these films, hosted in the Covenant Fine Arts Center, is $1.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://www.calvin.edu/sao/about-us.html|work=Student Activities Office|publisher=Calvin University|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ben Harper at Calvin College.jpg|thumb|[[Ben Harper and the Innocent Criminals]] live at Calvin College, 2000|345x345px]]\n\nCalvin is also notable for its extensive concert series. Before each concert, Calvin hosts a question and answer session with students and the artist. These sessions are meant to give artists a way to converse with students about their music and art. Calvin has hosted a variety of acts including:<ref>{{cite web|title=Calendar|url=http://www.calvin.edu/sao/calendar/|work=Student Activities Office|publisher=Calvin University|access-date=30 December 2016|date=September 2016}}</ref> Fun., Switchfoot, Death Cab for Cutie, Sufjan Stevens, MuteMath, Gungor, MGMT, the Soil & the Sun, Twin Forks, Ingrid Michaelson, Home Free, Regina Spektor, Over the Rhine, Anberlin, Jon Foreman, Peter Rollins and David Bazan, Kishi Bashi, All Sons & Daughters, NEEDTOBREATHE, Shad, Miracles of Modern Science, Diego Garcia, San Fermin, The Brilliance, Delorean, Pop Scholars, Okkervil River, The Head and The Heart, The National, Julianna Barwick, Lone Bellow, The Milk Carton Kids, Lily & Madeleine, Lecrae. The January Series also offers a wide selection of authors, singers, and musicians.\n\nBecause of its extensive and varied concert series, the Student Activities Office has faced controversy over the years.  In September 2010, the college canceled a concert by Canadian indie rock band, [[The New Pornographers]]. According to an official statement released by Calvin, the concert was cancelled after several complaints were made due to the band's name referring to pornography.<ref>{{cite news|title=Calvin College CANCELS New Pornographers Concert Over Band's Name|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/09/15/calvin-college-cancels-ne_n_717494.html|accessdate=26 August 2013|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=15 September 2010}}</ref> [[Fun (band)|Fun.]]'s advocacy of changed marriage laws when Calvin hosted them in 2012 was also met with significant controversy.<ref name=\"Fun. Concert Controversy\">{{cite web|last=Struyk|first=Ryan|title=Role of gay marriage advocacy at Fun. concert raises concerns|url=http://www.calvin.edu/chimes/2012/10/31/role-of-gay-marriage-advocacy-at-fun-concert-raises-concerns/|accessdate=July 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Safety===\n\nCampus security and parking policy enforcement services are provided Calvin University's Campus Safety Department. Some Calvin University campus safety officers have been armed with firearms since 2008,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.campussafetymagazine.com/news/calvin-college-officers-to-carry-firearms/|title=Calvin College Officers to Carry Firearms|date=2008-04-16|website=Campus Safety Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref> a decision that the Campus Safety Department director William Corner describes as a response to concerns that the College was not adequately prepared to respond to a similar event following the 2007 Virginia Tech campus shooting.<ref name=\"calvinchimes.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://calvinchimes.org/2016/11/05/calvin-a-model-for-armed-campus-safety-officers-at-christian-colleges/|title=Calvin a model for armed campus safety officers at Christian colleges|last=Hughey|first=Maddie|date=November 5, 2016|website=Calvin College Chimes|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref> Initially, only Campus Safety supervisors who were former law enforcement and fully licensed to carry firearms on a school campus were permitted to carry firearms on Calvin's campus. At that time, all campus safety supervisors were issued collapsible batons, chemical spray and handcuffs as standard policy, even if they were not armed with a firearm.\n\nAt the time and until 2017, non-supervisory Campus Safety officers were student employees who performed their duties unarmed. In 2017, the Campus Safety Department made the decision to discontinue hiring students for non-supervisory campus safety officer roles, electing instead to hire former law enforcement officers who were licensed to carry firearms on campus. The Department continued to employ students employees as dispatchers, building security officers and customer service staff. The Campus Safety Department director, William Corner, stated that student officers were not fully qualified for the risk level of some of the incidents they were responding too. \u201cWe were putting the students in positions that, honestly, I was not comfortable with for their safety and their level of experience.\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://calvinchimes.org/2017/09/29/campus-safety-increases-staff-student-hires/|title=Campus safety increases staff, hires fewer students|last=Butler|first=Hannah|date=September 29, 2017|website=Calvin College Chimes|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, full-time, non-student Calvin College campus safety personnel began wearing body cameras while on duty. Officers are required to turn on the cameras in specific circumstances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://calvinchimes.org/2014/09/25/campus-safety-recordings-hold-both-sides-accountable/|title=Campus Safety recordings hold both sides accountable|last=Bullis|first=Jenny|date=September 25, 2014|website=Calvin College Chimes|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Calvin College was described as being a model for the arming of campus security staff at other smaller college institution in the United States.<ref name=\"calvinchimes.org\"/>\n\nA Calvin College campus safety supervisor was criminally charged with \"reckless use of a firearm\" after a November 2016 on-duty incident.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlive.com/news/grand-rapids/2017/02/calvin_campus_safety_patrol_su.html|title=Calvin campus safety patrol supervisor charged over gun incident with pedestrian|last=Tunison|first=John|date=February 16, 2017|website=mlive.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref> The armed supervisor, Lee Swafford allegedly did not fire his duty firearm in the incident that resulted in his arrest, but after a routine review of body camera footage by the Campus Safety Department director William Corner, the decision was made to place Swafford on administrative leave pending the outcome of an internal investigation. Swafford was fired by Calvin College on December 6, 2016 after an internal investigation that led to all evidence being forwarded to the Grand Rapids Police Department and then charged by Kent County persecutors in February 2017. Swafford turned himself in to police after a warrant was issued for his arrest and was then released on bail.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://calvinchimes.org/2017/02/15/campus-safety-officer-charged/|title=Former campus safety officer charged with misdemeanor|last=Hughey|first=Maddie|date=February 16, 2017|website=Calvin College Chimes|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref> In an open letter to college students, faculty, staff and visitors, College president Michael Le Roy described the officer's actions as \"deeply disappointing to me.\" He also stated that the incident had involved a campus visitor, not a student or staff member.<ref>https://calvin.edu/dotAsset/0b0c3205-a868-4753-884f-50c11e586217.pdf</ref>\n\nCalvin University implemented a \"one button\" campus lockdown system in 2017. The new [[UTC Climate, Controls & Security|Lenel]] system can lockdown every exterior door on the college campus with the push of a single button. The college has also offered active shooting training to some staff and students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://calvinchimes.org/2017/10/13/calvin-prepared-for-active-shooter/|title=Calvin prepared for active shooter|last=Ford|first=Peter|date=October 13, 2017|website=Calvin College Chimes|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n<!-- U.S. rankings -->\n| Forbes        = 266\n<!-- Regional -->\n| USNWR_REG     = 3\n}}\n\nCalvin University has approximately 3,570 students, 53.6% female and 46.4% male.<ref name=day10report /> The average class size is 24, and there is a 13:1 student/faculty ratio.<ref name=classsizeandfacultystudentratio>{{cite web|title=Key Facts|url=https://calvin.edu/about/key-facts/|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref> Michigan students comprise 55% of the student body and 12% of the students are from other countries.<ref name=day10report /> The college has an 84.6% retention rate from first to second year and a six-year graduation rate of 75.7%.<ref name=day10report /> 224 full-time faculty teach at the college and 90.6% have the terminal degree in their field.<ref name=day10report />\n\nThe middle 50% of incoming first year students at the college have a [[GPA]] (4.0 scale) between 3.45 and 3.99, an [[ACT (examination)|ACT]] composite score between 23 and 30, and a [[SAT]] Critical Reading and Math score between 1060 and 1315.<ref name=\"financialaid\">{{cite web|title=Key Facts|url=https://calvin.edu/about/key-facts/#student-profile|website=Calvin University|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nTuition is currently $33,100, room and board is $9,990, and yearly fees are about $235. Approximately 99% of students receive some sort of financial aid.<ref name=\"financialaid\"/>\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Alumni===\n{{main category|Calvin University alumni}}\n*[[Dave Agema]], 1971, Republican National Committeeman\n*[[Jon Vander Ark]], president of [[Republic Services]]\n*[[William Brashler]], author of ''The Bingo Long Traveling All-Stars and Motor Kings''<ref>https://archives.calvin.edu/?p=collections/findingaid&id=21&q=&rootcontentid=9146</ref>\n*[[Meindert DeJong]], a Dutch-born American writer of children's books who won the Hans Christian Andersen Award.\n*[[Betsy DeVos]], former chair of the Republican party in Michigan and current Secretary of Education<ref>{{cite web|last1=Westervelt|first1=Ed|title=Trump Chooses Betsy DeVos For Education Secretary|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/ed/2016/11/23/499642077/trump-chooses-betsy-devos-for-education-secretary|website=nprEd|accessdate=31 December 2016|date=23 November 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Keith DeRose]], Allison Foundation Professor of Philosophy at Yale University\n*[[Richard DeVos]], founder of Amway and Orlando Magic CEO\n*[[William K. Frankena]] 1930, moral philosopher, Chairman UofM philosophy department, Distinguished Alumnus\n*[[Hans Halvorson]], Stuart Professor of Philosophy at Princeton University\n*[[Wayne Huizenga]], businessman (attended)\n*[[Bill Huizenga]], U.S. Congressman\n*[[Rose Ibiama]] 2005, member of Academy Award-winning DreamWorks Animation teams<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://calvin.edu/publication/spark/2015/03/01/dressing-up-anna-and-elsa?dotcmsredir=1|title=Dressing up Anna and Elsa|last=|first=|date=1 March 2015|website=Spark|access-date=9 July 2017}}</ref>\n*[[M.I Abaga]], Nigerian Musician\n*[[Peter Kreeft]], Professor of Philosophy and Theology at Boston College\n*[[Marc Evan Jackson]] 1992, actor and comedian\n*[[Todd Martinez]] 1989, theoretical chemist and professor\n*[[Jeannine Oppewall]] 1968, Academy Award-nominated production designer\n*[[Alvin Plantinga]], prominent (theistic) contemporary philosopher of religion\n*[[Patricia Rozema]] 1981, filmmaker\n*[[Paul Schrader]] 1968, Academy Award-nominated screenwriter and filmmaker\n*[[Carl Strikwerda]], President of [[Elizabethtown College]]\n*[[Jay Van Andel]] Businessman, co-founder of Amway\n*[[John Van Engen]] 1969, Professor of History and [[Haskins Medal]] winner\n*[[John Witte Jr.]] 1982, [[Robert W. Woodruff Professor]] at [[Emory University School of Law]]\n\n===Faculty===\n*[[Lionel Basney]], Professor of English, poet, author, critic\n*[[Johannes Broene]], 1908-1925 teaching primarily in Philosophy and Education but also classes in History, Civics, Government, Chemistry, and Psychology\n*[[Brian Diemer]], 1986\u2013Present, Head Cross Country Coach\n*[[Vern Ehlers]], 1966\u20131982, Professor of Physics, served as U.S. Representative from Grand Rapids\n*[[John E. Hare]], 1989\u20132003, Professor of Philosophy\n*[[Paul B. Henry]], 1970\u20131978, Professor of Political Science\n*[[William Harry Jellema]], 1920\u20131936, 1948-1963 founder of Calvin's Philosophy Department\n*[[George Marsden]], 1965\u20131986, 2010\u2013present, Professor of History\n*[[Richard Mouw]], 1968\u20131985, Professor of Philosophy\n*[[Alvin Plantinga]], 1963\u20131981, Professor of Philosophy\n*[[H. Evan Runner]], 1951\u20131981, Professor of Philosophy\n*[[Gary D. Schmidt|Gary Schmidt]], 1986\u2013present, Professor of English, awarded two [[Newbery Medal|Newbery Honor]] awards for his young-adult fiction\n*[[James K.A. Smith]], 2002\u2013present, Professor of Philosophy\n*[[William Spoelhof]], 1946\u20131951, Professor of History and Political Science\n*[[Ralph Stob]], 1915\u20131964, Professor of Classics\n*[[Howard J. Van Till]], Emeritus Professor of Physics\n*[[Nicholas Wolterstorff]], 1959\u20131989, Professor of Philosophy\n\n==Athletics==\n{{Main|Calvin Knights}}\nCalvin University fields ten men's and ten women's intercollegiate teams and several club sports, known as the [[Calvin Knights]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sports & Recreation|url=http://www.calvin.edu/community/sports.html|work=Calvin University|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nStudents at Calvin publish a weekly student newspaper, ''Chimes'',<ref>{{cite web|title=TCalvin Chimes|url=https://calvin.edu/offices-services/student-organizations/calvin-chimes|publisher=Calvin University|accessdate=20 November 2019}}</ref>  and a monthly journal of arts and letters commentary, ''Dialogue''. A yearbook, ''Prism'', is also published for each school year. Student filmmakers have also made many short films and videos, like the popular [http://vimeo.com/11201881 Lipdub at Calvin College] and the super-low-budget adaptation of Homer's ''[[Iliad]]'', ''Meynin'', both in 2010.\n\nThe school distributes ''Knightfile'', a seasonal magazine on sports at the college,<ref>{{cite web|title=Knightfile|url=http://www.calvin.edu/publications/knight/|publisher=Calvin College|accessdate=20 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120127141026/http://www.calvin.edu/publications/knight/|archive-date=27 January 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>  ''Uncompressed'', a cultural discussion publication, and ''Spark'',<ref>{{cite web|title=The Calvin Spark|url=http://www.calvin.edu/spark/|publisher=Calvin University|accessdate=20 March 2012}}</ref>  a magazine for alumni and friends.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of presidents of Calvin University]]\n* [[Cornelius Van Til]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Calvin University (Michigan)}}\n* {{Official website}}\n{{Grand Rapids, Michigan}}\n{{Colleges and universities in Michigan}}\n{{CCCU}}\n{{Michigan Intercollegiate Athletic Association navbox}}\n{{Portal bar|Calvinism|Michigan|Education}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Calvin University| ]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1876]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges affiliated with the Christian Reformed Church]]\n[[Category:Education in Grand Rapids, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Kent County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Grand Rapids, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Evangelicalism in Michigan]]\n[[Category:1876 establishments in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Council for Christian Colleges and Universities]]\n", "name_user": "Nihiltres", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Simplified hatnote syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calvin_University"}
{"title_page": "Don't Wanna Fall in Love", "text_new": "{{For|the Green Day song|Shenanigans (album)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Don't Wanna Fall in Love\n| cover      = Don't Wanna Fall in Love.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Jane Child]]\n| album      = [[Jane Child (album)|Jane Child]]\n| B-side     = World Lullabye\n| released   =\n* February 10, 1990 {{small|(US)}}\n* April 11, 1990 {{small|(UK)}}\n| format     = [[CD single|CD]]\n| recorded   = 1988\u20131989\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[synth-pop]]\n| length     = 4:07\n| label      = [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n| writer     = [[Jane Child]]\n| producer   = [[Jane Child]]\n| prev_title = [[Welcome to the Real World (Jane Child Song)|Welcome to the Real World]]\n| prev_year  = 1990\n| next_title = Welcome to the Real World (reissue)\n| next_year  = 1990\n}}\n\n\"'''Don't Wanna Fall in Love'''\" is a [[1990 in music|1990]] hit song for [[Toronto]]-born singer [[Jane Child]]. Released as the second single from her [[Jane Child (album)|self-titled debut album]], the single went to number two for three consecutive weeks on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] from April 14 to April 28, 1990.<ref>[http://www.stylusmagazine.com/feature.php?ID=1699 Stylus Magazine] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213165802/http://www.stylusmagazine.com/feature.php?ID=1699 |date=February 13, 2008 }}</ref> It was kept out of the top spot by \"[[I'll Be Your Everything (Tommy Page song)|I'll Be Your Everything]]\" by [[Tommy Page]] and [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]]'s recording of \"'[[Nothing Compares 2 U]]\". In addition, a \"[[new jack swing]]\" remix of the song was produced by [[Teddy Riley]] and reached number six on the R&B chart,<ref>{{cite book |title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942-2004|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=117}}</ref> and number eleven on the dance chart.<ref>{{cite book |title= Hot Dance/Disco: 1974-2003|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=57}}</ref> [[Shep Pettibone]] also remixed the single, but was only released to DJs. When released around Europe, it also became successful albeit more modestly. In the UK, the single stalled at number 22 after Child refused to appear on the popular British TV program ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' while the single was climbing the charts, considering the program to be a \"sellout\".\n\nIn April 1990, the single was certified gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]].<ref>[http://riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=Jane%20Child&format=SINGLE&startYear=1958&endYear=2010&sort=Artist&perPage=25 RIAA Gold & Platinum Searchable Database - Jane Child Singles]{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. RIAA.com. Retrieved 2010-02-13.</ref>\n\nIt is Child's best known song and only top 40 hit, making her a [[one-hit wonder]] in the public eye.\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video shot in B&W and in color, was filmed in [[New York City]] by cinematographer Derek M. Allen at the request of Child, due to having written the song while living there. In it, Child is seen walking through downtown Manhattan at night, alternating with scenes of the artist at work, laying down tracks on a [[Fairlight CMI|Fairlight]] and mixing the results on a [[Multitrack recording|multitrack board]].\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n!Chart (1990\u20131991) \n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n|Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite book|last=Ryan|first=Gavin|title=Australia's Music Charts 1988\u20132010|year=2011|publisher=Moonlight Publishing|location=Mt. Martha, VIC, Australia}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|97\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|4|chartid=9138|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadaadultcontemporary|3|chartid=7982|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadadance|7|chartid=9048|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|26|song=Don't Wanna Fall in Love|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|52|artist=Jane Child|song=Don't Wanna Fall in Love}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|12|artist=Jane Child|song=Don't Wanna Fall in Love}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|16|artist=Jane Child|song=Don't Wanna Fall in Love}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|22|date=19900609|artist=Jane Child|song=Don't Wanna Fall in Love|accessdate=26 February 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|2|artist=Jane Child|accessdate=26 February 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboarddanceelectronic|11|artist=Jane Child|accessdate=26 February 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrandbhiphop|6|artist=Jane Child|accessdate=26 February 2018}}\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1990)\n!Position\n|-\n|Canada Top Singles (''RPM'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.9139&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.9139.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.9139|title=Top 100 Hit Tracks of 1990|work=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|49\n|-\n|Canada Adult Contemporary (''RPM'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.9175&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.9175.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.9175|title=Top 100 Adult Contemporary Tracks of 1990|work=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|42\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://longboredsurfer.com/charts.php?year=1990 |title=Billboard Top 100 - 1990 |accessdate=2009-09-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mpyyjb8t?url=http://longboredsurfer.com/charts.php?year=1990 |archivedate=2010-01-17 }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|29\n|-\n|US ''Cash Box''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://50.6.195.142/archives/90s_files/1990YESP.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-11-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131229035257/http://50.6.195.142/archives/90s_files/1990YESP.html |archivedate=2013-12-29 }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|27\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Other versions==\nThe song was covered in 2008 by [[Kimberly Wyatt]] of [[The Pussycat Dolls]], appearing on the bonus disc for their album ''[[Doll Domination]]''.\n\nIn 2010 Ingrid Kjosavik covered the song on her album ''Sweet Freedom.''\n\nIt was also sampled by producer [[M-Phazes]] under his Camden Arc side project, and was used for the 2014 song \"Don't Wanna Fall in Love\" by rapper [[Kyle (musician)|Kyle]].\n\n== In popular culture ==\nThe song is featured in ''[[Grand Theft Auto V]]'', it is played on [[Non-Stop Pop FM]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|jane-child|dont-wanna-fall-in-love}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n[[Category:1990 singles]]\n[[Category:Jane Child songs]]\n[[Category:Warner Records singles]]\n[[Category:1989 songs]]\n[[Category:New jack swing songs]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Dance Recording of the Year recordings]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the Green Day song|Shenanigans (album)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Don't Wanna Fall in Love\n| cover      = Don't Wanna Fall in Love.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Jane Child]]\n| album      = [[Jane Child (album)|Jane Child]]\n| B-side     = World Lullabye\n| released   =\n* February 10, 1990 {{small|(US)}}\n* April 11, 1990 {{small|(UK)}}\n| format     = [[CD single|CD]]\n| recorded   = 1988\u20131989\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[synth-pop]]\n| length     = 4:07\n| label      = [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n| writer     = [[Jane Child]]\n| producer   = [[Jane Child]]\n| prev_title = [[Welcome to the Real World (Jane Child Song)|Welcome to the Real World]]\n| prev_year  = 1990\n| next_title = Welcome to the Real World (reissue)\n| next_year  = 1990\n}}\n\n\"'''Don't Wanna Fall in Love'''\" is a [[1990 in music|1990]] hit song for [[Toronto]]-born singer [[Jane Child]]. Released as the second single from her [[Jane Child (album)|self-titled debut album]], the single went to number two for three consecutive weeks on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] from April 14 to April 28, 1990.<ref>[http://www.stylusmagazine.com/feature.php?ID=1699 Stylus Magazine] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213165802/http://www.stylusmagazine.com/feature.php?ID=1699 |date=February 13, 2008 }}</ref> It was kept out of the top spot by \"[[I'll Be Your Everything (Tommy Page song)|I'll Be Your Everything]]\" by [[Tommy Page]] and [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]]'s recording of \"'[[Nothing Compares 2 U]]\". In addition, a \"[[new jack swing]]\" remix of the song was produced by [[Teddy Riley]] and reached number six on the R&B chart,<ref>{{cite book |title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942-2004|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=117}}</ref> and number eleven on the dance chart.<ref>{{cite book |title= Hot Dance/Disco: 1974-2003|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=57}}</ref> [[Shep Pettibone]] also remixed the single, but was only released to DJ's. When released around Europe, it also became successful albeit more modestly. In the UK, the single stalled at number 22 after Child refused to appear on the popular British TV program ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' while the single was climbing the charts, considering the program to be a \"sellout\".\n\nIn April 1990, the single was certified gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]].<ref>[http://riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=Jane%20Child&format=SINGLE&startYear=1958&endYear=2010&sort=Artist&perPage=25 RIAA Gold & Platinum Searchable Database - Jane Child Singles]{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. RIAA.com. Retrieved 2010-02-13.</ref>\n\nIt is Child's best known song and only top 40 hit, making her a [[one-hit wonder]] in the public eye.\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video shot in B&W and in color, was filmed in [[New York City]] by cinematographer Derek M. Allen at the request of Child, due to having written the song while living there. In it, Child is seen walking through downtown Manhattan at night, alternating with scenes of the artist at work, laying down tracks on a [[Fairlight CMI|Fairlight]] and mixing the results on a [[Multitrack recording|multitrack board]].\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n!Chart (1990\u20131991) \n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n|Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite book|last=Ryan|first=Gavin|title=Australia's Music Charts 1988\u20132010|year=2011|publisher=Moonlight Publishing|location=Mt. Martha, VIC, Australia}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|97\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|4|chartid=9138|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadaadultcontemporary|3|chartid=7982|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadadance|7|chartid=9048|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|26|song=Don't Wanna Fall in Love|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|52|artist=Jane Child|song=Don't Wanna Fall in Love}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|12|artist=Jane Child|song=Don't Wanna Fall in Love}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|16|artist=Jane Child|song=Don't Wanna Fall in Love}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|22|date=19900609|artist=Jane Child|son